<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HitlerParties 2ndLd-Writethru a0797 10-12 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hitler Parties, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0797 ,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede GRAND FORKS, N.D.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Casino Hotel Owner Plans To Donate Nazi Collection</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE that Engelstad plans to donate
Nazi material to Holocaust museum. Picks up 4th graf pvs, ``I have
...' ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hotel owner criticized for throwing Adolf
Hitler birthday parties for his employees said Wednesday he plans
to donate his collection of Nazi material to a planned Holocaust
museum in Washington.
   Ralph Engelstad, 58, who owns the Imperial Palace hotel and
casino, said he began discussions Wednesday with officials of the
U.S. Holocaust Memorial Council toward donating the Nazi items.
   ``We have offered it. They have expressed interest in having
it,'' Engelstad said.
   Engelstad, who earlier painted over a Nazi wall mural and
scrapped plans to display the Nazi items at his car museum, said he
hoped the planned donation to the Holocaust museum would end the
flap over his activities.
   ``As I said earlier, I now feel I have done what can be done,''
Engelstad said, reading from a statement. ``I have apologized for
what cannot be undone.''
   Engelstad said he hoped to donate the various Nazi artifacts to
a Holocaust museum that is being planned by the council in
Washington. But he said he would keep the various cars he has
bought that are related to the Nazi regime.
   In a letter to the Jewish Federation of Las Vegas on Tuesday,
Engelstad said he would sell the collection of Nazi-era cars,
motorcycles, posters and other items and turn the room into a
warehouse.
   ``I have not been successful to date in convincing you that my
apology for my insensitivity to Jewish concerns was heartfelt and
sincere,'' Engelstad wrote.
   ``In retrospect, I realize that what was missing in my apology
was an acknowledgement of the specific hurt and pain felt by the
Jewish community over this issue,'' he said.
   Engelstad, a former goaltender on the University of North
Dakota's hockey team, announced plans earlier this year to set up a
$5 million endowment to benefit the university's hockey program.
   The school's Winter Sports Center was subsequently renamed Ralph
Engelstad Arena.
   Officials said the university doesn't plan to reject Engelstad's
money and won't change the name of the hockey venue. But school
President Thomas Clifford said school officials would watch the
controversy for any new developments, and ``we're keeping our
options open.''
   Engelstad, a native of Thief River Falls, Minn., has apologized
for the two Hitler parties, which he held in 1986 and earlier this
year.
   ``In retrospect, they were not only stupid but insensitive, but
at the time they were merely excuses for parties,'' Engelstad said,
adding that he threw parties often for his employees.
   Engelstad's collection included a portrait of Hitler, signed
``To Ralphie from Adolf 1938,'' and a bumper sticker inscribed
``Hitler Was Right.''
   Engelstad has said the portrait was sent to him by a Phoenix
broker as a joke after he purchased a number of German vehicles.
Engelstad did not authorize the bumper stickers and found them
offensive, he said.
</TEXT>
