<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Newspage-NLPlayoff     10-12 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newspage-NL Playoff,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dodgers Defeat Mets, Will Meet Oakland in World Series</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dodgers won the National League pennant
Wednesday night by beating the favored New York Mets 6-0 in the
seventh game of a playoff.
   Los Angeles will be host of Game 1 of the 85th major league
baseball World Series on Saturday against Oakland. It is a rematch
of the 1974 Series won by the Athletics in five games.
   Orel Hershiser, who pitched a five-hitter for the Dodgers,
finished the season with a record 59 consecutive scoreless innings.
We was credited for the win, after starting playoff Games 1 and 3
without getting a decision but getting a save for Game 4.
   The pennant is the Dodgers' ninth championship since moving to
Los Angeles in 1958 from Brooklyn, and their first since 1981, when
they went on to beat the New York Yankees in the World Series.
   The Dodgers scored first in six of the seven games against the
Mets and made things easy for Hershiser by scoring a run in the
first inning Wednesday off losing pitcher Ron Darling. Los Angeles
then chased him with five runs in the second as New York made three
sloppy fielding plays.
   Hershiser had five strikeouts, two walks and two hit batsmen in
pitching the third shutout in a series-deciding game in playoff
history. Catfish Hunter of Oakland beat Baltimore 3-0 in the final
game of the 1973 AL playoff and Danny Cox of St. Louis shut out San
Francisco 6-0 last year in the NL playoff.
</TEXT>
