<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 0027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FraternitySuspended     10-12 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fraternity Suspended,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fraternity Suspended Amid Rape Charge; Sorority in Maine Also in
Hot Water</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Mississippi suspended the
Sigma Alpha Epsilon fraternity Tuesday after an ``extended period
of disruptive behavior'' that included a member being charged with
raping a sorority pledge.
   And in Orono, Maine, the University of Maine withdrew
recognition of a sorority after a hazing inciden in which pledges
allegedly were branded with a heated metal stamp.
   The earliest the Mississippi fraternity will be eligible to
return to campus is Jan. 1, said Gordon Beasley, university vice
chancellor for student affairs.
   Last month, the university banned all on-campus
fraternity-sorority parties when a freshman Chi Omega Sorority
pledge said she was raped after attending a mixer held by the
fraternity and the sorority.
   That party was held off-campus because the fraternity was
already on social probation because of a rush infraction and was
prohibited from having on-campus parties.
   Stover Smith, 18, of Metairie, La., was freed late last month on
$50,000 bond after being arrested on rape charges, said Oxford
Police Chief Billy White. The woman told officers that she left the
party and was driven to a field, then beaten and raped, White said.
   University officials said the rape charge was not the only
reason for the suspension of the fraternity, but it was a
contributing factor. The unversity began an investigation into the
fraternity's activities after the incident.
   The suspension means removal of all fraternity members from the
campus chapter and the placing of the chapter in the hands of an
alumni committee, Beasley said.
   The identities of the victims in the Sept. 25 incident in Maine,
said to have occurred in a Bangor cemetery, were not disclosed.
Officials said a preliminary investigation found that two pledges
had suffered burns.
   An associate dean, William Lucy, said the burns had been
characterized as minor.
   Hazing is prohibited by both state law and school policy,
university officials said.
</TEXT>
