<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 0013EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Election Bjt   10-12 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Election, Bjt,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Fights For Crucial Sephardi Vote In Likud Strongholds</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMLE, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cheering children greeted Moroccan-born
David Levy, the No. 2 man in the right-wing Likud bloc, during a
campaign stop in this town where two-thirds of the residents are
Jews of North African origin.
   When Shimon Peres, head of the left-of-center Labor Party,
campaigned in Ramle's open-air market last week, he was jostled and
booed. Likud supporters shouted ``traitor'' and ``Peres go home.''
   The contrasting receptions underscore Labor's continuing
difficulties in winning the support of the Sephardim, Jews of
Middle Eastern and North African origin. They make up 55 percent of
the 2.1 million Israeli voters and will be crucial in determining
the outcome of the Nov. 1 elections.
   In 1984, 70 percent of the Sephardim voted for the Likud, and
this time, ``there is still a strong element of identification with
the Likud,'' said a pollster for the Labor-affiliated Decima
polling company, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   However, Labor pollsters said they expected a dip of about 5
percent in Sephardic support for Likud, providing an opening for
Labor to campaign aggressively among Sephardic voters.
   A key target group are young, financially successful Sephardim
born in Israel who make up about half of the 5 percent of the
voters wavering between Labor and Likud, said the Decima pollster.
   They might determine the election because polls show Labor and
Likud running neck-to-neck.
   Sephardic voting power first became evident in 1977 when Labor
was ousted from the government after 29 years because Sephardim
voted for the Likud in massive numbers.
   The Sephardic identification with Likud has its roots in the
1950s and 1960s when Labor, at the time dominated by Western-born
Ashkenazim, often was arrogant toward the North African newcomers.
   Today, most Sephardim still feel greater affinity toward Likud
than Labor, but after 11 years of the Likud government, some
supporters are becoming more critical.
   ``I will vote for the Likud again, but it's not what it used to
be in the times of (former Likud Prime Minister Menahem) Begin,''
said Yehuda Cohen, 36, a taxi driver in Ramle where 70 percent of
the votes traditionally go to Likud.
   ``Labor was in the government for 30 years, and became corrupt.
Now the same thing is happening to the Likud,'' he added.
   ``Likud can no longer say `the Sephardim belong to us,''' said
his colleague, Eli Zarfati, a former Likud voter who is now leaning
toward Labor.
   Political analyst Daniel Elazar warned that the Likud might be
overestimating its hold on Sephardic voters.
   ``The Likud is convinced they have the Sephardim in their back
pocket. I don't think they do,'' said Elazar, head of the Jerusalem
Center for Public Policy, a think tank.
   ``If the Likud had been better at governing and had not been
associated with inflation and the war in Lebanon, their position
with the Sephardim would have been unassailable,'' he added.
   Labor officials say they are making inroads, mainly because
Labor candidates for the 120-member Parliament includes 16
Sephardim.
   In addition, Peres, currently the foreign minister, is making
many campaign appearances in predominantly Sephardic areas.
   But Levy, who as deputy prime minister is the highest-ranking
Sephardi in the Cabinet, played down the importance of the ethnic
vote.
   ``Forty years have passed. Time has come to do away with the
labels of Sephardim and Ashkenazim and to relate to people as
Israeli citizens,'' Levy told The Associated Press.
   During a tour of Ramle on Tuesday, Levy was greeted by more than
100 school children, many of them chanting the party's slogan:
``Only Likud Can.''
   Likud spokeswoman Odelia Karmon denied Labor claims that
Sephardic support for the Likud was weakening, but said Likud
leaders are not targeting thos voters in particular. ``Labor has to
do that because of the past, but we have nothing to apologize
for,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
