<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0817 10-12 0742</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0817,0764</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Wrather, Troast and Adams; AMs separates moved as a0720
on Flowers and as a0826 on Wrather.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY62</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Wayland Flowers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wayland Flowers, a ventriloquist who brought
life to a cackling, off-color puppet named Madame, died Tuesday of
cancer. He was 48.
   Flowers created a cast of characters, but it was the craggy old
hussy Madame, manipulated with rods rather than strings, that
launched the popularity of the television and showroom act.
   Wayland & Madame's first big break came on ``The Andy Williams
Show'' and led to guest appearances on the reincarnated
``Laugh-In,'' ``Hollywood Squares'' and a four-year stint on
``Solid Gold.'' Their own syndicated situation comedy ``Madame's
Place'' was shown in 1982.
   Flowers also brought life to such characters as Crazy Marv, who
had terribly accurate observations on humanity, Jiffy from Harlem
with humor and song stylings, vaudevillian Mr. Mackelhoney and Baby
Smedley's high chair view of the world.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>B. Frank Polk</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. B. Frank Polk, who helped pioneer AIDS
research as a professor of epidemiology at The Johns Hopkins
University's School of Public Health, died Tuesday in Boston of a
brain tumor at age 46.
   Polk was a member of a committee that started the Hopkins
hospital AIDS inpatient unit in 1986. Three years earlier, he had
started a program called SHARE, for Study to Help AIDS Research
Efforts, which became one of four National Institutes of
Health-supported studies of the natural history of the incurable
disease.
   Polk had been conducting several studies, still in progress, on
heterosexual transmission of acquired immune deficiency syndrome
and on the risk of infection by the AIDS virus among recipients of
screened blood, prison inmates, intravenous drug abusers, mothers
and their unborn children.
   He worked with AIDS patients in the Hopkins hospital and
directed the AIDS outpatient clinic, where more than 700 patients
receive care.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Lois Wilson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lois Wilson, the founder of Al-Anon Family
Programs, died Wednesday in Mount Kisco, N.Y. She was 97.
   Mrs. Wilson was the widow of Alcoholics Anonymous co-founder
Bill Wilson.
   Al-Anon, established in 1951, provides support programs for
friends and family members of recovering alcoholics. The program,
based on the 12-point plan of Alcoholics Anonymous, has about
500,000 members.
   Alcoholics Anonymous was founded in Akron in 1935 by Wilson, a
New York stock broker, and Dr. Robert Smith of Akron. Their program
to start and keep alcoholics on the road to sobriety has an
estimated 1.5 million members.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Bonita Wrather</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bonita Granville Wrather, an
actress, businesswoman, philanthropist and widow of
oilman-entrepreneur Jack Wrather, died Tuesday of cancer at age 65.
   Mrs. Wrather starred in her first film, ``Westward Passage'' at
age 7. She earned an Academy Award nomination for her role as a
lying school girl in the 1936 movie ``These Three,' and by the time
she was 23 she had been in 50 films, including ``Cavalcade,'' ``Ah,
Wilderness,'' ``Now Voyager'' ``The Plough and the Stars,'' and
``Hitler's Children.'
   In 1946, Mrs. Wrather starred in ``The Guilty,'' and fell in
love with the movie's producer, Texas oilman Jack Wrather. They
married the next year.
   She appeared on television in the 1950s in such shows as ``The
U.S. Steel Hour,'' ``Playhouse 90,'' ``Climax,'' and ``Studio One.''
   Mrs. Wrather was active in several Los Angeles philanthropic
organizations. She was appointed by President Nixon in 1972 to
serve on the Board of Trustees of the John F. Kennedy Center, and
was appointed for another term in 1982 by President Reagan.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>George Troast</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HEMET, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George William Troast, 78, a Hollywood art
director whose 40-year career included 14 years with the ``Lassie''
show, died Monday.
   Troasts' credits included the ``My Three Sons'' television show,
the ``Sandburg's Lincoln'' miniseries and the 1977 movie, ``The
Magic of Lassie.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Joseph Adams</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph H. ``Joey'' Adams, an award-winning
former Philadelphia Daily News photographer, died Sunday. He was 59.
   Adams started as an apprentice at the old Philadelphia Bulletin,
working as the equivalent of a copy boy in the photo department.
During the Korean War, Adams sereved as an Army combat photographer
and won the Bronz Star.
   He worked for the Daily News from 1954 to 1973 and amassed some
25 major awards for his news and feature photos. He set a record in
1957 when he won four prizes in the PPPA contest.
</TEXT>
