<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 0101EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Panama-Cocaine     10-12 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Cocaine,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Witness Testifies He Posed As Soldier To Deal In Cocaine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who told police he had 8.5 kilograms
of cocaine in his car when they stopped him for a traffic violation
testified Tuesday he made $139,000 dealing drugs while posing as a
U.S. soldier in Panama.
   Jackie Lee Bigelow, dismissed from the Army in 1986, said he
made six trips to Panama in his old uniform between April 1987 and
last May. He testified he was paid $25,000 for each of five times
he flew back with duffle bags containing cocaine, which he then
took to apartments in New York City.
   He said he also was paid $13,000 for a cardboard box of cocaine
he mailed to a girlfriend and also got another $1,000 from a
contact in Panama.
   Bigelow's testimony came in the first day of the U.S. District
Court trial of four people accused in a smuggling ring that
included the alleged drug mailings.
   Bigelow, of Doerun, also was charged in the case but has pleaded
guilty.
   The case broke when Bigelow, 27, was stopped by police on May 28
for failing to have a driver's license. He told police he had 8.5
kilograms of cocaine in his car.
   On trial are Oscar Smith, Regina Smith and Julia Thom of New
York, and Gary King of Doerun. They are accused of smuggling up to
600 pounds of cocaine into the United States through various means.
   Defense lawyers have said that Bigelow has concocted his story
to win a lighter sentence for himself. But Bigelow testified that
King made two of the Panama trips with him, and that Smith was on
the receiving end of most of his visits to New York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
