<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Cambodia     10-12 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Cambodia,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Calls for Measures To Block Khmer Rouge in Cambodia</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: time of meeting indefinite</NOTE>
<HEAD>Laserphoto WX9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration is expressing strong
support for the efforts of former Cambodian leader Norodom Sihanouk
to achieve national reconciliation in his homeland and says
``effective safeguards'' must be imposed to prevent a return to
power by the Khmer Rouge.
   Sihanouk, who was meeting today with Secretary of State George
P. Shultz, said Tuesday after a visit with President Reagan he
agrees that leaders of the Khmer Rouge ``must go into exile, if
possible,'' as part of a post-settlement coalition government.
   The Khmer Rouge are believed to have killed between 1 million
and 2 million Cambodians during their 3{ years in power during the
late 1970s. They are one of three rebel groups fighting the
Vietnamese-backed government now in power in Phnom Penh.
   The Reagan administration is providing $5 million in non-lethal
assistance to the two anti-communist rebel groups and is consulting
with members of Congress about the possibility of an increase.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Reagan told
Sihanouk that he ``supported (Sihanouk's) efforts to establish a
reconciliation government in Cambodia.''
   ``He said our policy rests on two elements, a complete
Vietnamese withdrawal and no return to power of the Khmer Rouge,''
Fitzwater said.
   State Department deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said China,
which has been a major backer of the Khmer Rouge, recognizes that
``discredited'' leaders of that group, such as Pol Pot, cannot be
permitted to play a role in a future Cambodian government.
   But she said the administration could not confirm a New York
Times report that China has offered political asylum to individual
Khmer Rouge leaders.
   There have been intensified diplomatic efforts to shape events
in Cambodia as Vietnam has begun a drawdown of its troops in that
country, setting a 1990 deadline for a complete withdrawal.
   Sihanouk, who was ousted as head of state in 1970 and heads a
rebel faction active in Cambodia, met with Undersecretary of State
Michael Armacost after his visit to the White House.
   Aligning himself with the Reagan administration, Sihanouk told
reporters it is ``necessary to give the world some guarantee about
the Khmer Rouge in the future.''
   Mrs. Oakley said the discussion with Sihanouk focused on ways to
achieve a negotiated settlement that includes the complete
withdrawal of Vietnamese troops and effective safeguards against a
Khmer Rouge return to power.
   The Khmer Rouge is said to be the strongest of the three
factions and a major international effort is under way to ensure
that group does not play a dominant role in Cambodia's future
political evolution.
   Particularly active in this effort have been the six members of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) _ Thailand,
Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, the Philippines and Brunei.
   One of the measures being discussed to limit the Khmer Rouge
role is the establishment of an international peacekeeping force.
Other measures under discussion include the disarming of all
Cambodian factions and removing leading Khmer Rouge figures from
Cambodia.
   Mrs. Oakley gave a strong endorsement of Sihanouk, calling him a
``leading symbol of Cambodian nationalism for the past 40 years.''
   ``We believe that his role is central to a satisfactory
settlement in Cambodia and we welcome the opportunity of his visit
to express our strong support for him,'' she said.
</TEXT>
