<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TreasuryBills     10-12 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yields Mixed on Short-Term T-Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities were mixed in the latest auction.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.0 billion in three-month bills
Tuesday at an average discount rate of 7.32 percent, up from 7.23
percent last week. Another $7.0 billion was sold in six-month bills
at an average discount rate of 7.46 percent, the same as last week.
   The rates for three-month bills were the highest since May 13,
1985, when they sold for 7.69 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 7.56 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,815.00 and and 7.86 percent for six-month bills selling for
$9,622.90.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said the average yield
for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for making
changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, fell to 8.13 percent
last week after averaging 8.18 percent the week before.
</TEXT>
