<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 0133EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-JapanPlutonium     10-12 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Japan Plutonium,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plutonium Shipment Plans Questioned; Japan May Provide Armed
Escort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan is opting to ship deadly plutonium for
its nuclear reactors by sea rather than by air, prompting
complaints from some members of Congress that the United States
should have been consulted.
   U.S. and Japanese officials disclosed the shipping plans on
Tuesday, touching off the dispute.
   Two Democratic lawmakers said Congress was tricked out of its
right to a reasonable period to review changes in the new 30-year
U.S.-Japan nuclear cooperation agreement.
   The State Department denied the assertion, saying the new pact,
which went into effect last July, allowed certain changes with 15
days' notice to Congress.
   The change provides for a temporary alternative of sea shipment
until crash-proof air shipment casks are developed. State
Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley told reporters that Congress
was notified formally on Sept. 20.
   Japan has been purchasing spent uranium atomic fuel from the
United States and sending it to Europe for refining into plutonium
before it reaches Japan. The United States seeks to retain control
over usage because plutonium is highly radioactive and usable not
only for fueling power reactors but also for nuclear weapons.
   In authorizing ocean shipments to Japan, the latest arrangement
requires that armed escorts be provided against potential terrorist
seizure.
   It defines the escort ``as a coast guard or maritime safety
vessel or any other ship on government service that is authorized
and fully capable of protecting the transport ship and cargo and
deterring acts of sabotage,'' said Richard J. Stratford, deputy
assistant secretary of state for nuclear energy and technology.
   He said the Japanese were told they could request U.S. escorts
but that they would be supplied only if consistent with overall
U.S. security priorities. The Japanese then ``indicated they were
considering providing the escort themselves,'' he said.
   Recalling testimony a year ago that air was preferable to sea
shipment, Rep. Howard Wolpe, D-Mich., said the Reagan
administration ``is trying to sneak by a hurried Congress a very
dangerous change in policy. The administration is playing
hide-and-seek with disaster by not guaranteeing the adequate safety
of sea shipments to Japan.''
   He said the administration ``has signed off on a 30-year
approval for shipment of the most dangerous substance known to man
and left Congress only 15 days to respond.''
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, also complained, saying that in
addition to opening a threat of nuclear blackmail by terrorists,
sea shipment increases chances of contaminating drinking water with
radioactivity.
   Another State Department spokeswoman, Nancy Beck, quoted the
Defense Department as saying air shipment was preferable but that
sea shipment was acceptable under proper safeguards, that hijacking
a plutonium-carrying ship was a task for ``a major naval power,''
and that the Pentagon was satisfied with the safeguards provided in
the latest arrangement with Japan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
