<HEAD>Panel Set for Dukakis-Bush Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bernard Shaw of Cable News Network will
moderate Thursday night's prime time debate between George Bush and
Michael Dukakis, with representatives of ABC, NBC and Newsweek
magazine serving as panelists.
   The sponsoring Commission on Presidential Debates said Tuesday
that Andrea Mitchell of NBC, Ann Compton of ABC and Margaret Warner
of Newsweek would pose the questions to the candidates during the
90-minute exchange in Los Angeles.
   The second and final debate between Bush and Dukakis will begin
at 9 p.m. EDT Thursday in Pauley Pavilion on the UCLA campus,
barring a rainout that delays the conclusion of the National League
baseball playoffs.
   The announcement came after CBS anchorman Dan Rather said he had
declined an invitation to be a panelist. Rather said the format
agreed to by the two campaigns was ``not the best'' and added he
would rather report on the event than participate in it.
   In a reverse of the first debate, the first question will go to
Dukakis, and Bush will have the final closing statement, according
to Bob Neuman, spokesman for the commission.
