<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PresidentialPoll     10-12 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Poll,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gallup Poll: Bush 49, Dukakis 43</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush held a 49-43 lead over Michael
Dukakis in a national survey of registered voters conducted by the
Gallup Organization, which also found equal numbers of respondents
calling themselves Republicans and Democrats.
   The organization polled 1,007 registered voters Friday through
Sunday. Because of a four-point margin of error, the two
presidential candidates were statistically tied.
   Other national polls also have found Bush retaining a small
numerical lead, indicating that he is slightly ahead.
   Most other recent polls have been conducted among registered
voters who are judged as likely to turn out. Gallup, applying a
relatively loose gauge of likely voters, found Bush leading by
52-41 in that group of 748.
   Gallup stressed the closer result in its analysis of the survey,
released Tuesday, saying it believed it was too soon to gauge
likelihood of voting.
   That bigger Bush lead could stem from his greater support among
better educated voters, who generally are more likely to vote. He
was backed by 58 percent of college-educated respondents, compared
with 37 percent of those who have not finished high school.
   Also, the Gallup poll found about as many respondents calling
themselves Republicans as Democrats, a result matched in some but
not all other polls. In past years, the Democrats have held a clear
edge.
   As in other polls, the Democratic vice presidential nominee,
Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, was seen as having decisively beaten his
Republican counterpart, Sen. Dan Quayle, in their debate last week.
   Just less than half rated Quayle as qualified to serve as
president if necessary, but that was up from about a third before
the debate. Seventy-six percent called Bentsen qualified, up from
68 percent.
   Gallup sought to ascertain the effect of doubts about Quayle by
isolating the respondents who saw no difference between Bush and
Dukakis but did see a difference between Quayle and Bentsen. They
made up 9 percent of the total, were mostly Democratic and went for
Dukakis by a 2-1 margin.
</TEXT>
