<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen-Texas     10-12 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen-Texas,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Even In Pennsylvania, Bentsen Has Eye On Texas Voters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Lloyd Bentsen picked up an AR-15 assault
rifle at a police practice range in eastern Pennsylvania and
brought the weapon to his shoulder, he was aiming all the same for
Texas votes.
   The Democratic vice presidential candidate's three shots Tuesday
hit just below the silhouette target's heart. Democrats in Texas
are hoping that on Nov. 8 he can hit an electoral bull's eye.
   After weeks of taking a drubbing, Bentsen's strong showing
against Dan Quayle in their debate has sparked new optimism and a
new offensive by the Texas Democrats.
   ``It was viewed as a slam dunk in Texas, and there's obviously a
lot of regional pride,'' said Joe O'Neill, Bentsen's chief of
staff. ``The mentality of the political guys down in the state has
changed dramatically over the past week.''
   O'Neill, Bentsen's top campaign aide, seems to spend as much
time in touch with the senator's Texas organization as he does with
the Democratic campaign's Boston headquarters.
   After all, winning Texas' 29 electoral votes _ third largest
prize in the nation _ was the main reason Bentsen was picked for
the ballot by Michael Dukakis. And he's turned what was expected to
be a GOP blowout into a horserace.
   But so far the polls show he's not winning it.
   Published surveys put the Democrats behind by five to 12 points.
Tom Cosgrove, director of the Dukakis-Bentsen Texas campaign, says
the Democrats' post-debate polling showed the gap near the small
end of that range, while Republicans privately say their data still
show a double-digit lead for George Bush and strong anti-Dukakis
sentiment.
   ``We feel good,'' says Reggie Basher, spokesman for Bush's Texas
campaign. Not only are the polls in Bush's favor, he says, but the
Republicans have a strong organization in the state that Bush also
calls home.
   The task for Bentsen clearly is to convince Texans that Dukakis
would be good for their economy and trustworthy on gut issues such
as crime and gun control _ issues the Bush campaign has used to
clobber the Democrats.
   After he picked up that rifle at the police academy in
Allentown, Pa., Bentsen spoke on how the Democrats were tough on
crime, despite Republican claims to the contrary.
   The image of the vice presidential candidate so armed delivered
the other message: If Dukakis is some kind of anti-gun nut, as the
the Republicans make him out to be, would he have a man on the
ticket like Bentsen who owns many firearms and uses them with
expert flair?
   The campaign is complementing its symbolism with an aggressive
new advertising campaign in the state.
   ``We've just begun to launch our attack, when Texas voters are
paying attention,'' said Cosgrove, a non-Texan who refuses to
accept criticism from state Democrats, including Bentsen, that the
campaign didn't respond quickly enough to the GOP onslaught.
   ``We're a patient campaign,'' Cosgrove said this week. ``This is
Monday, Oct. 10, not Monday, Nov. 7,'' he said this week.
   On the heels of Bentsen's debate, Democrats in the past week
have launched a new television and radio blitz. While Bush has
attacked Dukakis for a prison furlough program and favoring gun
control, the ads say Bush has supported the same things.
   A direct mail campaign lampoons Bush's visits to flag factories.
It features flags of other nations that are doing well under a
Republican administration _ such as drug-exporting countries, the
Iranians who traded hostages for arms, and Japan, with its trade
dominance of the U.S.
   Bentsen has maintained his home state popularity despite being
tied to Dukakis, who is more liberal than most Texas politicians.
Trying to rub some of that approval off on Dukakis, Bentsen flew to
Lone Star, Texas, the day after his Omaha debate for a joint rally
with Dukakis, and he'll be there this week to watch on television
as Dukakis debates Bush.
   And he'll be back.
</TEXT>
