<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iraq-Gas     10-12 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iraq-Gas,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Seeking Last-Minute Compromise On Iraq Sanctions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is seeking a last-minute compromise
as it tries a final time to agree on a package of sanctions against
Iraq for its alleged use of poison gas against Kurds.
   House and Senate negotiators are considering a Senate-passed tax
bill which includes the anti-Iraq provision. The bill is one of the
final items on the congressional agenda before the legislators
adjourn for the year.
   The sanctions package was approved by the Senate, 87-0, as an
amendment Tuesday evening, shortly before the entire bill was
passed, 87-1.
   It was third time in two months the Senate has voted on the
issue, following reports that the Iraqi army used chemical arms in
late August to put down Kurdish rebels.
   ``The world cannot stand by in the face of repeated use of
poison gas by Iraq,'' said Sen. Albert Gore, D-Tenn.
   The measure, less sweeping than the sanctions package adopted by
the Senate a month ago, is similar to a plan already approved by
the House.
   The bill would ban the export to Iraq of U.S. munitions and some
high technology items, and require America to oppose loans to Iraq
by international financial institutions such as the World Bank.
   In addition, President Reagan would have to levy more sanctions
by Dec. 31 unless Iraq provides verifiable assurances that it won't
against use chemical weapons. Those potential sanctions include
denial of export-import credits and downgrading diplomatic
relations.
   But the bill wouldn't restrict grain exports or halt Iraqi
attempts to get monetary credits to buy U.S. agricultural products.
   Sen. David Pryor, D-Ark., reflecting the worries of farm state
legislators, said, ``The concern is that this not lead to an
embargo on agricultural exports to Iraq.''
   But Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., complained that the measure unfairly
penalized U.S. manufacturers.
   ``They're probably laughing at us in Iraq right now,'' Heinz
said, declaring that the bill would not cut off the export to Iraq
of the equipment and chemicals needed to produce such chemical
weapons as mustard gas and nerve gas.
</TEXT>
