<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Polio     10-12 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Polio,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>12-Year-Old Becomes Latest Israeli Polio Sufferer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old boy is the 11th Israeli to
contact polio since an outbreak began last month, and health
officials said an inadequate sewer system was contributing to the
spread of the disease.
   The Health Ministry last week ordered a nationwide vaccination
campaign after the polio virus was found in sewage in at least a
dozen Israeli cities.
   On Tuesday, the third day of the campaign, the government began
vaccinating about 1 million school children against the paralyzing
disease.
   Since September, there have been 11 confirmed cases of the
disease and six suspected cases. But Health Ministry officials
insisted the outbreak has not become an epidemic.
   ``We wouldn't be vaccinating the whole population if we didn't
think the whole population could be at risk. But this absolutely is
not an epidemic,'' said Paul Slater, chief epidemologist for the
Health Ministry.
   He said the latest case, the first confirmed since Sept. 12, was
reported in the town of Hadera, about 30 miles north of Tel Aviv.
The outbreak began in Hadera and most of the cases have been
reported there.
   Doctors believe the boy contracted the disease from an infected
person, not from contaminated sewage, Slater said.
   But Avraham Morag, chairman of the ministry's committee on
infectious diseases, said sewage has contributed to the spread of
the virus in some parts of the country.
   The former head of Israel's sewage system, Avraham Meir, told
Israeli radio that the nation's sewer system must be improved as
soon as possible.
   ``We have to tell the truth, purification centers are not
creating sterile surroundings,'' Meir said on the radio. ``But I'm
against scaring the public and saying, like I heard a child say:
`When I drink water I drink polio.'''
   In Tel Aviv, authorities closed two beaches amid fears that
overflowing sewage could contaminate the water with the virus.
   A spokesman said no trace of the polio virus had been found in
the water but city officials decided to close the beaches as a
precaution.
   At vaccination centers across the country, school children
received drops of the Sabin vaccine on their tongue. In some areas,
nurses went to schools and administered the vaccines in classrooms.
   Ministry officials expect to finish vaccinating school children
today and are now preparing doses of the vaccine for adults.
   More than 3 million people under the age of 40 will be
vaccinated in the next three weeks at a cost of about $2.5 million.
</TEXT>
