<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Herbicide-Drugs     10-12 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Herbicide-Drugs,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Colombian Government Cancels Use of Glyphosphate Against Drugs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia's Ministry of Justice has
canceled plans to use chemical spraying against marijuana and coca
plants because of a peasant protest, Justice Minister Guillermo
Plazas Acid said.
   Colombia's National Dangerous Drugs Board had planned to spray
1,760 acres of marijuana and coca plants with the herbicide
glyphosphate in southwest Colombia.
   About 2,000 peasants marched on the town of Corinto, took over
the town and kidnapped a newspaper reporter and two television
reporters last Saturday.
   The reporters, all Colombians, were released after a government
commission arrived in Corinto, 190 miles southwest of the capital
of Bogota, to talk with the peasants.
   ``The plants will be destroyed by hand, without using chemical
products,'' the justice minister said at a news conference Tuesday.
   The minister said in a response to a reporter's question that
Colombian drug traffickers apparently had organized the peasant
protest.
   A spokesman for the peasants said that the peasants grow
marijuana and coca because drug traffickers loan them money for
planting and buy the crops for cash.
   Government agencies will not loan money to peasants, the
spokesman, Javier Franklin, said in an interview published Tuesday
by Colombia's leading newspaper, El Tiempo, of Bogota.
   The U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration has used glyphosphate
against marijuana plants in the United States.
   Earlier this month, DEA Director John Lawn said that marijuana
had been sprayed by the herbicide from the air for the first time
in the United States.
</TEXT>
