<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CosmosClub     10-12 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cosmos Club,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Previously All-Male Club Admits Women</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government officials, diplomats and economists
are among the first women admitted as members of the previously
all-male Cosmos Club, a 110-year-old private retreat for the
powerful and famous in the nation's capital.
   The group of 18 admitted Tuesday includes Secretary of Labor Ann
McLaughlin, U.S. Commissioner of Labor Statistics Janet L. Norwood,
former ambassador Carol Laise, microbiologist Rita R. Colwell of
the Maryland Biotechnology Institute, and economist Mary Dublin,
associate director of the Conference on Economic Policy.
   The club, housed in an ornate stone mansion, has long been a
retreat for government officials, judges, journalists, university
presidents, businessmen and scientists. Its ranks have included 28
winners of the Nobel Prize and 47 Pulitzer Prize winners.
   A 757-14 vote to admit women came last spring after almost two
decades of controversy that led to the resignation of some
prominent members, including Supreme Court Justice Harry A.
Blackmun. The District of Columbia Office of Human Rights found
last fall that there was ``probable cause to believe'' the men-only
rule violated the city's anti-discrimination law.
   Two women whose nominations to the club were previously reported
_ journalist Nina Totenberg and former League of Women Voters
president Lucy Benson _ were not in the first group approved. Club
officials said work on their nominations has not been completed.
</TEXT>
