<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Jobless-Entrepreneurs     10-12 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jobless-Entrepreneurs,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jobless In Three States To Get Help In Starting Businesses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As many as 2,000 laid off workers in three
states will receive their unemployment compensation benefits in
lump sums for use in starting their own businesses, the Labor
Department said.
   The jobless workers in Oregon, Massachusetts and Minnesota will
be part of a demonstration project authorized by Congress last
year. The project will divert about $8 million in the unemployment
insurance fund to helping between 1,000 and 2,000 beneficiaries
``become successful entrepreneurs.''
   The program, starting in mid-1989, would provide cash allowances
equal to the amount laid off workers would normally receive in
weekly unemployment insurance benefits, the department said.
   ``Small businesses have been the primary source of new jobs in
the United States over the last decade,'' said Labor Secretary Ann
McLaughlin. ``This pilot project will help unemployed persons with
entrepreneurial spirit to create jobs for themselves by starting
new business ventures.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
