<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 0227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador     10-12 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftist Politician Returns To El Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leftist leader returned to
this Central American country from exile after the government said
he could resume his political activities if he renounced any ties
with Salvadoran guerrillas.
   Mario Aguinada Carranza, secretary-general of the Democratic
Nationalist Union, returned from Mexico Tuesday after spending
eight years in exile. The U.S.-supported government considers
Aguinada's party a front for the underground Communist Party.
   Vice President Rodolfo Castillo Claramount told journalists
Monday night that Aguinada could participate in politics if he
renounces any post he may have held in the guerrilla organization.
   Aguinada had been scheduled to accompany two other Nationalist
Union leaders who returned from exile in July. He postponed that
trip in response to reports he would be arrested upon arrival.
   Communications Minister Roberto Viera said in July that Aguinada
had held a high, but unspecified post in the guerrilla hierarchy.
   Nationalist Union officials denied it, saying Aguinada's work
was on behalf of the Democratic Revolutionary Front, the political
organization allied with the rebel combatants.
   Aguinada told about 200 supporters at the airport: ``I greet you
again in this country of ours, for which thousands have offered
their blood and their lives in the struggle for liberation.''
   About 65,000 people have been killed in the war, most of them
civilians.
   A military communique said Tuesday that troops raided a
guerrilla camp in northeastern Cabanas province, killing two rebels
and wounding five.
   The army also said a soldier was wounded in one of numerous
harassment attacks Monday on army positions in different parts of
the country.
   Rebels also destroyed six utility poles in their continuing
campaign to sabotage electrical installations, the statement said.
   The guerrillas on Tuesday celebrated the eighth anniversary of
the founding of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, the
organization of five guerrilla armies fighting to overthrow the
government.
   ``We have carried the war to the cities and the rearguard of the
enemy,'' the rebels said on their clandestine Radio Venceremos.
   ``Our objective is to construct a new and sovereign country,
where the campesino can be the owner of the land he works, where
men have equality,'' Cmdr. Ferman Cienfuegos said in the broadcast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
