<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Australia-Indonesia     10-12 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Australia-Indonesia,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Killing Of Australian Yachtsman Sparks Diplomatic Row</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The shooting death of an Australian
yachtsman by Indonesian police has caused a major diplomatic row
between the two countries, with Prime Minister Bob Hawke rejecting
Indonesian explanations.
   The Indonesian government called the Aug. 14 killing of David
Blenkinsop an accident, but Hawke on Tuesday demanded a full
inquiry into the ``dastardly event.
   ``We are not going to have a situation where Australian
nationals can be pushed around, in this case killed, and just sit
quietly back,'' Hawke said. ``We will pursue this matter to see
that it is properly investigated.''
   The Indonesian Embassy in Canberra said police boarded the
couple's yacht and Blenkinsop and his pregnant British-born
fiancee, Joanne Mist, were shot accidentally during a struggle. The
embassy said the yachtsman drowned after falling overboard.
   Ms. Mist says Blenkinsop was shot twice and thrown overboard.
Her baby was not injured.
   ``Certainly the late Mr. Blenkinsop's fiancee has a quite
different story and I must say that I'm not prepared to accept at
face value some story on the part of Indonesian authorities about
an accident,'' Hawke said.
   Blenkinsop's parents said they spent $6,400 to search for their
son's body. Frustrated at the lack of information, they finally
wrote to Hawke.
   Thaufick Salim, spokesman for the Indonesian Embassy, said
Blenkinsop and his fiancee entered Indonesian waters during a
voyage from Thailand to Australia two months ago, to seek shelter
from rough weather and refuel.
   They landed on the island of Serui where their yacht was boarded
by police, who asked them to sail to the island of Biak for
immigration clearance and to collect supplies.
   ``Someone unfortunately told Mr. Blenkinsop they were going to
be arrested on Biak and he tried to sail in another direction,''
Salim said. ``After ignoring a warning from one of the police, Mr.
Blenkinsop rushed at the police officer.
   ``His gun exploded and hit Mr. Blenkinsop in the arm. It
exploded again and hit Ms. Mist,'' Salim said.
   Indonesian authorities said they could not complete their
investigation because they did not have testimony from Ms. Mist.
   Hawke said later that Indonesian authorities arrested a
policeman and a civilian officer involved in the incident.
   He said the shootings were appalling and despicable. ``It was a
dastardly event,'' Hawke said.
   He told Parliament he will continue to press for an impartial
and proper inquiry and put further pressure on Jakarta by promising
to take up cases of Australians jailed in that country. The Foreign
Ministry said 11 Australians are in Indonesian jails, mainly in
Bali, on drug offenses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
