<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     10-12 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEOC Didn't Pursue Job Bias Cases, GAO Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a House panel that oversees
the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission says a new report shows
the agency was ``more concerned with reducing paperwork than with
protecting claimants' civil rights.''
   The General Accounting Office released a report Tuesday that
said the EEOC did not fully investigate up to 82 percent of job
discrimination claims over a three-month period last year.
   Rep. Augustus Hawkins, D-Calif., who ordered the study as
chairman of the House Education and Labor Committee, said ``The
EEOC's failure to fully investigate job discrimination claims is
further evidence of the agency's attack on civil rights
protections.''
   The GAO, an investigative arm of Congress, said 41 to 82 percent
of the charges closed by six EEOC district offices during the
period and 40 to 87 percent of charges closed by five state
agencies were not fully investigated.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>US to Pay Former Patients Drugged in CIA Experiment $750,000</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department said a settlement of a
law suit will provide $750,000 to nine people who were subjected to
mind-control experiments by their psychiatrist, whose research was
aided by a CIA front organization.
   The CIA in the late 1950s granted $60,000 to Dr. Ewen Cameron, a
Canadian, who used the money to conduct a series of experiments
with his patients.
   He subjected the patients to drug-induced sleep therapy for
weeks at a time, gave them LSD and administered electroshock
therapy at up to 75 times the usual intensity.
   Nine former patients of Cameron brought a suit in 1980 in U.S.
District Court in Washington, D.C., and a tentative settlement with
the CIA, now given final approval, was disclosed last week in
court. The Justice Department announced the final settlement
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Labor Awards $2 Million For Migrant Retraining</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Separate programs in four states will split $2
million in federal grant money to retrain migrant and seasonal farm
workers who lost their jobs because of the summer drought.
   ``These workers are caught in an adverse situation beyond their
control,'' Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin said Tuesday in
announcing the grants. ``We want to provide them with the necessary
skills training so they can quickly return to being productive.''
   Five areas of Texas will get a total of $1.5 million to assist
some 1,100 migrant workers returning to the state, their home in
the winter, with little or no income because of the effects of the
drought on crops.
   Job training programs in Oregon, Alabama and Indiana also
received grants.
</TEXT>
