<1ST_LINE>r p PM-TheNegativeCampaign 1stLd-Writethru a0465 10-12 1018</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-The Negative Campaign, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0465,990</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Finally Responding to Bush's Negative Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS publishable editor's note at end on writer</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After enduring weeks of attack on hot-button
issues such as crime and the flag, the slow-to-anger Democratic
presidential nominee responded with the emotion his backers longed
for this campaign. But not before Michael Dukakis' own mother did
first.
   ``Can anyone get as low as this?'' 85-year-old Euterpe Dukakis
asked after recounting what she regarded as personal attacks by
George Bush and the Republicans.
   ``I am telling these truths because my son refuses to,'' she
said.
   Appearing together in Maine last weekend, both Dukakises
demonstrated dismay at a Republican campaign focusing on a handful
of issues.
   Bush has been blamed for trivializing the 1988 presidential
campaign. He has devoted weeks to attacking the governor of
Massachusetts over his veto of a bill requiring the Pledge of
Allegiance in schools; over a program allowing weekend furloughs
for inmates, including convicted murders; for membership in the
American Civil Liberties Union; and for moving slowly on pollution
in his own back yard.
   And he has had help, too.
   President Reagan's reference to Dukakis as an ``invalid,'' was
quickly retracted _ but the fact that he uttered it thrust onto
front pages the Washington rumors that Dukakis had hidden past
mental trouble. The rumors were false, by all evidence. But the
episode coincided with the beginning of Dukakis's slide in the
polls.
   Republican Sen. Steve Symms of Idaho asserted that an old photo
existed of Dukakis's wife burning an American flag in protest over
the Vietnam war. Kitty Dukakis denies it. No photo ever emerged.
But subtle damage may have been done.
   Dukakis has begun responding with his own negative assaults. On
television commercials and in speeches, he belittles Bush's running
mate Dan Quayle; he accuses Bush of plotting a ``raid'' on Social
Security; and he depicts Bush as lacking judgment.
   All of this is part of what frequently is lamented as the
negative nature of the 1988 presidential race.
   Minor issues, or outright distortions, are screamed while hardly
a whisper is heard about the national debt piling up by the
billions, relations with the Soviets, the AIDS plague, or the
hostages still in Lebanon.
   ``It is true _ it's a very negative campaign, and I say most of
the blame lies with Bush,'' said William Schneider, political
observer at the American Enterprise Institute, a conservative think
tank.
   ``I say his campaign is probably the most disgraceful in modern
American history,'' Schneider adds. ``It is also working. It is
both disgraceful and effective.''
   The only real surprise, though, is that this type of campaign
comes as much of a surprise to anyone.
   For one thing, look what happened to the two candidates who did
talk about the deficit. Democrat Bruce Babbitt and Republican Bob
Dole, like Walter Mondale four years earlier, found voters didn't
want to hear it.
   And the negative campaign is hardly a 1988 phenomenon.
   ``It is more negative at an earlier stage than any presidential
campaign I've seen,'' said Frank Greer, a Democratic consultant who
has been advising Dukakis on his debates. ``But it follows the
pattern of Senate and gubernatorial races ... The 1980s have seen a
real escalation in the use of negative advertising.''
   In fact, Democrats have become accustomed over the past eight
years to facing intensely negative campaigns centered on one or two
or three emotional issues in statewide races.
   NCPAC, the National Conservative Political Action Committee, ran
a series of campaigns in which they targeted Democratic incumbents
with intensive negative television commercials on a few emotional
issues. In 1984, Sen. Jesse Helms of North Carolina ran negative TV
ads about his opponent for more than a year.
   Democrats have learned to deal with such campaigns by responding
forcefully.
   Dukakis's running mate, vice presidential nominee Lloyd Bentsen,
faced a NCPAC campaign in Texas in 1982, when he was seeking
re-election. He fired back and won easily.
   On his campaign plane last weekend, Bentsen expressed relief
that Dukakis at last had begun to respond with their own tough ads.
   ``Where have they been?'' he said, holding out his arms in an
expression of frustration at the delay.
   Bentsen said the Dukakis campaign should have responded
immediately when, after the Democratic convention in July, the
Republicans began attacks on Dukakis's record and even his
patriotism.
   Some say Dukakis and his advisers are to blame for failing to
forsee the attacks, failing to recognize the visceral impact some
were having, and failing to respond before the damage was done.
   Dukakis, after all, has never before run against a serious,
conservative Republican campaign.
   ``One reason why he frittered away 17 points was because he
didn't respond and didn't go hard negative himself,'' said Larry
Sabato, political scientist at the University of Virginia.
   ``You have to fight fire with fire. You can't sit there and take
it. And you can't just occasionally respond and be defensive. You
have to give your response immediately, in tough terms, and then go
on the attack yourself. That's modern politics in a nutshell.''
   Sabato says the negative campaign shouldn't be a surprise when
viewed in a historical context, too. In 1964, for instance, Barry
Goldwater was depicted as representing the threat of nuclear war _
a pretty negative notion.
   The reason campaigns have grown increasingly negative is that
such attacks work.
   The issues the Bush campaign selected seemed to resonate with
voters as symbols of something larger and unsettling.
   Bush's aim was to raise doubts about Dukakis and depict him as a
Massachusetts liberal. He apparently has succeeded.
   In early August, Dukakis said Bush ``has some of the highest
negatives ever recorded in the history of American politics.'' He
was referring to unfavorable ratings in polls.
   Two months later, it is Dukakis who has the high negatives.
Polls show his unfavorable rating now tops 40 percent, exceeding
that of both Bush and Quayle.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   William M. Welch is covering the Michael Dukakis
presidential campaign for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
