<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     10-12 0746</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis In Debate City After Rowdy Rally In North Dakota</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Should stand.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He sang ``Happy Birthday,'' doffed his
suitcoat in favor of a football jacket and, to the astonishment of
aides, kissed the two cheerleaders who presented the gift.
   Michael Dukakis was delivering what advisers hope he can deliver
again Thursday night in his final debate with George Bush _ a
genuine show of emotion, something Dukakis rarely allows himself on
the campaign trail.
   The Democratic presidential nominee arrived here late Tuesday
night and was staying in the Los Angeles area until the showdown
with Bush.
   ``One of the nice things about debates is that they get people
out from behind the balloons and out of the flag factory and it
gets them to address the issues,'' Dukakis told a crowd of about
350 people at the airport here.
   The Massachusetts governor had no public events scheduled today
but was holding meetings with about 20 aides and advisers on the
debate. The confrontation could prove crucial to Dukakis' attempts
to overcome Bush, who holds a slight lead in most polls but is
believed to have a larger edge in Electoral College votes.
   Dukakis aides, speaking to reporters on the flight from Boston,
said they believed voters were still not familiar with Dukakis and
that one of his major debate challenges would be to convince voters
he cares more about their concerns than Bush.
   Those aides were thrilled by what they saw in Fargo, N.D., where
Dukakis held an airport rally while his plane was refueled Tuesday
night.
   About 800 people who braved 45-degree temperatures to attend the
late-night rally appeared happy with Dukakis' performance as well.
   He had just finished greeting the state and local officials on
hand when he introduced Ted Mondale, a Midwest coordinator for
Dukakis, and the son of the 1984 Democratic nominee, Walter Mondale.
   Dukakis told the crowd Ted Mondale celebrates his 31st birthday
today.
   Then came the unexpected: Dukakis led the crowd in singing
``Happy Birthday,'' with even Mondale looking on in apparent
surprise.
   An upbeat Dukakis delivered his standard stump speech to the
crowd and told them ``victory is out there'' if they work hard for
a Democratic victory.
   He also took his staple swipe at Republican vice presidential
nominee Dan Quayle.
   Dukakis mentioned his choice, Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, and
referred to him as ``the best qualified person for the job.''
   ``I wonder if the Republicans can say the same?'' Dukakis,
sporting a broad grin, asked rhetorically.
   At the end of the rally, two cheerleaders from North Dakota
State University, the No. 1 ranked team in NCAA Division II
football, presented Dukakis with a bright yellow Bisons jacket,
which he quickly donned before thanking the cheerleaders with a
kiss on the cheek. He sported the jacket on the flight from Fargo
to Los Angeles as well.
   Dukakis' pre-debate coaching has been rich with suggestions that
Dukakis make an emotional connection with voters.
   ``I think it's very important that the American people know his
values, know what he cares about,'' John Sasso, the campaign's vice
chairman, said during the flight West. ``The question is: Where are
you going to lead us?''
   California Rep. Tony Coehlo, who traveled with the Dukakis
entourage, said many voters would consider Dukakis a ``blind date''
because they do not know enough about him.
   ``The American people don't want to elect George Bush,'' Coehlo
said. ``They think he's OK but they don't want to elect him. They
want another option and just need to get to know Mike Dukakis to
have it.''
   Dukakis aides also make no secret of the fact that Quayle will
be a Dukakis debate target.
   ``It's obvious that a lot of people are frightened,'' Sasso
said. ``This is a guy who is a heartbeat away from the presidency.
... It scares people.''
   At the same time, though, Dukakis will try to frame the Quayle
selection in the larger context of Bush's judgment and also try to
contrast the proposals on health care, college opportunity,
housing, trade and education in recent weeks with what the Dukakis
camp terms as a Bush campaign of ``symbols and slogans'' that lacks
substance.
   ``They don't like where the dialogue is going and they want to
get it back on, who knows what, the Pledge of Allegiance,'' Sasso
said. ``This is not a ping pong match of one liners.''
</TEXT>
