<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Iraq     10-12 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq and Iran Exchange Soldiers' Bodies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq and Iran exchanged soldiers' remains
for the first time since their cease-fire took effect seven weeks
ago, a senior U.N. official said.
   But an Iraqi government-run newspaper said there was no progress
in U.N.-mediated talks toward a permanent peace settlement.
   U.N. Assistant Secretary-General Marrack Goulding told a news
conference in the Iraqi capital that each side on Tuesday handed
over the bodies of eight soldiers killed during the eight-year war.
   He said the exchange took place in the war front's southern
sector, but gave no further details.
   Goulding, visiting Iraq and Iran for talks on consolidating the
cease-fire, said the exchange was ``a sad and moving event but it
showed that through the United Nations there can be cooperation
between the two sides.''
   Goulding was scheduled to leave today for Tehran for talks with
Iranian officials and a visit to the Iranian side of the front.
   U.N. peacekeeping troops are posted along the Iraq-Iran border
to monitor the cease-fire that went into effect Aug. 20. Peace
talks started Aug. 25 but are bogged down over Iraq's demand for
free navigation in the Persian Gulf and clearing the Shaat al-Arab
waterway.
   Goulding said the cease-fire was holding although both sides
reported minor violations and ``two or three'' soldiers were
killed. He gave no details of how the deaths occurred.
   The U.N. official also said some soldiers had been taken
prisoner since the cease-fire. But he did not say whether they were
Iranian or Iraqi and noted a number of them had been freed.
   Iran last month released 72 disabled Iraqis, but Iraq has not
yet freed any prisoners of war and is known to have taken more than
700 Iranians POWs in September in what Tehran called a major
cease-fire violation.
   According to the Red Cross, a total of 50,182 prisoners of war
are held by Iran and 19,284 by Iraq. But U.N. officials and
diplomats in Baghdad and Tehran believe Iran holds 60,000-70,000
prisoners and Iraq 30,000-50,000.
   An Iraqi government-run newspaper said Tuesday there has been no
progress in the Iran-Iraq peace talks since they started over six
weeks ago.
   The front page editorial in Al-Joumhouriya was the first comment
by Iraq's official media on the statement Saturday by Iranian
Foreign Minister Ali Akhbar Velayati, who said the two sides agreed
in principle to U.N. proposals to end the war.
   The daily said Iran has not committed itself to respecting free
navigation in the Persian Gulf and clearing the Shaat al-Arab
waterway, the estuary of the Tigris and Euphrates rivers and Iraq's
main outlet to the sea. It said there was no breakthrough in
negotiations and accused Iran of continuing ``delaying tactics and
procrastination.''
   Velayati said Iran agreed to a U.N. proposal that it give up its
right to search ships in the Strait of Hormuz, the strategic mouth
of the gulf.
   He did not mention Iraq's demand to clear the Shatt al-Arab
before letting the talks progress.
   The talks have moved from Geneva to New York and are expected to
return to Geneva at the end of the month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
