<DOCNO> AP881012-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 0338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Cambodia     10-12 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Cambodia,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Would Accept Khmer Rouge Leader, Diplomats Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China may be willing to grant sanctuary to
Pol Pot, leader of the feared Khmer Rouge guerrilla group, to clear
the way for a settlement of the war in Cambodia, diplomats say.
   The communist Khmer Rouge, blamed for mass executions and forced
relocations during nearly four years of brutal rule in Cambodia,
were overthrown by the Vietnamese in 1978.
   But the Khmer Rouge's continued presence as a potent guerrilla
force has been viewed as an obstacle to negotiating the withdrawal
of Vietnamese troops.
   China supported the Khmer Rouge when it ruled Cambodia but has
been distancing itself from the group. Diplomats have said that Pol
Pot's exile to China may accelerate a settlement in the conflict.
   China has not ruled out such a development.
   ``The Chinese government would take any alien as a refugee to
China if the whole affair conforms with Chinese law,'' China's U.N.
Mission spokesman, Yuan Shibing, said Tuesday.
   Vietnam has said it would withdraw its troops from Cambodia by
1990 and has been negotiating with the three-member Cambodian
resistance, which includes the Khmer Rouge.
   Diplomats say China's acceptance of Pol Pot could help pave the
way for a settlement.
   ``This offer is what China intends to do if it is necessary that
Pol Pot and his close collegues should be given exile somehwere
outside of Kampuchea (Cambodia),'' said one Asian diplomat familiar
with negotiations, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   China, he said, still insists that Vietnam withdraw its troops
as a first step in any settlement. The diplomat, speaking on
condition of anonymity, described a possible offer of exile as
``the bottom line,'' but not something that China immediately would
offer.
   In Washington, meanwhile, Cambodian Prince Norodom Sihanouk,
leader of one of the factions fighting the Vietnamese occupation,
said Tuesday: ``I think it is necessary to give the world some
guarantee about the Khmer Rouge in the future.
   ``I think the ones who are responsible for the genocide of the
Cambodian people'' in the 1970s ``must not continue to lead the
Khmer Rouge movement and they must go into exile if possible,'' he
said after a meeting with President Reagan.
   Reagan spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the president reiterated
U.S. policy favoring a complete withdrawal of Vietnamese troops and
opposing a return to power of the Khmer Rouge.
   In a sign of Beijing's distancing itself from Pol Pot, Chinese
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen recently told the General Assembly
that the armies of the Cambodian factions should be dissolved and
replaced with a new national army, equally representing all
factions.
   Pol Pot's regime has been blamed for killing an estimated 1
million people.
   Chinese officials were expected to meet this week with
ambassadors of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations to
discuss the Cambodian problem.
   The Khmer Rouge is the strongest of three factions fighting
Vietnam's occupying forces in Cambodia. Besides the non-communist
forces of Sihanouk, the resistance includes the forces of Son Sann,
a Western-leaning politician.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881012-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 0351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Venezuela-Military     10-12 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Venezuela-Military,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Calls Region's Foreign Debt Its Biggest Security
Risk</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's defense minister says
Latin America's foreign debt is a bigger security risk than its
drug trade, insurgencies or border conflicts.
   ``Behind the drug trafficking and behind the subversion is the
incommensurable weight of the foreign debt, which erodes and
asphyxiates our economies,'' said Gen. Italo del Valle Alliegro.
   ``It is not just an economic problem, but a political and social
problem that can create strong centers of disturbance for our
systems,'' Del Valle Alliegro said in an interview with The
Associated Press this week.
   Latin American countries are struggling to pay foreign debts
totaling over $400 billion. Venezuela, which owes at least $34
billion, is the region's fourth-largest debtor.
   Del Valle, named defense minister in July, said Venezuela's
armed forces are committed to defending a 30-year-old democratic
system.
   ``We have a solid and mature democracy, and our armed forces are
convinced of their role of supporting the nation's civil
institutions,'' he said.
   He said Venezuela never adopted the doctrine of national
security which led to military takeovers throughout Latin America
because it felt the theory was ``authoritarian and
anti-democratic.''
   The theory, which broadened the scope of national defense to
allow the military a legitimate political role in keeping out
communism, originated in the U.S. War College and was further
expanded by the Brazilian armed forces.
   It is credited with having opened the way for military ousters
of civilian rulers in Argentina, Bolivia, Brazil, Uruguay, Chile
and other countries in the 1960s and early 1970s.
   He said a document backed last year by military leaders
throughout Latin America, including Venezuela, did not constitute a
joint defense pact.
   The document identified the international communist movement as
the ``common and principal threat'' to the Americas. It was issued
by 14 Latin American nations and the U.S. during the 17th
Conference of American Armed Forces, which took place at Mar del
Plata, Argentina in November 1987.
   ``It was one working paper among many others. There is no
anti-communist pact,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
