<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Austria     10-12 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Austria,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Concerned About Western European Economic Moves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev reiterated his
concern over Western European plans for economic integration,
saying they could work against cooperation with the East, Tass
reported.
   In a Kremlin meeting with Austrian Chancellor Franz Vranitzky,
the 57-year-old Soviet leader said Tuesday that Europeans have been
striving for economic internationalization and political
independence.
   ``But on the other hand, what awaits the all-European process if
the Western part of Europe cruelly closes itself off in a new
formation?'' Gorbachev asked, in excerpts reported by Tass, the
official news agency.
   ``How, then, would a `European home' be built?'' he said,
referring to a concept that calls on East and West Europeans to
cooperate politically and economically.
   It was the second time Gorbachev has expressed concern to a high
Western European official over plans by the 12-member European
Economic Community to create a single market in 1992, by
eliminating borders and unifying customs regulations. Austria is
not an EEC member.
   In a July 30 Kremlin meeting with West German Foreign Minister
Hans-Dietrich Genscher, Gorbachev said European politicians would
have to bear responsibility for any damage the proposal would have
on ``positive beginnings'' toward disarmament and strengthening
security.
   Gorbachev apparently shares the same fears expressed by other
world leaders that the 1992 economic unification of Europe will
shut out trade with nations that are not members of the EEC.
   He also may fear that the EEC will pose a more formidable
competitor to Moscow in selling its goods on the world market.
   Vranitzky arrived in Moscow on Monday and is scheduled to leave
Thursday.
</TEXT>
