<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Angola     10-12 0435</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Angola,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Botha: Cuban Troop Withdrawal Timetable Still To Be Worked Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President P.W. Botha of South Africa
says an agreement in principle has been reached on the withdrawal
of 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola, but that the timetable still
needs to be worked out.
   Botha, speaking at a press conference Tuesday, dismissed press
reports that South Africa, Cuba and Angola had agreed during
weekend a meeting in New York on a timetable for a troop withdrawal.
   ``The principle has been accepted, but the timetable needs to be
worked out,'' he said.
   South Africa has scheduled for Nov. 1 the start of an
independence plan for neighboring South-West Africa, known as
Namibia, but it has linked Namibian independence to a Cuban troop
withdrawal from Angola.
   Botha warned that the Nov. 1 deadline for beginning the U.N.
independence plan for Namibia may not be met.
   ``South Africa wants to see South-West Africa to be
independent,'' he said. But he said if ``other forces'' who are
taking part ``are not prepared to start with the necessary
machinery on the first of November, that is not South Africa's
fault.'' He did not elaborate.
   The parties involved in the talks are to meet later this month
in Brazzaville, Congo.
   In New York, Cuba's deputy foreign minister, Ricardo Alarcon de
Quesada, and Angola's ambassador to the U.N., Manuel Pedro
Pacavira, also said Tuesday that negotiators reached no agreement
in talks held Friday through Sunday.
   They spoke at a news conference in response to published reports
saying the talks reached agreement on a 24- to 30-month pullout by
the Cubans.
   ``We are at an impasse, which is not precisely synonymous with
agreement,''' said Alarcon.
   ``As you can see in the newspapers' reports almost daily, we
haven't yet achieved an agreement or understanding on the calendar
for the withdrawal of the Cuban forces in Angola,'' he said.
   Alarcon said Cuba and Angola need 30 months to train and equip
Angolan forces to deal with any future raids by South Africa or by
the Angolan rebels that are backed by the United States and South
Africa.
   The United States, serving as mediator in the talks, has
suggested a 24-month withdrawal and South Africa agrees, said
Alarcon and Pacavira.
   Pacavira said the conflicting proposals were advanced a month
ago in a meeting in Brazzaville.
   South Africa in the past has launched periodic raids from
Namibia into southern Angola to back up rebel forces when they
encountered heavy resistance from Cuban forces.
   Under a preliminary agreement in the peace talks, all South
African forces left southern Angola by Sept. 1.
</TEXT>
