<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CloseStrippers     10-12 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Close Strippers,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Says Male Strippers Performed Too Close to Female
Patrons</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note Contents</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WESTMINSTER, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Male strippers cavorted too close to
female patrons at a fire department fund-raiser, upsetting some
husbands and violating a state law requiring performers to remain
at least 6 feet away, a prosecutor said.
   During the male dance revue last month, strippers came close
enough for members of the Taneytown Volunteer Fire Department's
women's auxiliary to tuck dollar bills in the dancers' G-strings,
Assistant State's Attorney Jill Trivas said.
   State liquor laws require G-string clad strippers in eight
counties to keep 6 feet between them and patrons. The law also
forbids the touching of buttocks.
   ``Had I been aware of these things, I might have been able to
talk with these gentlemen and explain what they could do,'' said
Diane Perry, secretary of the women's auxiliary, whose members paid
$10 each to see the Sept. 23 show.
   The Carroll County liquor board, which took the matter under
consideration after a few husbands lodged complaints, expects to
render a decision in 30 days on whether the fire department was
responsible for allowing the violation to occur. Possible penalties
include a $2,000 fine.
   Ms. Perry asked the liquor board Tuesday for leniency, saying
she did not learn about the 6-foot rule until moments before the
event started.
   Ms. Perry said the show, which raised $2,000, could not have
been canceled that night ``without a demonstration.''
   Mustang, Rebel, Jaguar and Flash were among members of ``The
Fox,'' a traveling troupe from Lansdale, Pa., who have performed
for more than 400 fire department women's auxilaries in seven
states, Ms. Perry said.
   Fire Department President James H. Parker, who obtained the
liquor license for the event, told the liquor board he agreed with
the prosecutor's interpretation of the law.
   Parker admitted he was warned about the law when the board
granted a one-day liquor license for the revue. He contended the
women failed to heed his warning, issued less than two hours before
the show began.
</TEXT>
