<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SouthAfrica-Spy     10-12 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Spy,0592</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weapons Analyst Pleads Guilty in First Espionage Case Involving
South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former civilian weapons analyst pleaded
guilty to passing military secrets to South Africa, an act his
attorney said was motivated by a misguided sense of patriotism.
   Thomas Joseph Dolce, 49, pleaded guilty Tuesday in U.S. District
Court to one count of espionage, the first such case involving
South Africa, prosecutors said. Dolce faces up to 10 years in
prison and a $10,000 fine.
   His attorney, Harold I. Glaser, said the father of three
believed the United States should be doing more to help what Dolce
considers to be an important U.S. ally fighting communism.
   ``He did it out of what he considered to be loyalty, but it was
of course a gigantic, gigantic mistake,'' said Glaser.
   Dolce, a former employee at the Aberdeen Proving Ground north of
Baltimore admitted mailing a classified document in 1979 to Col.
Bernardus Redelinghuys, a defense and armed forces attache at the
South African Embassy in Washington.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Gary P. Jordan, reading from a statement
of facts at a hearing, said Dolce ``furnished the South Africans
with anything he came across pertaining to Russian equipment. He
reasoned that the South Africans were confronted with Soviet
equipment in Angola and that the United States should be providing
this information to them.''
   Jordan said Dolce delivered the document to Redelinghuys because
of its potential use for sabotage by South Africa, a staunchly
anti-communist country that is ruled by its white minority under a
system of racial segregation called apartheid.
   Dolce also acknowledged delivering batches of classified
documents on 40 or more occasions, by mail and in person, to three
military attaches at the embassy and to South African missions in
London and Los Angeles between the fall of 1979 and the summer of
1983.
   For agreeing to plead guilty to the single count and to
cooperate with prosecutors, he was not prosecuted under a more
severe statute carrying a maximum sentence of life in prison.
   Dolce had security clearance through his work for the Army
Material Systems Analysis Activity, a Department of the Army agency
charged with evaluating weapons systems.
   Glaser said Dolce was the only U.S. citizen involved, adding the
government learned of his client's activities ``inadvertantly.''
The lawyer declined to elaborate.
   Authorities said Dolce had insisted his activities were
motivated by ideological, rather than financial, concerns. Jordan
said there is no evidence that Dolce accepted money.
   U.S. authorities would not discuss the extent of the damage
Dolce's activities caused to national security.
   Alayne Resberg, press secretary for the South African Embassy,
said her country considered the matter ``history.''
   ``Two of the officers allegedly involved have already retired
from active service, and the third officer is no longer in the
United States of America,'' she said.
   ``We would just like to point out that South Africa doesn't
consider itself an unfriendly nation toward the U.S.A.,'' she said,
adding that neither the FBI nor the Justice Department has talked
to anyone in the embassy about the case.
   Dolce ended his relationship with the South Africans in 1983,
apparently because of a personality clash with the embassy's new
defense attache, authorities said.
   U.S. District Judge Herbert F. Murray ordered Dolce held in jail
without bail pending a sentencing date, which has yet to be set.
   Prosecutors said they would recommend Dolce be given the maximum
sentence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
