<HEAD>James Brown Leaves For Concert Tour Despite Court Dates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soul singer James Brown left for a monthlong
European concert tour despite pending court dates in two states,
and officials said they would seek to put the entertainer in jail
if he does not appear as scheduled.
   Brown faces several charges in Georgia and South Carolina, and
could forfeit nearly $33,000 in bonds if he misses the court
appearances.
   Buddy Dallas, Brown's attorney, said Tuesday that the singer had
left for the tour. Court officials said no requests for delays had
been filed.
   Brown has an Oct. 18 date in Augusta's municipal court on three
charges, including driving under the influence, stemming from a
Sept. 25 arrest.
   Harry James, solicitor for the court, said Brown ``is making a
mockery of the court system if he has no intention of appearing.''
   If Brown is not in court, James said he will seek a warrant for
Brown's arrest.
   The singer also is scheduled to appear Oct. 24 in Aiken County,
S.C., General Sessions Court to answer charges of assault and
battery with intent to kill, driving under the influence and
failure to stop for police stemming from a Sept. 24 incident.
   In addition, Brown is scheduled for arraignment in State Court
in Augusta on Nov. 8 on charges including carrying a pistol without
a license and carrying a deadly weapon to a public gathering.
   Dallas, meanwhile, said Brown voluntarily admitted himself
Friday to an Atlanta hospital for treatment of a drug problem.
   Dallas refused to identify the hospital.
   Brown tried to admit himself to an Athens, Ga., hospital Sept.
27, but was turned away for lack of space. Brown had said he would
try to enter the hospital again Sept. 30.
   However, he went to the Atlanta hospital because it could take
him sooner, Dallas said.
