<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 0456EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AlamoBattles     10-12 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Alamo Battles,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alamo Battle's Descendants Still Fight On</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Alamo may have been at peace since 1836,
but descendants of those who fought there have a new battle brewing
over control of $1.7 million banked from souvenir sales at the
shrine.
   The Daughters of the Republic of Texas have always had charge of
the Alamo and its bank account. But the League of United Latin
American Citizens, angered over what it calls a misrepresentation
of history by the Daughters, says they should turn any surplus over
to the state.
   ``In my opinion, all they want to do is get their hands on the
money,'' Ella Stumpf, 84, one of the Daughters, said this week.
   The Alamo is a self-financing facility: No state tax money is
invested and the Daughters must generate funds from the souvenir
shop to pay for a staff of 65 and an annual budget in excess of $1
million.
   The mission, visited by 3 million people a year, occupies four
acres of state land in downtown San Antonio. The Daughters serve at
the pleasure of the Legislature, which alone has authority to end
their custodial role.
   ``I don't think too many people knew they had $1.7 million in
the bank off sales from their souvenir shop. I don't think anyone
had ever asked,'' said state Rep. Orlando Garcia, whose inquiry
into the Alamo ledgers started the current flap.
   Garcia said unless the Daughters ``have a great purpose for
these funds'' the money could become available to the state.
   When the attorney general ruled that the Alamo finances fell
under the Texas Open Records Act, the Daughters sent a copy of
their latest audited budget to Garcia.
   ``We'd never had to face this before. ... We're happy to do
whatever the proper authorities want us to do. We don't have
anything to hide,'' said Peggy Dibrell, a member of the Daughters'
Alamo Committee.
   Attached to the audit was a note explaining the intended plans
for the surplus funds: a new film and activity center, two new
educational films and a permanent operating ``hedge'' against a
sudden drop-off in tourism.
   Jose Garcia de Lara, president of the Latin American citizens
league, was quick to call for a full accounting of the finances,
with any surplus funds be considered for other state programs.
   ``Quite frankly, we aren't very adamant about taking over the
Alamo. Our main issue is we want accountability by whomever is
running it to the peoples of the state and to the history of our
citizenry,'' he said.
   ``The Daughters have created their history by perpetuating myth
and by omission: These thousands of bad Mexicans killed our few
good Anglos and this has made the chapel a symbol of oppression.''
   About 180 Texans, including Davy Crockett and Jim Bowie, died at
the Alamo fort-chapel when it was attacked by an army of thousands
of Mexicans during the Texas Revolution in 1836.
   But Garcia, the legislator, said there is no historical or
cultural component to his inquiry.
   ``I don't have time to get annoyed by what did or didn't happen
in 1836,'' he said. ``What is at issue is access to records about
finances that should be public. My name could be Davy Crockett the
Fifth and I'd be asking the same questions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881012-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 0539EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     10-12 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain, Sleet And Even Snow Fall Over Eastern Great Lakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain, sleet and even snow fell over the eastern Great Lakes
region as a low pressure system over western Quebec combined with
high pressure over Manitoba, Canada, to produce a taste of winter
weather.
   The low pressure system scattered the rainshowers late Tuesday
while the high pressure area provided the cold air that caused the
rain to become mixed with sleet at times.
   Rain and sleet were reported from northeast Ohio into northwest
Pennsylvania. Snow flurries fell on Canton and Akron, Ohio, and
occasionally at Pittsburgh. Snow was falling over northwest lower
Michigan late Tuesday, with accumulations of up to an inch reported
in some areas.
   The high pressure was expected to bring light winds and cold
temperatures tonight to the upper Mississippi Valley and upper
Great Lakes into the lower Ohio Valley and lower Missouri River
Valley. Lows by sunrise were expected to be in the mid or upper 20s
across the upper Great Lakes and in the lower 30s across the lower
Missouri River Valley.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered over the Great Basin of
Nevada late Tuesday, bringing heavy local rain, including
three-quarters of an inch at both Austin, Nevada, and Cedar City in
western Utah.
   Indianapolis dropped to 28 degrees early today, tying the record
low for the date, which was set in 1876 and also tied the same date
last year.
   For today, scattered rain or snow showers were predicted from
Michigan across the eastern Great Lakes and western Pennsylvania
into northern New England, while widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms were expected over parts of the Southern Plateau.
High pressure was expected to provide pleasant weather across the
Plains and the Mississippi Valley.
   High temperatures were forecast to be in the 60s or 70s across
much of the nation east of the Rockies; in the 40s and 50s from the
upper Mississippi and Ohio valleys to North Carolina, the
mid-Atlantic coastal states and New England; the upper 30s over
northern Michigan and portions of the northern and central
Appalachians; the 80s over southern Florida, southern Texas, parts
of eastern Colorado and central Montana, and across interior
valleys of California; and in the 80s and 90s across the desert
Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 26
degrees at Duluth and International Falls, Minn., to 80 degrees at
Nellis Air Force Base near Las Vegas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 51 fair; Boston 46 fair; Buffalo 36 showers;
Charleston, S.C. 59 fair; Cincinnati 30 fair; Cleveland 41 partly
cloudy; Detroit 33 fair; Miami 71 fair; New York 47 fair;
Philadelphia 42 fair; Pittsburgh 37 cloudy; Portland, Maine 41
fair; Washington 49 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 42 fair; Chicago 39 windy; Dallas-Fort Worth
53 fair; Denver 49 fair; Des Moines 36 fair; Indianapolis 30 fair;
Kansas City 39 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 30 fair; Nashville 45
fair; New Orleans 64 foggy; St. Louis 43 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 52 fair; Anchorage 31 cloudy; Las Vegas 73
cloudy; Los Angeles 63 partly cloudy; Phoenix 78 fair; Salt Lake
City 55 cloudy; San Diego 65 cloudy; San Francisco 56 cloudy;
Seattle 57 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 39 partly cloudy; Toronto 34 showers.
</TEXT>
