<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Spain-Arabs     10-12 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Spain-Arabs,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Ambassadors Agree to Help Restore Toledo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOLEDO, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab ambassadors have agreed to help save
this city which served for centuries as the meeting ground for
Moslem, Jewish and Christian cultures, Mayor Jose Manuel Molina
said.
   Molina said Tuesday the ambassadors from Syria, Saudi Arabia,
Egypt, Morocco, Lebanon, Mauritania, the United Arab Emirates,
Jordan, Libya and the Arab League agreed to discuss their
assistance next month in Madrid.
   The Toledo Foundation seeks restoration of the medieval heart of
the city 40 miles southwest of Madrid in time for 1992, when Toledo
will be the site of a yearlong commemoration of Spain's
tri-cultural past.
   World Jewish organizations also will take part in the
restoration as well as the 1992 commemoration, which coincides with
the 500th anniversary of Christopher Columbus's first voyage to the
New World _ and with the royal edict expelling Moslems and Jews
from Spain.
</TEXT>
