<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-Fire     10-12 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Fire,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arson-Caused Fire Damages Roman Catholic Church Headquarters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pre-dawn fire ripped through
the headquarters of South Africa's Roman Catholic Church in
Pretoria today. Authorities said it was arson.
   There were no injuries, but a nun and three other people staying
in the building were rescued by firemen after they were trapped on
a balcony by the flames.
   ``If it hadn't been for the fast action of the fire department,
we would have all been killed,'' said one of the four, Rob Lambert.
   It was the second major attack in six weeks on the headquarters
of an anti-apartheid church organization. The main office of the
South African Council of Churches was devastated by a bomb Aug. 31.
   Police said four nearly empty containers of gasoline and
paraffin were found on the ground floor of Khanya House in
Pretoria, the headquarters of the Southern African Catholic Bishops
Conference.
   The fire seriously damaged the organization's archives and print
shop on the ground floor and also caused damage on two upper floors.
   Police said a mini-bus with 11 people inside, including blacks
and whites, was seen by a policeman at the building shortly before
the fire broke out about 2 a.m. The vehicle had a false license
plate, police said.
   No arrests have been made in connection with the bombing of
Khotso House in Johannesburg, which housed the offices of the
council of churches and other organizations seeking an end to
apartheid, or the white-minority goverment's policy of racial
segregation.
   Leading activists have suggested the bombing was carried out
either by right-wing vigilantes or by a covert security force unit.
   The Catholic Church in South Africa is predominantly black. Two
weeks ago, the Catholic bishops distributed a pastoral letter
suggesting Catholics consider not voting in this month's nationwide
municipal elections.
   Activists say the elections for segregated local councils serve
only to entrench apartheid and will bring blacks no closer to
obtaining voting rights on the national level.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
