<DOCNO> AP881012-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 0617EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PeanutsProtest     10-12 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peanuts Protest,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Peanuts' Cartoon Changed Following Protest By Indian Parents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Television has deleted references to
American Indians as ``savages'' from a Thanksgiving-related
``Peanuts'' cartoon because an Indian parents group here
complained, a network official said.
   Carol Altieri, vice president of program practices for the CBS
Broadcast Group in Hollywood, said the producer's notes on the
script to ``The Mayflower Voyagers'' indicate that the word
``savages'' has been dropped throughout.
   The ``Peanuts'' special is scheduled to air Oct. 21 as part of
an animated historical miniseries called ``This Is America Charlie
Brown.''
   Ms. Altieri said the change was made because of concerns raised
by the Concerned American Indian Parents group of Minneapolis and
the CBS affiliate in Minneapolis, WCCO-TV. She said no other
affiliates had complained.
   The network distributed scripts of the cartoon and teaching
instructions to affiliate stations, which distributed them to
participating schools, said Joanne Brokaw-Livesey, director of
educational and community services for CBS in New York.
   Because the script referred to Indians as ``savages'' in at
least two places and included historical inaccuracies that gave
negative portrayals of Indians, WCCO-TV shortened the script and
revised the teaching instructions, said Tom Cousins, a consultant
for the station.
   He said the material being given to 52,000 students at about 150
schools in Minnesota was changed to ``foster cultural sensitivity.''
   ``We're going to go with the revised one to remove anything that
would be insensitive to the Native Americans,'' Cousins said. ``It
was corresponding with myths rather than actuality.''
   He said the cartoon wrongly portrays Indians as giving ``war
whoops'' and unfairly portrays the Indian Squanto, who befriended
the Pilgrims, as a ``grateful slave'' who learned English after
being kidnapped by an Englishman who took him away to Europe.
   ``The war whoops are a myth of the old-time cowboy movies,''
Cousins said.
   In the finished program, Squanto says, ``I served a wonderful
man who also had me learn English. And that man finally gave me my
freedom to sail back here to my land.''
   The network-distributed script was shortened by Cousins so that
it ends with the Mayflower's arrival in North America, and the
teaching instructions were revised to suggest ways for teachers to
discuss myths surrounding Thanksgiving, Cousins said. A committee
that included an American Indian and a human relations professor at
St. Cloud State University agreed on the changes, he said.
   Ms. Altieri said CBS will air the program despite objections
from Concerned American Indian Parents.
   ``We're not stereotyping Indians or Native Americans here as
much as we are telling the story of a man (Squanto) who, through
extreme adverse experiences in his life, brought those experiences
to bear in becoming the salvation of people who landed in this
strange land,'' Ms. Altieri said.
   She said the actual program may not come off as harsh as the
advance script in the eyes of those who have complained.
   ``I think it might be a mistake to make the judgement prior to
seeing the program,'' she said.
   But Phil St. John, a member of the parents group in Minneapolis,
said he still objects to airing of the program.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881012-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 0622EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea     10-12 0504</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korea Ready To Make Concessions In Talks With North Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korean delegates, elated by
their country's success as Olympic host, will be more flexible when
they resume talks with North Korea Thursday on reunification,
officials said today.
   The talks at the border truce site of Panmunjom will be the
first meeting between parliamentary officials of the two Koreas
since the 1988 Summer Olympics ended in Seoul on Oct. 2.
   ``The Olympics have given us new impetus. We will be more
flexible,'' a senior government party official said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   The two sides began discussions Aug. 21 on possible formal talks
between the two Koreas' parliaments but made no major progress in
four meetings. In the fourth session Aug. 26, each accused the
other of blocking agreement, but they agreed to resume discussions
after the Olympics.
   The two sides differed widely over both the agenda and format of
the proposed formal talks. North Korea demanded a joint meeting of
the nearly 1,000 members of the two Koreas' parliaments, but South
Korea sought a smaller meeting.
   ``We will be flexible about the two pending issues and make new
proposals,'' the South Korean official said.
   At Thursday's meeting, he said, South Korea would suggest that
each side send up to 100 delegates to the main talks. Previously,
South Korea had sought to limit the number to 25.
   In its flexible stand on the agenda, the official said, South
Korea may agree to discuss a North Korean proposal that the
parliaments of the two sides issue a joint ``non-aggression
statement.''
   North Korea said any such statement should call, among other
things, for the withdrawal of the 42,000 U.S. troops stationed in
South Korea and drastic arms reductions by the two Koreas.
   South Korea had sought to sign a non-aggression treaty rather
than a non-aggression statement, which has no binding force, but
Pyongyang officials maintained that the two Koreas are not separate
states and thus cannot conclude a treaty.
   South Korean officials said they would take a ``soft stand'' and
try to accommodate North Korean proposals as much as possible, but
they did not say whether they would consider the North Korean
proposal for a pullout of the American troops and arms reductions.
   Other topics expected to arise at the meeting include a recent
call by South Korean President Roh Tae-woo for summit talks with
North Korean ruler Kim Il Sung, the official said.
   In a major policy speech on Oct. 4, Roh renewed a call for
summit talks with Kim and said he was ready to end rivalry and
confrontation on the Korean peninsula. The summit, if held, would
be the first since the Korean peninsula was divided in 1945 into
the Communist North and capitalist South.
   In response to Roh's proposal, North Korea's official radio said
on Sunday the proposed summit would not be possible unless South
Korea accepted Pyongyang's pre-conditions, the South Korean news
agency Naewoe reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881012-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 0633EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StormJoan     10-12 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Storm Joan,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tropical Storm Joan Moves Toward Caribbean</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 10th tropical storm of the Atlantic hurricane
season gradually strengthened as it followed a course that could
threaten the Lesser Antilles in two or three days.
   At 6 a.m. EDT today, Tropical Storm Joan was centered near 12.2
north latitude and 50.8 west longitude, or about 575 miles east of
Barbados, moving west-northwest at 15 mph, the National Hurricane
Center said.
   The system has maximum sustained winds of 50 mph with some
stronger gusts, according to the center.
   Little change in strength was expected today, and Joan was
expected to maintain the same speed and direction for the next 24
hours, the center said.
   Joan, first spotted by satellite late last week in the
mid-Atlantic, was upgraded from a depression to a tropical storm
Tuesday. Tropical storms are named when sustained winds reach 39
mph and hurricanes when winds hit 74 mph.
   Four hurricanes have formed this season, including Hurricane
Gilbert, which killed more than 300 people and caused billions of
dollars damage as it ravaged Jamaica, the Cayman Islands and Mexico.
   The hurricane season runs from June to November.
</TEXT>
