<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0460 10-12 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0460,0708</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grenade Thrown At Car, Soldiers Blow Up Or Seal Nine Houses Of
Activists</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with grenade attack in Gaza, house
demolitions in Nablus, Moslem leader arrested, details. CHANGES
byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians hurled a hand grenade at a
civilian Israeli car in the occupied Gaza Strip today, and in the
West Bank town of Nablus Israeli soldiers blew up or sealed nine
houses of suspected activists, the army said.
   Nablus, a city of 120,000, was under army-imposed curfew for the
sixth straight day today following a bloody clash last week in
which troops shot and killed four people and wounded 21. Residents
said they were running short of food.
   No injuries were reported in the grenade attack on Nasir Street
in the center of Gaza City, the second such assault in two days.
   On Tuesday, a Palestinian tossed a hand grenade at an Israeli
patrol in Gaza City and wounded two soldiers, the army said.
   The two Arab attacks were among only a few involving firearms in
the 10-months-old uprising against Israeli rule in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip, occupied by Israel since 1967. Six Israelis and 295
Palestinian have died in the uprising that began Dec. 8.
   The army said the grenade today missed its target. Israel army
radio and an Arab reporter in Gaza said troops closed the area and
started searching house to house for suspects after the morning
incident.
   In Tuesday's attack, a Soviet-made grenade was thrown at the
first vehicle in a military patrol from the grounds of Nasir Eye
Hospital in a residential section of Gaza. Soldiers found the
grenade pin and handle in the courtyard of the hospital, an army
spokesman said on condition of anonymity.
   Two army sergeants were lightly wounded in their legs.
   Also in Gaza City, the army today detained Ibrahim Al Yazouri,
an Arab pharmacist and the secretary-general of the Mujama
Al-Islami, or Islamic Grouping, a radical religious group. Al
Yazouri is believed to be the operational leader of Moslem
fundamentalists in the Gaza Strip.
   Israel radio quoted Arab reports as saying other fundamentalist
leaders were detained in the last few days.
   The arrests followed a rapprochement between radical Moslems and
pro-PLO activists, declared in the latest leaflets of the
underground Moslem Hamas movement and the PLO-linked Unified
National Leadership of the Uprising.
   In the West Bank's largest city, Nablus, soldiers blew up four
houses and sealed off five others in the Old City and the Ras
El-Ein neighborhood, the army said.
   It said the houses belonged to Arabs suspected of being members
in a nine-man squad of ``strike forces'' that enforced orders by
underground uprising leaders. It said several members of the squad
were arrested.
   They were accused of hacking and stabbing to death three Arabs
suspected of collaborating with Israel in Nablus in September, of
beating other Palestinians and of inciting riots.
   The squad's members belonged to Fatah, the mainstream faction of
the PLO, the army said.
   Nablus residents, under an army-imposed curfew, told The
Associated Press telephone lines in the Old City were cut off for
the last four days.
   Burning tires were seen in the streets of the Old City, and some
Palestinians climbed the rooftops to whistle and shout Islamic
slogans as an army helicopter circled overhead, those reached by
relephone in nearby areas said.
   ``There are many soldiers in the Old City, some of them also on
the roofs, and many army cars,'' one woman said. ``We saw the smoke
from the explosion when they destroyed a house.''
   Nablus residents also complained of food shortages caused by the
curfew.
   ``People are starving. This is the sixth day of curfew. We need
help. The babies are without milk. I called all the foreign
embassies and we hope they will help us,'' said prominent Nablus
businessman Said Kennaan.
   The army denied the charges. An army spokeswoman said Red Cross
and hospital officials were permitted to move freely in the city.
The curfew was lifted for two hours Tuesday to allow residents to
buy food, she said.
</TEXT>
