<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Eiffel Strike,0135</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Ends; Tourists Once Again On Top Of Paris</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tourists could once again get a bird's eye view of
Paris today after workers at the Eiffel Tower ended a four-day
strike.
   The 100-year-old steel tower, France's top tourist attraction,
had been closed to visitors since Saturday morning because of the
strike by the 130 employees.
   Early today, a union strike committee announced that all the
strikers' key demands had been met, including an increase of about
30 cents in the $4.60 hourly wage.
   The Eiffel Tower stands 984 feet high, with three observation
levels, and is one of the few tall structures looking out over the
rooftops of a city of five- and six-story buildings. When it opened
in 1888, it was the world's tallest structure.
</TEXT>
