<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GandhiAssassination 1stLd-Writethru a0508 10-12 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gandhi Assassination, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0508,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Warrants Issued For Two Sikhs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, `Both men still...' with new graf to</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   UPDATE with two Sikhs appealing for mercy. Picks up 6th graf pvs,
`The convictions...'
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge today approved the execution of
two Sikhs convicted in the 1984 assassination of Prime Minister
Indira Gandhi, news reports said.
   District Judge S.C. Jain signed the ``black warrants''
authorizing the hanging of Satwant Singh and Kehar Singh, the
United News of India said.
   The warrants were delivered to the superintendent of the
maximum-security Tihar Central Jail in New Delhi, where the two men
are being held, the news agency reported.
   The execution date was not immediately disclosed, the news
agency said.
   Shortly after the warrants were signed, lawyers for both men
appealed for mercy to President Ramaswamy Venkataraman, who must
rule within 90 days, a Home Ministry spokesman said on condition of
anonymity.
   The convictions and death sentences for both men has been upheld
and the Supreme Court has rejected their appeals. The conviction
and death sentence of a third man, Balbir Singh, was overturned in
August for lack of evidence.
   Mrs. Gandhi was shot and killed in the garden of her home on
Oct. 31, 1984, by two of her Sikh bodyguards, Satwant Singh and
Beant Singh.
   Both were involved in a gun battle with other security guards
minutes after the assassination, and Beant Singh died of bullet
wounds.
   The two are not related. Singh, which means lion in the Punjabi
language, is part of every Sikh's name by doctrine of the faith.
   Kehar Singh, Beant Singh's maternal uncle, was arrested on Nov.
30, 1984, and charged with conspiracy in the case.
   The assassination was apparently in revenge for an army raid
Mrs. Gandhi ordered four months earlier on the Golden Temple, the
holiest Sikh shrine, to counter separatist militants entrenched
inside. At least 1,200 died in the raid, most of them Sikhs.
   After an eight-month trial in a makeshift courtroom at Tihar
Central Jail, Satwant Singh was convicted of assassinating Mrs.
Gandhi. Kehar Singh and Balbir Singh were found guilty of aiding
the conspiracy.
   The Delhi High Court upheld the convictions and death sentences
on Dec. 3, 1986. The Supreme Court on Aug. 3 also confirmed the
death sentences of Satwant Singh and Kehar Singh, but acquitted
Balbir Singh.
</TEXT>
