<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Algeria 3rdLd-Writethru   10-12 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Algeria, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0511,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Of Emergency Ends, Curfew Lifted</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to CORRECT time of curfew in 7th graf.
Pick up 8th pvs, `Islamic fundamentlists...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tanks and troops disappeared from the
streets of Algiers at dawn today when the government abruptly
lifted a state of emergency imposed during violent nationwide
protests last week.
   Armored personnel carriers and tanks rumbled away from public
buildings and main intersections at 5 a.m. in this Mediterranean
port city. Only the Defense Ministry and other military
installations were manned by soldiers.
   But more than 3,000 looters and agitators arrested in the last
hours of the state of emergency still were being held in the police
school at El Biar and elsewhere.
   The government acknowledged that at least 180 people were killed
nationwide in the past week, but unofficial counts placed the death
toll at more than 500.
   More than 1,000 people were said to have been injured, mostly by
machine-gun fire directed at crowds of demonstrators.
   Shops were open today, and government offices, public services
and Algiers' vital harbor were functioning normally.
   A 10 p.m. to 6 a.m. curfew was also lifted, effective this
morning.
   Islamic fundamentalists, recognizable among the generally
European-clad population of Algiers by their flowing white robes,
could not be found this morning.
   They had sought to take over the spontaneous protests against
high prices and a government austerity program, and their calls for
demonstrations were widely followed.
   President Chadli Bendjedid promised in a nationwide television
address Monday to meet demands for economic and political reform.
He said there would be a purge of those responsible for the crisis,
but he gave no specifics.
   There was speculation Mohamed Cherif Messaadia,
secretary-general of the National Liberation Front, the sole legal
political party, would be among those purged.
   The party and its boss have not spoken publicly since the crisis
began Oct. 4. Political analysts said the party's authority has
been seriously reduced by the riots.
   In his speech, Bendjedid made no mention of the party, saying
political reforms would be publicly debated and perhaps submitted
to a referendum.
   Bendjedid's speech was widely seen as weak, but the government
organized ``spontaneous'' demonstrations of support for it
throughout the country.
   Government officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, say
the official death toll of about 180 was low, but they also
contended that reports of up to 500 dead were exaggerated.
   Reliable accounts from hospital, medical and police sources
indicated at least 400 people died and more than 1,000 were injured
in the biggest crisis faced by the government since its
independence from France in 1962.
   Among those killed in violence Monday was Sid Ali Benmechiche, a
senior editor at the official Algerie Presse Service, said
diplomatic and family sources.
   The government announced Friday that 900 people were arrested,
but sources following judicial proceedings said more than 3,000
people were in custody.
   In the eastern city of Annaba, trials began Tuesday for people
arrested during the riots, and six demonstrators were sentenced to
prison terms ranging from four to eight years, the Algerian League
of Human Rights said in Algiers.
   According to lawyers present in the courtroom, the charges were
vandalism, sabotage and attacks on government and private property.
   Food shortages, soaring prices and low wages were among the
complaints when the protests began in Algiers and more than a dozen
provincial cities.
   Demonstrators targeted an austerity program introduced by
Bendjedid in January. Measures include cutting food subsidies,
reducing the workforce at some nationalized industries and giving
those industries more autonomy.
   Algeria, which has a Soviet-style centrally directed economy,
has been hurt by the crash of oil prices. More than 95 percent of
the north African country's exports come from oil and natural gas.
</TEXT>
