<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Prices 1stLd-Writethru   10-12 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0512,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Modernize And Streamline, Don't Raise Food Subsidies, Economist
Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with 10 grafs to ADD report of West German credit to
Soviet Union. Pick up 9th pvs, `That's half...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet economist says boosting food subsidies
will only fuel inflation but that modernizing agriculture will help
reduce waste that costs $96 billion annually.
   Kim N. Khmelkov, an economist and director of a Moscow-area
farming enterprise, said that to finance more subsidies, the
government probably will have to take the money from state-run
enterprises, the Communist Party daily Pravda reported Tuesday.
   Those enterprises in turn would be forced to raise prices to
make up for the loss, he said.
   ``In a word, it's a race in a circle. (Price increases) would
not strengthen the economy, but destabilize it. And the
destabilization would start with those with the lowest incomes,''
Pravda quoted him as saying.
   Many Soviet economists have said the prices of basic commodities
must be increased in the next few years to make the economy more
efficient. President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has promised consumers
will be compensated for any price increases.
   Khmelkov said that officials must instead keep strict control
over prices and end vast inefficiencies in agriculture.
   As an example, he said a new kind of milking machine that could
easily be produced in the Soviet Union would increase milk
production by 10 percent to 15 percent while saving $4 billion
across the country.
   In West Germany, financial sources said a consortium of banks
plans to sign a $1.6 billion credit agreement for the Soviet Union.
The New York Times said Soviet officials hope to use the money to
improve the nation's food processing and consumer goods industries.
   Deutsche Bank, West Germany's largest commercial bank, is
heading the consortium involved in the agreement, which would be
the biggest Western credit line ever to the Soviet Union.
   Scientists have calculated that inefficiency and waste in Soviet
agriculture account for $96 billion a year, Khmelkov said.
   ``That's half the cost of what is grown in the fields and
farms,'' he said.
   The government spends $105 billion a year to keep the prices of
milk, meat, bread and other food products low in keeping with
long-term policies officials have espoused as proof of the
superiority of their economic system.
   Khmelkov said his enterprise produces beef costing $2.50 a pound
but it is sold in stores at government prices 80 cents lower.
   The economist said it costs other farms twice as much to produce
the same amount of meat and the state picks up the difference
between the cost of production and the retail price.
   Nevertheless, some Moscow consumers cannot afford to buy meat,
which is not always available, he said.
   In addition to considering retail price increases, Gorbachev has
been trying to trim the top-heavy management of the state-run
agricultural system. The Soviet president also is trying to
encourage state farms to give more responsibility to families and
small groups of workers, allowing them to earn more money for
better work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
