<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WrongVictim     10-12 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wrong Victim,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Hears TV Newscast Report Her Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKFORD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paula Ann Moore was home watching
television when a local newscast flashed her photograph on the
screen and reported that she had been murdered.
   A Paula Ann Moore had indeed been killed the previous day. She
was from Rockford, 18 years old and black. Two local television
stations illustrated the story by using the ninth-grade school
photograph of the Paula Ann Moore who was alive, from Rockford, 18
_ and white.
   ``I knew that a Paula Ann Moore had been killed,'' Ms. Moore
said Tuesday. ``But then the news showed my picture. I didn't know
what to do. All I could think was that everybody, my friends and
relatives, would think I was dead.
   ``I called my mom right away. I guess I kind of freaked out.''
   Paula was not the only one upset. Friends and relatives began
calling her mother, Rebecca, Friday after reading newspaper
accounts _ minus the photograph _ of the slaying.
   ``The phone started ringing at 7 a.m.'' Rebecca Moore said. ``I
spent the whole morning explaining to people that our Paula was
fine.''
   Mrs. Moore was so busy making calls that she missed the 5 p.m.
newscasts. She sat down to watch the 10 p.m. news.
   ``I knew it wasn't my daughter who was dead, but seeing her
picture like that and hearing the story, I was shaking all over,''
said Mrs. Moore.
   She said her daughter's photo accompanied the murder story on
two local stations, WIFR and WREX. Spokesmen for both channels
confirmed that they had used the wrong photograph. The two stations
apologized for the error during Tuesday newscasts, Mrs. Moore said.
   Mrs. Moore said officials from Jefferson High School, where her
daughter attended classes, told her they did not release the
picture.
   Linda Dawson, spokeswoman for the Rockford School District, said
no one from administrative headquarters released the photo either.
She speculated that the television stations obtained a school
yearbook independently.
   The real victim was found dead Thursday in a small storage shed
behind a Rockford home. Police said the woman, who had been a
live-in baby sitter at the home for the last month, was reported
missing by her family several weeks ago.
   Bennie F. Jones, described by police as an acquaintance of the
victim, turned himself in Thursday night. He has been charged with
first-degree murder.
</TEXT>
