<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 0928EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Afghanistan     10-12 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghanistan,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Stresses Commitment To Ending War</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Mohammad Hasan Sharq
said today his government is committed to seeking a negotiated
settlement to end the war with Moslem guerrillas.
   Sharq also said he hoped the U.S. presidential election next
month will lead to a change in Washington's policy toward the
U.S.-supported guerrillas.
   ``We hope that the smell of blood of innocent people will no
longer be to the liking of the leaders of the United States of
America,'' Sharq said during a 90-minute meeting with Western
reporters.
   He made no new offers that might persuade the guerrillas to stop
fighting the Soviet-backed Afghan government, but he indicated a
preference for making deals with local guerrilla commanders inside
the country rather than trying to persuade their Pakistani-based
leaders to give up the fight.
   ``If we are not able to have ways of negotiating with all of
them, we will have negotiations with some of them,''the 63-year-old
prime minister said. ``Those who are sharing the miseries of the
people of Afghanistan will come first.''
   The Afghan government has been pursuing a policy of trying to
establish what it calls ``coalition governments'' at the provincial
level. If successful, this strategy could neutralize _ on a
piecemeal basis _ the guerrillas by persuading them to lay down
their arms in exchange for local power.
   The prime minister, whose remarks in Dari were translated into
English by government officials, urged the United States and
Pakistan to stop arming the guerrillas.
   He dismissed any similarity between the United States' arming of
the guerrrillas and the Soviet Union's resupplying of the Afghan
army. He said the Kremlin has been arming the Afghan government for
35 years.
   American aid to the guerrillas began in earnest when Soviet
troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to support the
communist government after a coup.
   Soviet troops started withdrawing from Afghanistan on May 15
under terms of an agreement reached in Geneva. The withdrawal is
now half completed, and the remaining Soviet soldiers _ estimated
at 50,000 to 60,000 _ are to be gone by Feb. 15, 1989.
</TEXT>
