<DOCNO> AP881012-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 0938EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-RadarBase     10-12 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Radar Base,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Invites UNESCO To Use Disputed Radar Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze invited
UNESCO today to create an international scientific group to begin
space research at a controversial radar station in the Soviet Union.
   He said Soviet scientists were ready to establish contacts with
the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization to carry out ``peaceful research at an absolutely
peaceful radar installation'' at Krasnoyarsk, 2,000 miles east of
Moscow.
   In a speech Sept. 16, Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
proposed that a center for international cooperation in the
exploration of space be set up at the radar station.
   The United States has said the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile
Treaty it signed with the Soviet Union would permit the Krasnoyarsk
station to be used for space tracking, but contends that evidence
suggests it actually is being used for missile detection and
warning, a violation of the ABM treaty.
   Shevardnadze, on the last day of a three-day official visit to
France, spoke to a special session of UNESCO's governing Executive
Board.
   He said the most important problem facing the 158-nation
Paris-based organization is to prevent the scientific and
technological revolution from alienating people who depend on it to
improve their lives.
   He said it was ``immoral and dangerous,'' particularly for
industrialized nations, to keep developing nations which constitute
a majority in U.N. organizations at the periphery of scientic
development.
   The United States and Britain left the organization respectively
at the end of 1984 and 1985 after charging that UNESCO was overly
political, free-spending and poorly managed. At the time, the
United States called the organization ``a champion of extreme
statist philosophies.''
   Shevardnadze said the Soviet Union bore a share of the
responsibility for the departure of the two Western nations.
   ``Sometimes we were also acting on the principle of a `tooth for
a tooth' under the pressure of confrontation,'' he said.
   He said ``excessive introduction of ideological dimensions in
UNESCO debates ... undermined the principle of tolerance that is
fundamental to international cooperation.''
   Shevardnadze was welcomed to UNESCO by Director General Federico
Mayor, who said he was sure the United States, Britain and
Singapore, which also left UNESCO, would heed an appeal
Shevardnadze made at the U.N. General Assemly last month to
reconsider.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
