<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CollegeTakeover     10-12 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-College Takeover,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students End Occupation at Goddard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLAINFIELD, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A handful of students who occupied an
administration building at Goddard College for nearly two days have
ended their vigil after narrowing a 26-item list of wide-ranging
demands to one.
   The three remaining students ended their blockade on the second
floor of the Community Center on Tuesday. Seven others had left the
building Monday night.
   The final demand agreed to before the protesters ended their
occupation was that the college fully disclose its financial
records, something Goddard President Jack Lindquist said was
already in effect.
   ``It's a funny issue to have as an issue,'' he said. ``Everybody
knows they can come to me for that information. I'm glad it wasn't
ending homelessness in America; that would have been harder to do.''
   After the barricades were removed Tuesday, about 100 students
and faculty met to discuss the issues that had been raised by the
protesters, which ranged from school issues such as increasing
student participation in the college's administration to more
global concerns, such as freeing South African activist Nelson
Mandela and ending homelessness in America.
   Before the barricades were removed, Zenzile Madikinea, a South
African and former Goddard student who organized the protest with
student Dan Abrams, cried softly.
   ``Because we are non-violent and don't want anybody to get hurt,
we are coming down to press all our demands. We care about the
students and respect the process,'' he said.
   Lindquist said the Community Life Committee, composed of
students and faculty, would decide whether any punitive action
would be taken against the students.
</TEXT>
