<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Yugoslavia 3rdLd-Writethru   10-12 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0543,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Party Chief Warns of Rampant Anti-Socialism</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 4th graf, `His comments...' to ADD that Suvar is Croat.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party chief today said
ethnic rallies that ignited nationwide unrest are an example of
couterrevolutionary tendencies running rampant in Yugoslavia,
state-run media reported.
   ``What the counterrevolution in Kosovo has been trying to do
(constitutes) ...the most brutal threat to socialism in
Yugoslavia,'' Stipe Suvar told the ruling Politburos of Yugoslavia
and Kosovo, an autonomous province in the republic of Serbia.
   But he added, ``Anti-socialist, and if you want,
counterrevolutionary tendencies, have grown in all of Yugoslavia so
that the Kosovo reality, in comparison, is not a particularly
isolated phenomenon.''
   Suvar, an ethnic Croat, spoke in Pristina, the capital of
Kosovo. His comments were reported by the state-run Tanjug news
agency.
   At a meeting Tuesday, Serbia's Communist Party chief, Slobodan
Milosevic, defended the Kosovo rallies and vowed he would assign
blame for the national crisis during a meeting of national leaders
next week.
   But Milosevic was criticized for failing to condemn calls for
violent solutions to tensions in Kosovo, where Serbs claim
discrimination by the Albanian majority.
   During the Belgrade meeting of the Central Committee of the
Serbian Communist Party, members demanded three Kosovo communists
be ousted from the national Central Committee for failing to
resolve tensions.
   The Belgrade and the Pristina gatherings were key preludes to
the crucial national Central Committee gathering Monday.
   The growing friction between ethnic groups and general
dissatisfaction with the nation's economy has led to widespread
public protests, strikes and political manuevering that add up to
Yugoslavia's most serious social unrest since World War II.
   Milosevic, hailed by Serbs as the heir apparent to the late
President Josip Broz Tito, is expected to have a major showdown
with national party leaders over the Kosovo dispute and the broader
protests over Yugoslavia's economy.
   Milosevic on Tuesday defended the nationalist rallies but said
they should not become a regular practice. The meeting was
broadcast on state radio and television in a break with usual
practice.
   He said Monday's meeting should be ``a confrontation with the
responsibility for the crisis.''
   The Serbian Central Committee, which has more than 100 members,
decided with only six negative votes to demand dismissals of two
ethnic Albanians and one Slav from their Kosovo party posts and
their expulsion from the national Central Committee.
   One of the three is Azem Vlasi, an ethnic Albanian and former
party chief in Kosovo, where predominantly Moslem Albanians make up
90 percent of the population. Most Slavs who live in the province _
Serbs and Montenegrins _ are Christian.
   Yugoslavia consists of six republics and two autonomous
provinces, each with its own government and party structure. The
autonomous provinces, Kosovo and Vojvodina, are part of Serbia but
not fully subject to its control.
   The decentralized system of government and collective federal
presidency were devised in Tito's 1974 constitution to prevent one
republic from gaining sway over the others, but has resulted in an
ineffective government.
   Suvar has said broad personnel changes would be made during
Monday's national party meeting.
   Ethnic tension in Kosovo has increased sharply in recent weeks
because of rallies by hundreds of thousands of Serbian
nationalists. Albanians deny discrimination against Slavs and say
the problems are economic.
   Mustafa Sefcet, an ethnic Albanian member of the Serbian Central
Committee, on Tuesday sharply criticized such rally chants as ``We
want arms'' and the calls for Vlasi's death.
   ``These are anti-socialist slogans which do not meet with sharp
condemnation, except for sharp condemnation by all nations and
nationalities'' in regions outside Serbia, he said.
   ``One should, on the spot, unmask all forces standing behind''
the slogans, he said in apparent criticism of Milosevic.
   Belgrade radio reported three more rallies Tuesday. It said
50,000 people demonstrated at Leskovac, 90 miles south of Belgrade;
20,000 massed at nearby Cuprija and another large rally was
reported at Valjevo, 50 miles south of Belgrade.
</TEXT>
