<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WaterMainBreak     10-12 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Water Main Break,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Water Main Break Disrupts Subway and Street Traffic in Manhattan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 200,000 commuters were derailed this
morning when a broken water main flooded subway tunnels and closed
some streets around a key midtown Manhattan subway hub, officials
said.
   Some sections of the subway system were under eight feet of
water and the water was lapping over some platforms, said Transit
Authority spokesman Bob Slovak.
   The break in the 36-inch main was reported at 2 a.m., said
Martha Holstein, a spokeswoman for the city Department of
Environmental Protection. It took about five hours for city crews
to close three water mains to isolate the break.
   ``It's no longer gushing in the area,'' Holstein said. ``It's
still very wet.''
   The broken main carries water into smaller distribution mains,
which connect to buildings.
   Transit Authority spokesman Bob Previdi said some 200,000
commuters were affected as train service on some lines was halted
for up to four hours before the trains could be rerouted.
   Holstein said water service was expected to be restored to the
affected areas _ between Broadway and Eighth Avenue and 56th and
60th streets, near the southwest corner of Central Park _ within
``a matter of hours.''
   The size of the actual break and its cause had not yet been
determined, she said.
   ``Subway vibrations, heavy traffic, a number of factors can
affect water mains in addition to age or freezing weather, so it's
very unclear what would have caused this,'' she said.
   Motorists were advised to avoid the area, said a police
spokesman, Sgt. Edward Burns.
</TEXT>
