<2ND_LINE>PM-Alien House,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Agents Find 91 People _ Most Of Them Immigrants _ In Hideout House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FULLERTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration agents say they found 91
people crammed inside a stuffy, three-bedroom house and garage
believed to be used by smugglers of illegal aliens to imprison
those who couldn't pay the smuggling fee.
   All of the people were arrested, including 14 booked for
investigation of taking money from illegal immigrants in exchange
for transporting them into the United States, authorities said
Tuesday.
   The immigrants, found Sunday, were being held captive because
they had not paid the smugglers their passage fee of $250 to $500
each, said Tom Gaines, an assistant district director of the
Immigration and Naturalization Service.
   People stood by entrances to keep the aliens from escaping, he
said. He declined to given more details about the smuggling ring
and his operations.
   Nearly all the immigrants were Mexican men, but a young family
was among those taken away in the Sunday morning raid, authorities
and witnesses said. ``What really broke my heart was to see what
appeared to be a mother, a father and three kids,'' said Donna
Gimondo, a neighbor who watched the INS raid.
   ``One kid was about 3 to 6 months old and (the mother) had him
cuddled in a blanket. One was about 2{ to 3 years old and the
oldest was a 4-year-old boy. ... All were crying.''
