<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1043EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-OkeechobeeSuit     10-12 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Okeechobee Suit,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds Sue State, Water Managers Over Okeechobee-Everglades
Pollution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. attorney's office today sued state and
local water resources agencies, seeking to force them to end
pollution of the Everglades and Lake Okeechobee.
   The five-count federal complaint says the agencies have failed
to protect water quality and prevent water pollution as required by
state and federal law.
   ``Lake Okeechobee and the Everglades are unique environmental
treasures,'' said U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen. ``The continued
degradation of the Everglades is a national tragedy.''
   The suit was filed against the South Florida Water Management
District, the Florida Department of Environmental Regulation and
the heads of those agencies.
   Lehtinen said the lawsuit seeks to stop water pollution
throughout the Kissimmee-Okeechobee-Everglades water system, since
pollution gathered by the system ends up in a national park and a
national wildlife refuge.
   Okeechobee, the nation's largest fresh-water lake outside of the
Great Lakes, has for years been receiving pollution, much of it in
the form of nutrient-laden runoffs from dairy farms along the
Kissimmee River Valley. The river, flowing from south of the
Orlando area, is a primary source of water for the lake.
   In turn, water from the lake flows into the Loxahatchee National
Wildlife Refuge, into Everglades National Park and to the
water-conservation areas that recharge the Biscayne aquifer,
southeastern Florida's primary water supply.
   Both state and federal laws are violated by allowing large
quantities of polluted water to enter the protected areas, Lehtinen
said.
   The state and the self-governing water district failed to
maintain legal water quality standards, operated pumps without a
permit and violated their contracts to supply clean water to the
national parks, the suit claims.
   Lehtinen stressed that the Everglades park provides sanctuary to
rare and endangered species of wildlife, including the Florida
panther, southern bald eagle, woodstork, American crocodile and
Cape Sable sparrow.
   The park requires low-nutrient, non-polluted water for the
survival of the species, he said, adding that without immediate
action, ``more and more wetlands will be lost.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
