<DOCNO> AP881012-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BabySwap     10-12 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Baby Swap,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Bows Out of Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI has ended its monthlong investigation
into allegations of a 1978 baby swap at a rural Florida hospital,
saying there was no evidence any federal laws were violated, an
agency spokesman said.
   ``We closed our case,'' FBI spokesman Russ Wood said Tuesday.
``Preliminary investigation failed to establish that there was a
violation of federal criminal statutes.''
   Wood declined to give details of the inquiry.
   The Pennsylvania couple who sought the probe, Ernest and Regina
Twigg, can ask state law enforcement officers to investigate, the
federal spokesman said, adding, ``That option is always available.''
   The Twiggs claim their newborn was stolen at Hardee Memorial
Hospital in Wauchula nearly 10 years ago. Mrs. Twigg maintains that
she gave birth to a healthy girl, but hospital workers sent her
home with a sickly child, then altered records to hide the swap.
   The couple say genetic blood tests this summer revealed that
Arlena, the child they raised, was not their real daughter. Arlena
suffered from a heart defect and died following surgery Aug. 23,
never knowing that doubts had been raised about her parentage.
   Last month, the Twiggs filed a $100 million suit against the
hospital and some of its employees and persuaded the FBI to
investigate to see if federal kidnapping laws had been violated.
   Records show that during its probe the FBI subpoenaed documents
from the hospital, and interviewed the Twiggs. They also talked
with the father of a Sarasota girl who the Twiggs claim was the
only other white girl born at Hardee Memorial during the time Mrs.
Twigg gave birth.
   The girl has not been identified to protect her from publicity.
   LaVonna Vice, one of the lawyers representing the Twiggs, said
she doesn't know why the federal investigation ended, but
speculated that it might show the child the Twiggs claim was stolen
was not taken out of Florida.
   Federal kidnapping law generally applies to victims taken across
state line. However, the law also states that keeping a victim more
than a day creates ``a rebuttal presumption'' that the victim was
transferred over state lines.
   The father of the 9{-year-old Sarasota girl said he doesn't know
what to think about the FBI departure from the case. He said he
cooperated with the agency and provided them with polygraph tests
results showing he knew nothing about an alleged swap. He claims
the Twiggs, of Langhorne, Pa., are wrong about his daughter's
identity.
</TEXT>
