<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0430,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Hopes To Complete Drug Bill Before Adjournment</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Top 4 grafs new with Byrd comments; picks up 2nd graf pvs,
The legislation.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd pleaded
with his colleagues today to complete work quickly on the $2.6
billion drug bill, and restrain themselves from trying to be ``the
John Wayne in the drug war.''
   Byrd, D-W.Va., indicated that Democratic and Republican
lawmakers have so far been unable to try to pare down the more than
100 amendments that may be introduced. Meetings were continuing,
but it was uncertain whether the Senate would begin debate on the
election-year bill today.
   Speaking on the Senate floor, Byrd cautioned senators against
introducing amendments aimed at ``trying to indicate who can be the
toughest, who can be the John Wayne in the drug war.
   ``We can all be tough, but we've got a good tough bill,'' he
said.
   The legislation would provide additional federal money for
treatment programs, new law enforcement officers and prisons. It
also would allow capital punishment for certain drug offenders who
commit murder, and toughen penalties for drug dealers who sell
their wares to children.
   The wide-ranging measure would distribute 60 percent of its
money to prevention and treatment programs, and 40 percent to law
enforcement.
   Even though the legislation is the joint product of Democrats
and Republicans, there are some lawmakers who want to strengthen
it, others who want to water it down and still others who wish to
attach unrelated language to it because it could be the last bill
Congress passes this year.
   Senators are ready to introduce amendments that would strip the
death penalty provision from the measure, limit the ability of
prisoners to appeal their sentences on technical grounds, permit
courts to accept some illegally seized evidence and force states to
conduct drug tests on drivers license applicants.
   Other amendments would apply sanctions against South Africa and
require containers of alcohol to carry warning labels. By some
counts, there are more than 100 amendments waiting in the wings.
   The clock is a factor because Congress is hoping to adjourn for
the year at week's end. For the last several days, some senators
and their aides have been trying to see if there is any way to
limit the number of amendments that would be offered.
   The House passed a strong version of the bill Sept. 22
containing the death penalty, but bearing many other tough
proposals the Senate bill lacks.
   One important provision that is absent from both is a mechanism
for paying for the programs created in the bill. Even though $1.4
billion is supposed to be spent in fiscal year 1989 _ which began
Oct. 1 _ legislators say the government only has $450 million left
in its coffers. The Senate has so far voted down efforts to raise
taxes or cut other spending programs to provide the missing $950
million.
   Even if the Senate passes a bill, House-Senate negotiators will
have to agree to a compromise version before it can be sent to
President Reagan for his signature.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
