<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SanJoseQuake     10-12 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-San Jose Quake,0186</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mild Quake in San Jose</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mild earthquake woke up some residents
early today and rattled a few windows, but there were no reports of
damage, officials said.
   The quake struck at 5:47 a.m. and measured 3.2 on the Richter
scale, according to the University of California Seismographic
Station. Its epicenter was about seven miles east of San Jose.
   ``It creaked a little and lasted three or four seconds,'' said
KCBS newsman Ken Bastida, whose office is on the 12th floor of a
downtown building.
   ``There was a slight shudder and that was it,'' said a city
telephone dispatcher who did not want to give her name. ``I wasn't
even sure it was an earthquake until the news people called.''
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number on the scale represents a
tenfold increase in the magnitude of an earthquake.
   A quake with a magnitude of 4.0 is capable of causing moderate
damage, while a quake of 6.0 can cause severe damage.
</TEXT>
