<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Czechoslovakia 1stLd-Writethru   10-12 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0446,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top-Level Changes Indicate Reform May Slow</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Leads with 7 grafs with new government appointed. Pick up 8th
pvs, `Adamec's main...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Gustav Husak today
appointed a new government after the premier and his Cabinet
resigned in a shake-up expected to slow the pace of reform.
   Husak appointed a new 20-member government, including Ladislav
Adamec to replace Lubomir Strougal as the federal premier, the
state-run CTK news agency said. The appointments amounted to a
rubber stamp of selections made Tuesday by the Communist Party's
Central Committee.
   Strougal, a key advocate of speedy economic and social reform,
was premier for 18 years. He resigned Monday during a meeting of
the Central Committee and also gave up his seat on the party's
ruling Politburo.
   Adamec, 62, was premier of the Czech Republic, one of the
nation's two republics. He is expected to be less insistent on
speedy reform than Strougal. The Czech Republic's Parliament today
chose Frantisek Pitra to replace Adamec as the republic's premier,
CTK said.
   The new government requires approval by the Federal Assembly, or
parliament, scheduled to meet in November. It was not immediately
clear what became of a caretaker government that was appointed
Tuesday.
   Speeches published after the Central Committee meeting made
clear that party leaders favor reforms but resist radical changes
in the economy, such as tampering with the socialist linchpin _
central planning.
   Warning of the potential for high inflation and unemployment
under rapid reform, the leadership backed personnel changes aimed
at pursuing a slower road to restructuring than that of the Soviets.
   Strougal, 63, was known to have championed thorough economic
reform similar to those being carried out in the Soviet Union under
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev. But Strougal's plans for innovative
changes were watered down by party conservatives.
   Adamec's main advantage appears to be that in the eyes of many
he is not associated with the brutal suppression that occurred
during the so-called ``crisis years'' of 1968-69 when then-party
chief Alexander Dubcek was purged in the wake of a Soviet-led
invasion.
   Party chief Milos Jakes, chief ideologist Jan Fojtik, and a
resolution published Tuesday made it clear that political change
like that in the Soviet Union has been ruled out for some time to
come.
   Fojtik denounced the ``radicalism'' of unidentified people in
Czechoslovakia, who are ``calling for a drastic reform with
bankruptcies and unemployment, rapid growth of prices of
foodstuffs, rents and of inflation.''
   Fojtik told reporters, ``We put emphasis on the leading role of
the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia in carrying out the
restructuring process.
   ``The economic reform is aimed at strengthening socialist
ownership relations,'' said Fojtik.
   As he met reporters, Fojtik claimed Strougal does not feel
healthy, is tired and ``is not really able to master the many
difficult task'' of premiership.
   Fojtik indicated that Strougal left the political scene in
anger, saying he will not even head the caretaker government.
   Fojtik and Jakes also stressed that despite some cautious
opening up in the arts, the party remains firmly opposed to
political liberalization, let alone the recognition of dissident
and nonconformist political and ecological groups.
   Without naming countries, the ideologist, who took over the
party portfolio from hard-line Politburo member Vasil Bilak, now in
charge of foreign policy, said Prague leaders are discouraged and
in fact appalled by reform setbacks in Hungary and Poland.
   Fojtik outlined some government changes Tuesday.
   He said Jaromir Johanes, first deputy foreign minister and a
former ambasssador to Canada and the United States, was nominated
to be the new foreign minister, replacing Bohuslav Chnoupek.
   Five new members, ages 43 to 56, were added to the Central
Committee Politburo, and Strougal and Peter Colotka stepped down.
Colotka also resigned as premier of the Slovakia republic.
   CTK said he was replaced by Ivan Knotek, 52, a newcomer to the
Politburo.
</TEXT>
