<DOCNO> AP881012-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 3Takes   10-12 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 3 Takes,0786</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers
throughout the nation.
   Oct. 10
   Kennebec Journal, Augusta, Maine, on the gas-guzzler boom:
   Last week, Secretary of Transportation James H. Burnley
announced that his department had again caved in to the demands of
the country's top two automakers and waived fuel economy
requirements for 1989 automobiles.
   Meanwhile, a new poll suggests that 90 percent of the public
believes government should require automakers to build more
fuel-efficient cars.
   The survey respondents know something the Department of
Transportation apparently doesn't.
   Oil may be cheap and plentiful at the moment, but the situation
can't last. So it makes sense to keep producing more fuel-efficient
cars, and cutting hazardous air pollution in the bargain.
   GM and Ford aren't doing that. Since the Reagan administration
signaled its willingness to agree to any figure the big automakers
came up with, they've put efficiency on the back burner,
strenuously pushing a new generation of ``muscle'' cars, for which
they have little foreign competition.
   That may boost profits in the short term, but makes little sense
in the long run _ precisely the condition the government fuel
standards were supposed to address.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 10
   The Seattle Times on sheltering the homeless:
   The federal government's benign neglect in evaluating surplus
government property that could be suitable for sheltering the
homeless has been given a needed jolt by a United States District
Court judge in Washington, D.C.
   It has been 15 months since Congress passed and President Reagan
signed the McKinney Homeless Assistance Act, a piece of legislation
that has been strangled in part by bureaucratic inaction.
   Among other things, the act requires federal agencies to turn
over buildings and land suitable for sorely needed shelters to
local governments and non-profit agencies. Implementation of the
act has lagged ludicrously. ...
   (The judge) lamented:
   ``Pitifully few of the numerous unused federal properties are
being evaluated for their suitability to assist the homeless and
those that are found to be suitable are not being made available.''
   It defies logic that only a dozen surplus federal properties
exist across the country as possible shelters for an estimated 3
million homeless Americans.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 10
   Los Angeles Daily News on George Bush, Michael Dukakis and the
ACLU:
   George Bush may turn out to be the best friend the American
Civil Liberties Union has had since the red-baiting Sen. Joe
McCarthy. Bush has made the ACLU into a cause celebre.
   The day after the first presidential debate, at which Bush
quoted an earlier remark by Michael Dukakis (that the Democratic
presidential nominee is ``a card-carrying member of the ACLU''),
the organization's president told the New York Times that the group
had gotten hundreds of phone calls from people interested in
joining. ...
   Dan Quayle may call the ACLU ``the criminal defendant's best
friend.'' But since people in this country are innocent until
proven guilty, they are allowed a few friends.
   There is no better safeguard in this country against abusive
prosecution than a pack of experienced ACLU lawyers.
   That said, we feel free to censure the other side of the ACLU.
That side is highly political, seemingly paranoid about the
supposed danger of religion in public life and overzealous in
looking for infringements on so-called free speech. ...
   Of course, if anyone is to blame for the superficiality of the
ACLU debate, it is Bush, for ignoring the group's beneficial side,
and Dukakis, for defending the organization as if its politics were
irrelevant.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 5
   Owatonna (Minn.) People's Press on the League of Women Voters'
withdrawal from presidential debate sponsorship:
   Hurrah for the League of Women Voters.
   Rather than putting up with another staged event, the League
withdrew its sponsorship of the second presidential debate of this
campaign.
   The League's decision is the first honest call of this campaign.
Anyone who witnessed the first presidential ``debate'' knows the
candidates were more interested in their appearance than the
substance of their answers.
   The League likened the debates to the ever growing list of
campaign charades devoid of substance, spontaneity and honest
answers to tough questions. We wholeheartedly agree.
   This campaign has been one staged event after another. Enough is
enough. It's time for the candidates to put the issues before their
wardrobes.
   Maybe the League's decision will bring these candidates back
into the real world _ not the one their campaign advisers have
carefully staged these past few months.
   Certainly, the voters deserve as much.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
