<DOCNO> AP881012-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   10-12 0823</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0854</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: as much.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 7
   Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald on the vice presidential debate:
   By all criteria _ style or substance _ Lloyd Bentsen was a
lopsided winner in (the) vice presidential debate. Dan Quayle's
only claim was that he was still standing. Call it a technical
knockout.
   Sure, Bentsen overplayed the need for a ``tough'' trade policy
(a trade war perhaps?) as a miracle cure for the American economy.
But in other policy matters _ like welfare reform, the environment
and defense burden-sharing by American allies _ he was resonant.
   Bentsen was perhaps most convincing in explaining that he can
differ in degree with Michael Dukakis. On Contra aid (which he
favors and Dukakis opposes), Bentsen criticized the Reagan
administration for banking so heavily on military force that
regional diplomacy is disregarded outright.
   Bentsen was also right on the shaky foundations of Reaganomics _
an economy propped up by foreign debt and deficit spending (``$200
billion in hot checks''). Quayle was left to give a testimonial to
foreign entrepreneurs.
   Dukakis still has a lot of convincing to do to show his mettle
as a leader, but Bentsen's performance helps him a lot.
   The senator from Texas came off as a real Dukakis asset _ a man
of competence and moderation.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 7
   Charleston (W.Va.) Daily Mail on prison furloughs:
   Some good is coming out of the presidential race. Michael
Dukakis' defense of a furlough program for felons is causing such
programs to undergo closer examination by the general public.
   It is insane to allow violent criminals to roam free before they
complete their prison sentences. Such releases needlessly place the
law-abiding public in jeopardy.
   The Willie Horton case (in Massachusetts) is a good example of
this. Not only was Horton bad news before he was convicted, he
violated prison rules while inside. The administration that allowed
this man to be freed is out-and-out incompetent.
   It was also wrong of Circuit Judge Larry Starcher to end due
process and capriciously free 56 inmates from the Huttonsville
(W.Va.) prison in 1986. Already, seven of those men have returned
to prison _ for crimes that wouldn't have been committed had they
been behind bars, where judges and juries sent them.
   Efforts to alleviate prison crowding need to be a little more
careful than this. These experiments have endangered the civil
rights of innocent citizens _ both in West Virginia and
Massachusetts.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 10
   The Albuquerque (N.M.) Tribune on banning chlorofluorocarbons:
   Even as a 46-nation treaty calling for a 50 percent reduction in
manufacuture of ozone depleting chemicals comes close to going into
effect, the head of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency is
saying that isn't enough. EPA Administrator Lee Thomas wants
complete elimination.
   He's right. If the danger is as dire as Thomas says _ and there
seems little reason to doubt him _ the treaty should be amended.
   The United States should lead the way with legislation
establishing a timetable for a complete ban in this country on the
manufacture of chlorofluorocarbons and other chemicals that are
believed to be breaking down the ozone layer high above the Earth.
   The elimination of chlorofluorocarbons and the development of
acceptable substitutes should proceed apace. Destruction of the
ozone layer, which screens out ultraviolet rays that are harmful to
health, is too dreadful to contemplate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Oct. 10
   The (Baltimore) Sun on the Soviet leadership shakeup:
   By solidifying his grasp on the Kremlin apparatus and conferring
on himself the trappings as well as substance of power, Mikhail S.
Gorbachev comes to resemble more closely the Soviet dictators whose
mistakes he vows to undo.
   To combat the terrifying legacy of Josef Stalin, become the next
Stalin. To stamp out the stultifying cult of Leonid Brezhnev's
personality, raise Mikhail S. Gorabachev onto the pedestal.
   It is not really so surprising. Gorbachev is a Russian and a
Communist. If he sends journalistic lances to prick the balloons of
Stalin's reputation, there is no debunking Vladimir I. Lenin. The
sources and legitimacy of power as Gorabachev exercises them are
those that Lenin erected. ...
   There is no doubting Gorbachev's desire to liberate the
creativity of the Soviet peoples by freeing them from red tape and
shackles of inherited practice. ...
   In the interest of economic productivity, at the base of state
and political power, he clearly intends reforms and liberations
that have a greater-than-economic dimension, extending into the
intellectual and even spiritual spheres, however distasteful some
of that may be to Gorbachev himself.
   But to impose this on fourth generaton bureaucrats, the party
functionaries raised by Brezhnev for their limited vision and
unlimited loyalty, Gorbachev requires unhindered cooperation at the
top, unbrooked by opposition. ...
   Diversity, pluralism, separation and balance of powers, whatever
their virtue lower in the hierarchies, still have no place in the
summit of Soviet power. The general secretary proceeds as his
predecessors have. He knows no other way.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
