<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Politics     10-12 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Politics,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cabinet Minister Suggests Electronic Tags To Reduce Crime</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGHTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cabinet minister in charge of law
and order today suggested crime could be reduced by putting
electronic tags on people freed on bail and by widening a ban on
drinking outdoors.
   Britain's crime rate dominated debate on the second day of the
Conservative Party's annual convention in the southern coastal
resort of Brighton.
   The convention has been marked by massive security. When the
governing party last met in Brighton in 1984, a bomb planted by the
Irish Republic Army killed five people and narrowly missed the
prime minister.
   Government statistics in March indicated a 12 percent increase
in muggings and other violent crime in England and Wales last year
and an 11 percent increase in sexual offenses.
   About 3.9 million crimes were reported to police in England and
Wales in 1987, up 45,000 from 1986.
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd, the Cabinet member in charge of law
and order, said the government would attack crime with more police
officers, a possible widening of the public drinking ban, and the
electronic tagging system.
   But Hurd once again rejected capital punishment, saying ``don't
let's get stuck just in this groove.''
   ``Capital punishment can't be the answer to all crime, or even
to violent crime in general,'' he said.
   Capital punishment was abolished in Britain in 1969, but an
overwhelming majority of Conservative delegates raised their hands
in favor of its reinstatement in an unofficial convention poll.
   Hurd said that if the experiment with electronic tagging works,
it could be expanded to monitor the movements of convicted
offenders.
   ``The apparatus is relatively simple,'' Hurd explained. ``It
looks like an electronic bicycle clip, and it works. ... If this
project proves successful then we shall take the idea further.''
   Roy Hattersley, deputy leader of the socialist opposition Labor
Party, on Tuesday condemned Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's
philosophy of individual self-reliance and her determination to
reduce what she calls the dependency culture based on state aid.
   ``The idea that the Tories are the party of law and order is
clearly nonsense,'' Hattersley said.
   ``The new Tory philosophy openly undermines the rule of law. It
is openly the party of callous individualism... Mrs. Thatcher's
values and Mrs. Thatcher's example lie at the heart of our
increasingly violent society. It is Mrs. Thatcher who has
encouraged the cult of selfishness,'' he charged.
   Legislator Teddy Taylor, a leading law and order activist on the
right wing of the Conservative Party, called at a fringe meeting in
Brighton on Tuesday for a ``crusade on crime'' backed by stiffer
penalties and deterrents.
   ``After nine years of Conservative government, people are
entitled to say the time has come for decisive action,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881012-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1138EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0470 10-12 0741</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0470,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Says He's Now `My Own Handler' For Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 9 grafs new with Quayle comments; picks up pvs 3rd graf
bgng, To the partisan.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential candidate Dan
Quayle said today he was ``not mad at anybody in the Bush
campaign'' but would take a greater role in running his own
campaign from now on.
   ``I am my own handler,'' Quayle told reporters as he left
Indianapolis. ``If you have any questions, ask me.''
   Quayle had previously expressed irritation at unidentified Bush
aides who have been quoted anonymously as saying he was a liability
to the GOP ticket.
   The Indiana senator complained about the sniping over the
weekend to Bush campaign chairman James Baker III. But Quayle said
there was no animosity between him and top campaign officials.
   ``I'm not mad at anybody in the Bush campaign,'' he said. ``I'm
going to coordinate with them. They're going to suggest things that
I say, suggesting that I do, and I'm going to take that under
consideration.''
   Quayle said he did not anticipate any campaign staff changes,
but ``if I can find any of those leakers ... I think there will be
staff changes.''
   He described his conversation with Baker as cordial and said
reporters would hear him ``say what's on my mind'' in the future.
   Quayle ended a successful Midwestern campaign swing Tuesday with
a promise in his home state to keep on fighting.
   ``We plan on taking some heat but staying in the kitchen. In the
end, we'll get the job done. We have just begun to fight,'' Quayle
shouted as supporters cheered.
   To the partisan crowd, the Indiana senator could do no wrong,
although Dukakis supporters mounted a small protest outside the
rally site. Quayle has said he expects to be a prime target of the
Democrats and that he is happy to be the ``lightning rod'' for the
campaign.
   Quayle travels to South Dakota and Montana today as he makes his
way west.
   But his reception probably won't top the one he received here,
where supporters cheered wildly as he stood before them and said,
``You're looking at the next vice president of the United States.''
   ``Welcome home, Dan,'' they shouted as he worked the crowd,
shaking hands while a band played ``Back Home In Indiana.''
   The welcome did not extend to reporters traveling with Quayle.
The crowd chanted ``Just say no!'' as the press entourage arrived.
   Indiana was the scene of one of the more notorious news
conferences of the Quayle campaign as he and George Bush held a
rally in Quayle's hometown of Huntington the day after the
Republican convention.
   Reporters were booed and denounced with shouts of ``BOR-ing'' as
they tried to question Quayle about his National Guard service.
   Tuesday's campaign events had a vastly more calming tone than
that day in August. Quayle rode through Ohio on a winding bus tour
through pastoral farm land, attacking Democrat Michael Dukakis as
soft on crime, one of the Republicans' favorite themes.
   Quayle was portrayed by speaker after speaker as a ``son of the
heartland'' and he told flag-waving crowds that their staunch
Midwestern values would be preserved under a George Bush presidency.
   ``Right and wrong is at the very core of life in this beloved
Midwest region that I grew up in and where you live,'' he said.
``The values of this region have not left me.''
   He spoke of the importance of Ohio, which has 23 electoral votes
and is viewed as a swing state in November.
   And in Napoleon, Ohio, Quayle delivered the campaign's response
to the Democratic presidential candidate's outrage at the way the
Bush-Quayle ticket was portraying the Massachusetts furlough
program and the escape of convicted murderer Willie Horton Jr., who
attacked a Maryland couple while on the lam.
   Dukakis had said during the weekend that he resented being
portrayed as insensitive to the plight of crime victims, and noted
that members of his own family had been victimized in the past.
Dukakis also noted that people such as Horton, who had been
sentenced to life in prison without possibility of parole, could
not be furloughed under current state law.
   But Quayle took issue with Dukakis' defense of what Quayle said
was his ``sorry record of dealing with violent crime.''
   ``He has not truly and sincerely owned up to his irresponsible
conduct,'' Quayle said.
</TEXT>
