<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HitlerParties 1stLd-Writethru a0574 10-12 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hitler Parties, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0574,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>University of North Dakota Accepts Money From Man Who Threw Hitler
Parties
^Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Officials said...', to restore dropped first
reference to university president Thomas Clifford. SUBS 13th graf,
`At one...', to delete now-redundant first reference.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   University of North Dakota officials say
they'll accept a $5 million endowment from a Las Vegas hotel owner
who threw Adolf Hitler birthday parties for his employees,
concluding he meant them only as a joke.
   A delegation from the school flew to Nevada on Sunday and met
with Ralph Engelstad, 58, a onetime University of North Dakota
hockey player who owns the Imperial Palace Hotel and Casino. The
trip was prompted by disclosures about Engelstad's private
collection of Nazi memorabilia, housed at the hotel, and the Hitler
parties.
   ``I don't think the World War II collection that we saw is a
problem in itself,'' said Barry Vickrey, associate dean of the
university law school. ``The bigger problem is some of Ralph
Engelstad's actions, most notably the Hitler parties, which have
given the whole collection a sinister context.
   ``Our delegation seemed to conclude that his motives were
unthinking, and that's not good,'' Vickrey said. ``But we weren't
able to conclude that he was anti-Semitic or pro-Hitler.''
   The collection includes a portrait of Hitler ``which has that
unfortunate, `To Ralphie, from Adolf,' on there,'' said Dave
Vorland, executive assistant to the university's president.
Engelstad explained the fake inscription as a joke, according to
the Star Tribune of Minneapolis.
   Engelstad also admits hanging an artist's portrait of himself as
a Nazi at a Hitler party _ ``again as a joke.''
   Officials said the university in Grand Forks, N.D., doesn't plan
to turn down Engelstad's money and won't change the name of the
Ralph Engelstad Arena, formerly the Winter Sports Center. But the
university's president, Thomas Clifford, added that the university
is watching the controversy for any new developments and ``we're
keeping our options open.''
   Engelstad pledged the $5 million endowment to benefit the
school's hockey program and has already given $500,000.
   Details about the Hitler parties and other elements surfaced
during an investigation by the Nevada Gaming Control Commission.
   In a statement delivered at a news conference last week, the
hotel owner said he threw Hitler birthday parties this year and in
1986 to boost employee morale at the casino.
   ``Looking for an excuse, I suggested one with Adolf's birthday
as a theme,'' he said. ``It wasn't meant to honor Hitler.''
   ``I can't tell you how much I regret my insensitivity on this
point. It was innocent, but it was very, very bad judgment. ... I
deeply regret it and apologize for it. ... I despise Hitler and
everything he stood for.''
   At one of the Hitler parties, Engelstad handed out T-shirts
depicting Nazi battle scenes as favors, said Clifford.
   ``He said it wasn't the brightest idea he ever had,'' Clifford
said. ``But I don't think it had anything to do with neo-Nazism. It
was just a bad joke ... bad taste.''
   In a letter to the Jewish Federation of Las Vegas, Engelstad
said he now plans to sell his collection of cars and other World
War II Axis memorabilia.
</TEXT>
