<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Saudi-Conference 1stLd-Writethru   10-12 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Saudi-Conference, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0473,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fahd Extends Olive Branch To Iran</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS with four grafs to CORRECT to Moslem nations, sted
Arab, adds background. Pick up 4th pvs, `A leading...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Fahd of Saudi Arabia says he
wishes Iran had sent a delegation to a meeting of Islamic
information ministers, the latest Saudi overture aimed at easing
bitter differences among Moslem nations.
   Fahd's signal to Iran came at the opening of the conference
attended by information ministers from about 45 Islamic nations.
   ``I would have wished the Iranian delegation to be with us,''
Fahd said in a speech Tuesday. ``Iran is an Islamic country, and
deep in my heart I would have loved to see my Iranian brothers here
today.''
   Iran's culture is Persian and most of its people belong to the
minority Shiite branch of Islam. Most Arabs belong to the Sunni
branch.
   A leading Islamic spokesman, meanwhile, assailed Western news
media for their reporting on Islamic matters.
   ``The image of the Muslim people in the world has been
stereotyped as backward, ignorant, fundamentalist and lacking
culture and civilization,'' said Sharifuddin Pirzada of Pakistan,
secretary-general of the Islamic Conference Organization.
   Saudi Arabia is hosting the information minister's conference in
this port city on the Red Sea. Officials said the gathering was
aimed at improving the flow of information among Islamic countries
and enhancing the image of Islam in the non-Muslim world.
   Fahd told delegates Islamic countries had to show the world
their faith was based on ``peace and stability.''
   His gesture to Iran was the clearest in a series of recent Saudi
overtures. It comes as Tehran seeks to improve relations with both
Arab and Western nations after the Aug. 20 cease-fire in the
8-year-old war with Iraq.
   The Saudis broke off diplomatic relations with Tehran April 26
after accusing the Tehran regime of carrying out sabotage,
subversion and terrorism against Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and other
Arab states.
   The king's remarks came a week after the Saudi government
executed four saboteurs it said were working on Iran's behalf.
   Iran condemned the executions and accused Saudi Arabia and other
gulf Arab states of producing more oil than the quotas set by the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to drive down oil
prices to weaken Tehran.
   Pirzada's attack on Western news media, delivered in a closed
session, was not reported in detail by the official Saudi press
agency, but a partial transcript was obtained by The Associated
Press.
   He said the international media are ``mostly unaware of and
indifferent to the realities of the Islamic world.
   ``At times they are actively hostile and indifferent toward our
faith, our cultural heritage, our objectives of socio-economic
development and our efforts to safeguard our independence,'' he
said.
   Pirzada said news reports from Western agencies, none of which
he named, ``either ignore or deliberately distort and undermine the
just causes of the Muslims.
   ``Our faith is villified, our culture sneered at, our
difficulties magnified and our peoples, governments and
institutions subjected to misrepresentation, ridicule and
censure,'' he said.
</TEXT>
