<2ND_LINE>PM-Myerson Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0530,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Clerk Says Other Side in Myerson Case Also Helped Judge's Daughter</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with testimony this morning,
picking up 8th graf pvs, `But under ....'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecution witness in the divorce-fixing
trial of Bess Myerson admitted under cross-examination that a
lawyer for the other side in the divorce case also did a favor for
the judge's daughter.
   Miss Myerson, a former Miss America and city cultural affairs
commissioner, is accused of giving a city job to the daughter of
former state Supreme Court Justice Hortense Gabel, in exchange for
favorable rulings in the divorce of Miss Myerson's lover, Carl
``Andy'' Capasso.
   Testimony by Mrs. Gabel's law secretary resumed today at federal
court in Manhattan, with the judge's daughter expected to take the
stand later in the day.
   Under questioning today by Assistant U.S. Attorney Stuart
Abrams, the law secretary, Howard Leventhal, amended his previous
testimony about when Mrs. Capasso's lawyer got an apartment for the
judge's daughter.
   On Tuesday, Leventhal said he didn't remember exactly when the
apartment had been obtained, but questioning by defense lawyers
left the impression that Mrs. Capasso's lawyer had done an innocent
favor for Mrs. Gabel's daughter while the judge was considering
issues in the divorce case.
   ``To the best of my knowledge,'' Leventhal said today, the
lawyer's help came after ``Justice Gabel's completing her rulings
in the Capassos' case.''
   The lawyer, Raoul Felder, said Tuesday that he helped Miss Gabel
find an apartment in 1986, by which time the Capasso case was
``ancient history.'' Felder is not accused of any wrongdoing.
   On Tuesday, Leventhal also testified that Miss Myerson called
the judge's private line several times while Mrs. Gabel was
deciding whether to cut Capasso's weekly support payments to his
estranged wife.
   According to the prosecution witness, Mrs. Gabel apparently did
not tell lawyers in the divorce trial about the Myerson phone calls
when the judge offered to excuse herself from the case after a
newspaper article revealed that Miss Myerson had hired the judge's
daughter.
   But under cross-examination by Mrs. Gabel's lawyer, Leventhal
said that Mrs. Gabel readily told him Miss Myerson was the
mysterious person calling and identifying herself as ``Barbara
Robinson'' or ``Barbara Goodman.''
   ``Did she (the judge) react in panic when you asked that
question?'' asked Feldberg.
   ``No, not at all,'' said Leventhal. ``She reacted in a jocular
manner.''
   Miss Myerson is accused of giving a $19,000-a-year city job to
Sukhreet Gabel, who was then 34, shortly after Miss Myerson became
cultural affairs commissioner in 1983. The prosecution alleges the
former beauty queen wanted to get the judge to reduce Capasso's
temporary support payments.
   Mrs. Gabel also did not tell the divorce lawyers that Felder
helped Sukhreet Gabel obtain an apartment, Leventhal testified
under questioning by the judge's defense attorney, Michael Feldberg.
   On Sept. 14, 1983, Mrs. Gabel cut Capasso's weekly temporary
alimony and child support payments from $1,850 to $680 a week.
</TEXT>
