<HEAD>Man Suffers Multiple Injuries While Driving Blind in `Sack Race'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A racetrack owner says he will
discontinue ``sack races'' in which drivers compete with bags over
their heads after a guide in one of the cars suffered serious
injuries in a crash.
   Harold Chafin said the event at Highland Rim Speedway was
intended to amuse spectators. But Jamie Hull, 32, suffered broken
ribs, a broken breast bone, collapsed lung and a deep gash on his
forehead.
   Hull was riding with Tommy Hagewood, his brother-in-law and a
regular driver at the speedway who received some bruises and a cut
on his knee in the four-lap, three-car event.
   Kay Hull said she did not know why her husband decided to join
in Saturday's race.
   ``We had come to the track to watch my brother Tommy and he
decided he was going to enter the (sack) race,'' she said. ``It all
happened so fast. The next thing I knew his car had hit the wall.''
   Chafin said the race is normally run at about 10 mph and that
Hagewood was going faster than that.
   Hull was listed in good condition in the intensive care unit of
Vanderbilt University Medical Center.
