<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1224EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Taxes Bjt   10-12 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Taxes, Bjt,0720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Will Yearly Tax Returns Become a Soviet Ritual?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Another Western influence may soon follow rock
music and fast food into Soviet society: the ritual of filing
annual financial returns and paying a progressive income tax.
   A pair of economists said in articles published Wednesday that a
complete reform of the Soviet tax system is necessary to expose
those who have made fortunes in the multibillion dollar black
market, and spread income more equitably.
   ``To search for some kind of scientific approach in our system
of taxation is useless,'' Deputy Finance Minister Viktor Semenov
told the weekly Moscow News.
   Semenov and economist V. Yaroshenko, writing in the Communist
Party daily newspaper Pravda, both said a yearly statement of
income and expenditures was essential.
   Yaroshenko added that the income tax should be made more
progressive, as it is in many other countries, to be fairer to poor
people.
   Currently, Soviets pay a flat 10 percent of their income in tax
if they make less than $320 a month, the average industrial wage.
The rate increases a few percentage points for higher incomes. Most
taxes are deducted at the work place and workers don't need to file
annual tax returns.
   ``Declarations of income and expenditures would serve as a means
of strong economic and psychological action most of all against the
system of organized crime,'' said Yaroshenko.
   By filling out such forms, illegal millionaires would be making
a ``preliminary accusation'' of themselves, he said.
   Black marketeering and other organized crime saps the economy of
more money every year than is paid out in benefits to pensioners,
invalids, students, families with many children and orphans, he
said.
   It is so well-organized that it constitutes a ``government
within the government,'' he said.
   The current economic and tax structure hurts the poor,
Yaroshenko said. He suggested the government impose more
progressive income taxes, and that illegal millionaires be allowed
to give their ill-gotten wealth to state-run charities anonymously
before filing their financial statements.
   Yaroshenko's article was the second published in Pravda in two
days to address the effects of economic reforms on the Soviet poor.
In an article published Tuesday, a farm economist said increasing
food prices would be an unacceptable way to eliminate the $105
billion the government pays every year in subsidies. Instead, Kim.
N. Khmelkov said the Soviet Union must make farming much more
efficient.
   In yet another article printed Wednesday, Moscow News said that
in the first half of the year, $130,000 was confiscated in the
Soviet capital from people illegally trading rubles for hard
currencies. But it said police are nowhere near able to control the
problem.
   Western tourists are approached near hotels and tourist sites in
large cities by hordes of people offering to exchange money. Such
exchanges are illegal and give the Soviets access to goods they
cannot buy in the official economy.
   Yaroshenko blamed the pervasiveness of organized crime on the
centralized Soviet economy's inability to produce large quantities
of high-quality consumer goods.
   ``Instead of the usual `sold' and `bought,' we started to say,
`threw out,' and `managed to get,''' Yaroshenko said. ``That money
is hard to earn has always been normal and natural _ but that it is
hard to spend, this is an alarming symptom.''
   Semenov said the tax system will be reformed in the early 1990s,
when economists also are aiming to implement a comprehensive system
of price reform.
   The government must reduce indirect taxes that are worked into
the retail prices of many goods and turn to direct taxes that now
make up only 7.5 percent of the national budget, he said.
   Semenov said some of the heaviest indirect taxes historically
have been imposed on light industry and food processing, two areas
of the economy Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev is urgently
trying to reform to provide a better life for Soviet citizens.
   Taxes significantly raise the retail price of refrigerators,
vacuum cleaners, TV sets and tape recorders, he said.
   The wholesale price of a Volga, the largest standard passenger
car produced in the country, is $5,460. After indirect taxes are
added, however, the final retail price is more than $25,600.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881012-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1228EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Reagan-Politics 2ndLd-Writethru a0548 10-12 0843</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0548,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Urges Students to Help Keep America `Envy of World' in
Election</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS pvs 3rd graf to delete reference to prepared speech;
INSERTS new 12th graf bgng, Reagan spoke, with color.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UPPER DARBY, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan borrowed a phrase from
Dan Quayle to hustle votes for the Republican ticket, urging high
school students to participate in the November election to help
keep America ``the envy of the world.''
   Reagan was campaigning today in Pennsylvania and New Jersey as
chief surrogate for GOP nominee George Bush while the vice
president prepares for his second and final debate Thursday night
with Democratic rival Michael Dukakis in Los Angeles.
   In a speech before students at Upper Darby High School in
suburban Philadelphia, a Republican stronghold he last visited late
in his 1980 campaign, the president made repeated references to
Quayle, Bush's running mate, and echoed the Indiana senator's
assertion that America is the wonder of the world.
   But Reagan said that unless the nation's youngsters take part in
the election, all that he has fought for in the past eight years
might be lost.
   ``I am dedicating myself this year to making sure that this
future of hope built on opportunity and traditional values remains
open to each of you,'' he said, citing the strong economegrees, although
Romanians
and foreign visitors say many houses actually are colder than that.
   The energy decree did not mention any change in the quotas for
natural gas, indicating strict limits set last year remained in
force.
   The higher quotas for electricty, while not considerably
improving Romanians' living standards _ generally viewed as among
the lowest in Europe _ were perceived as a sign that the regime of
President and Communist Party leader Nicolae Ceausescu may fear new
public protests at the outset of winter.
   About 10,000 people marched through the streets of Brasov,
Romania's second-largest city in November, shouting slogans against
the regime and clamoring for ``more food and more heating.''
   The protest in Brasov, a leading industrial center, was believed
to be the largest against the government since the communist
takeover in 1947.
   The comparatively higher power quotas this year might have also
been intended to shield Romania from the wave of unrest in
neighboring Yugoslavia triggered by worsening living conditions and
ethnic problems in the Balkan nation.
   Romanians also have suffered from widespread food shortages, and
despite official calls for better supplies of meat, cheese and
other staples, shortages have worsened, Romanians and Western
diplomats in Bucharest said.
   In July, even bread was hard to find in the capital for a week.
   White flour, cooking oil, sugar, butter and eggs have been
rationed since the early 1980s, but in August and September no
sugar rations were distributed.
   Romania's centralized economy has been grappling with perennial
failures in the past decade to meet plan targets in coal-mining and
shortcomings in the operation of coal-fired stations. Scinteia
recently has again carried articles complaining about repair delays
and poor supply of coal at the stations.
   Under the measures published Wednesday, electricity consumption
beyond assigned quotas will be penalized with up to four times the
normal charge.
   According to the measures, a family of three to four people
living in a three-room apartment will be alloted a quota of 47
kilowatt hours in January for lighting and other household needs,
which equaled the quota for that month two years ago.
   An energy-saving decree issued in November, regarded by
Romanians as beyond the absolute minium they could be expected to
endure, had alloted a family just 35 kilowatt hours for that month.
   Last year, a family of three was allotted 236 cubic meters of
natural gas for heating and cooking in January, the coldest month
of the winter.
   In most homes, cooking is done by natural gas. Heating systems
in the apartment blocks, where most urban Romanians live, are
heated by centrally controlled thermal systems that authorities can
turn down to decreed limits.
</TEXT>
