<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Poaching,0154</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Vehicle Impounded With 132 Elephant Tusks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have impounded a
government vehicle loaded with 132 elephant tusks and detained four
people, it was reported Wednesday.
   The vehicle, belonging to the Morogoro Regional Development
Directorate, was found Sunday in Morogoro region west of this
Indian Ocean port city and north of the Selous game reserve, the
state-run Tanzania News Agency said.
   The government did not cite the ivory's estimated worth.
   The world market value for ivory is $82 per pound, according to
Nairobi-based trade expert Esmond Bradley Martin. An average tusk
weighs about 12 pounds, which would put the current market value of
132 tusks at about $130,000.
   Although big game hunting is permitted at controlled levels in
Tanzania, the country has outlawed elephant hunting. In the last 11
years, poachers have slashed Tanzania's elephant herd in half, to
about 55,000.
</TEXT>
