<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--China-Korea     10-12 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--China-Korea,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Extends Flight Permission for KAL</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has authorized South Korea's
flag carrier Korean Air to fly over the communist country through
October, extending an earlier permit for the Olympics, the
Transportation Ministry said Wednesday.
   Under the renewed permit, officials said KAL will operate 17
flights on the Seoul-Zurich route and five on the Seoul-Tripoli
route over Chinese territory.
   They said KAL will be able to save $1,300 in fuel per flight.
Its usual southern route is through Taipei and Bangkok en route to
European and Middle East points.
   Under the earlier permit, KAL flew over China from Sept. 3 to
Oct. 9 for transporting Olympic athletes and officials.
   The Korea Herald, an English-language daily, quoted a ministry
official as saying KAL may continue to fly over China after the end
of this month. A ministry spokesman said he had no knowledge of the
report.
   KAL also was seeking an extension of a similar permit from the
Soviet Union that also allowed flights over the Soviet Union on the
Seoul-Europe route during the Olympics.
   South Korea has no diplomatic relations with the two communist
countries.
</TEXT>
