<DOCNO> AP881012-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Vietnam-MIA Bjt   10-12 0939</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-MIA, Bjt,0965</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US-Vietnamese Team Searches New Crash Sites</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Associated Press correspondent Peter Eng
accompanied the latest joint team searching crash sites for
evidence of Americans still missing in action from the Vietnam War.
This is his report.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAIPHONG, Vietnam (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At low tide, the beach seems to extend
all the way to the submerged wreckage of an American bomber shot
down 20 years ago near the lighthouse that unwittingly guided its
raid on this industrial port.
   Residents of nearby villages recall little about the crash and
the fate of the crew remains a mystery to them. The local
administrator said he wrote a brief report for his superiors but
does not know what happened to it.
   The United States still seeks to account for 2,393 Americans
listed as missing in action in the Southeast Asia war more than 13
years after it ended. Defense Department sources in Washington say
about 400 were airmen lost in crashes in water, whose remains
probably never will be recovered.
   Difficulties even with cases considered most easily resolvable
show a hard road lies ahead despite last week's unprecedented joint
investigations in Vietnam, where 1,757 Americans are missing.
   U.S. and Vietnamese specialists searched in five provinces,
visiting crash sites and interviewing villagers about six lost
airmen. The six are among 70 ``discrepancy cases'' Washington says
Vietnam should have information on, including cases of men captured
but never returned.
   They retrieved two sets of unidentified remains and some
wreckage but it was an arduous task just reaching the sites, which
were chosen in part becasue of their nearness to Hanoi, the
capital. The team trekked across mountainous, leech-infested areas,
through monsoon rains and along roads enveloped in blinding dust.
   Wreckage from a 1968 crash is said to be submerged in a
water-filled crater in a rice field at Die Hop village near
Haiphong.
   Tran Van Loi, 50, then the local Communist Party chief, said the
villagers put the airman's body in a nylon bag and buried it near
the wreckage, but he could not find it now because the land has
been planted so often.
   Wreckage litters rice fields from Haiphong to Hanoi, but only
the cores of jet engines remained at two sites visited last week.
   Nguyen Hop, 60, said residents stripped all the metal for
souvenirs and to make household items after a crash near his
village in 1967. He smiled and held up a large rice pot made from
the wreckage.
   At another crash site nearby, young men still were stripping a
muddied jet turbine 20 years after the crash, selling the metal for
the equivalent of half a cent a pound.
   U.S. experts also surveyed crash sites in Laos recently for a
planned fourth joint excavation, but reported no progress in
obtaining numerous remains the authorities in war-torn Cambodia
claim to have.
   The project in Vietnam was a major breakthrough because many
U.S. officials believe Vietnam is withholding information, a
suspicion fed by previous refusals of permission for U.S. experts
to search the countryside.
   Washington demands ``the fullest possible accounting'' of the
missing, which requires trust built on progress with the
discrepancy cases, said a Western official interviewed in Bangkok,
Thailand, who has an important role in the matter.
   ``What I want most is to get some kind of confidence that we are
getting something approaching full disclosure on the discrepancy
cases,'' he said, on condition of anonymity.
   Diplomats in Hanoi see the cooperation as a a step toward
diplomatic relations, now blocked by U.S. opposition to Vietnam's
military occupation of Cambodia. They say Foreign Minister Nguyen
Co Thach convinced Communist Party colleagues to allow the
investigations, putting aside preoccupations with sovereignty and
security to do what is needed to improve ties with Washington.
   ``Everyone agrees it's extremely unlikely they will account for
all the MIAs,'' one Western ambassador said. ``The joint
investigation is an exercise in trying to find ways and means of
normalizing relations. It's symbolism.''
   U.S. bombers raided North Vietnam from 1965 to 1968, then again
in 1972. Pilots followed the glow of the lighthouse to strike
Haiphong, the country's biggest port, Vietnamese officials said.
   The U.S. Defense Department says the official press published
information on U.S. aircraft losses in North Vietnam throughout the
war and Hanoi kept records on deaths and burials of prisoners.
   Of the 2,393 MIA cases, 1,128 were classified from the beginning
as ``killed in action-body not recovered,'' and Defense Department
sources say few of the remains will be found.
   The other 1,265 originally were labeled ``prisoner of
war-missing in action,'' but a few years ago all but one symbolic
case were changed to the status of presumed dead.
   In the villages, what evidence remains is fading with the
memories of older residents and the destruction wrought by man and
nature.
   Investigators said it was difficult to find people still living
in crash areas because they fled during the bombing. Reports on
crashes written by local officials often were inaccurate because of
the chaos, said Nguyen Can, head of Vietnam's MIA office.
   He said Vietnam has resolved 22 of the 70 discrepany cases, 11
by returning remains and the others by concluding after
interviewing villagers that nothing could be recovered. In some
cases aircraft exploded in the air, he said.
   A U.S. investigator said: ``You go to a town in the U.S. and you
ask what happened 20-25 years ago, after offices have been moved,
records have been moved. It's hard. (The Vietnamese) have no
equipment, no personnel, no money and they have great economic
problems of their own.''
</TEXT>
