<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BerlinWall     10-12 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Berlin Wall,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Official Praises East German Escape Attempts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRIEDER REIMOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deputy Secretary of State John C. Whitehead on
Wednesday called on communist authorities to tear down the Berlin
Wall and praised East Germans who have risked their lives to escape
to the West.
   The State Department's No. 2 official, who spoke to reporters at
the wall in West Berlin, recalled President Reagan's June 1987
speech at the gray barrier East Germany built in 1961 to stop the
westward flow of refugees.
   ``(Reagan) called on those who put it up to tear it down _ and
so they should. The sooner the better,'' said Whitehead, who is in
Europe on an official visit to East and West Germany, Romania,
Poland, Hungary and Czechoslovakia.
   ``(The Berlin Wall) is a gray, monstrous snake,'' he said as he
stood on a podium in front of what he called ``an anachronism, a
barrier inconsistent with our contemporary world.''
   He recalled recent escapes and escape attempts into West Berlin
from the eastern sector.
   ``When I hear of young men shot at as they run for freedom ...
or of a pregnant woman chased by a patrol boat as she swims ...
across the Spree (the river that divides East from West), I feel
deep admiration for the courage of those Berliners,'' Whitehead
said.
   Whitehead said that he had discussed with East German officials
their country's practice of shooting at people trying to escape.
   ``I do believe that the shootings are less frequent than when I
started to raise the issue,'' Whitehead told reporters.
   Whitehead said the Allies governing West Berlin _ the United
States, Britain and France _ would continue to support Reagan's
1987 ``Berlin Initiative'' aimed at easing regulations and
improving international air access to the divided city.
   The Allied powers in December issued a memorandum to Soviet
officials proposing improvements to the Berlin Initiative.
   Allied officials have refused to disclose the Soviet response,
but the West German newspaper Bild am Sonntag said last month that
the Soviets accused the Allies of ``ignoring the territorial and
political realities of central Europe.''
   Whitehead's tour of Warsaw Pact countries included talks in East
Berlin on Tuesday with East German leader Erich Honecker.
   Whitehead also said ``a time of change'' was coming to Eastern
Europe because of people's dissatisfaction with economic and social
conditions.
</TEXT>
