<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Islam     10-12 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Islam,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ministers Seek to Break Down Anti-Islam Prejudices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leading Islamic spokesman urged
action Wednesday to counter what they said was widespread prejudice
against Moslems as backward, ignorant fanatics.
   The concern over anti-Moslem sentiment became a principal theme
as information ministers from more than 40 Islamic countries worked
on a plan to improve the exchange of news among themselves and
breaking down barriers to the non-Islamic world.
   Professor Abdelhadi Boutaleb, director-general of the Islamic
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization, said the world's
estimated 800 million Moslems must be educated against outside
influences including ``foreign media'' characterizations of
``backwardness, ignorance and fanaticism as the main features of
our peoples.''
   On Tuesday, Sharifuddin Pir Zadeh, the Pakistani
secretary-general of the Organization of Islamic Conference, told a
closed session that reports from Western news agencies ``ignore or
deliberately distort'' Islamic issues.
   Some Saudi newspapers echoed the theme.
   The Jiddah-based English-language Arab News urged the
information ministers to act against an ``ugly phenomenon'' that it
said was particularly virulent in Western Europe, but also apparent
in nationalist movements within the communist bloc and increasing
even in the Third World.
   ``Outside the Islamic world, anti-Islamic prejudice is most
definitely on the increase. Much of it is pure religious bigotry,
but there is a marked streak of racism involved in it as well,''
the newspaper said.
   It said any effort to correct this would be wasted if it is
``nothing more than a machine pushing Islamic information back into
the Islamic world.
   ``We cannot allow ourselves to rely on the insensitive and
uncomprehending international news agencies ... when Islam is
involved,'' it said.
   Except for a U.S. television crew from Cairo, Western news
agencies appeared to be the only outside media permitted to cover
the conference. Saudi Arabia rarely grants entry to foreign
reporters.
   The two-day meeting in this Red Sea port city drew ministers or
their representatives from all but a few of the 46 members of the
conference.
   The absentees included Afghanistan, whose Marxist government was
expelled from the conference several years ago, and Iran, with
which host Saudi Arabia broke diplomatic relations in April.
</TEXT>
