<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Athens-Smog     10-12 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Athens-Smog,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taxis Prolong Boycott of Athens Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The capital's 17,000 cabbies on Wednesday
extended a 15-day boycott of downtown Athens to the end of the
month to protest anti-pollution measures restricting taxis in the
city center.
   Taxis are included in traffic restrictions banning half the
city's 800,000 cars from a 5-square-mile zone around the city
center from 7 a.m. to 8 p.m. weekdays, based on odd and even
license plate numbers.
   ``We decided to extend the boycott until Oct. 31 because we felt
the government wasn't taking us seriously enough,'' said a
spokesman for the Athens Taxi Drivers Union.
   Cabbies object to the taxi ban, in effect since January, saying
half of their fares are generated in the city center. The union
says the average driver takes home about $400 a month.
   A brown colored smog, known to Athenians as the ``Nefos'' _ the
Greek word for cloud _ forms over the city on warm, still days.
Cars, diesel-powered taxis and the city's aging buses are blamed
for most of the pollution.
   The transport ministry has threatened taxi drivers boycotting
the downtown area with a $200 fine and removal of their operating
license.
</TEXT>
