<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Afghanistan     10-12 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Afghanistan,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Pledge $600 Million For UN's Afghan Reconstruction program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union today pledged $600
million to the United Nation's campaign for the reconstruction of
Afghanistan and repatriation of millions of Afghan refugees, the
program's coordinator said.
   The coordinator, Prince Sadruddin Aga Khan, told reporters the
Soviet pledge was the largest to date since an appeal for donations
went out in June. His Geneva-based office, the U.N. Humanitarian
and Economic Assistance Programs Relating to Afghanistan, estimates
that rebuilding that war-shattered nation will cost more than $2
billion.
   Moslem guerrillas have been at war for nearly 10 years with
Afghanistan's pro-Soviet government. Soviet troops entered the
country in December 1979 but began withdrawing in May under terms
of a U.N.-mediated accord signed in April.
   Under the agreement, the more than 100,000 Soviet troops are to
be out of Afghanistan by Aug. 15.
   Sadruddin said he has also received pledges of $60 million from
Japan, which said it planned further contributions and would send
civilian personnel to aid in refugee repatriation; $27 million from
West Germany; $7 million from Sweden; and 10,000 tons of food aid
from Greece worth $2 million.
   The United States was unable to estimate how much it would
contribute due to the upcoming presidental election and Congress
being in recess, Sadruddin said.
   He noted that the United States has already promised special
assistance to the Afghan people in detecting and clearing the mines
littering their homeland.
</TEXT>
