<1ST_LINE>u a PM-OfficialEnglish     10-12 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Official English,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Overturns Federal Judge's `Official English' Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HILLIARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals today
overturned a decision that had threatened to throw the state's
``official English'' initiative off the Nov. 8 ballot on the
grounds that the petitions for the proposal should have been
available in Spanish.
   The appellate court panel issued the decision at the end of a
90-minute hearing this morning on Colorado Secretary of State
Natalie Meyer's appeal of U.S. District Judge Jim Carrigan's
decision of Sept. 16.
   Carrigan had said petitions circulated in 12 Colorado counties
should have been printed in Spanish and English. The petitions were
printed in English only. He said failure to circulate bilingual
petitions in those counties violated the federal Voting Rights Act
of 1965.
   The decision had thrown the status of the ``official English''
ballot initiative into doubt, because his rejection of petitions
from the 12 counties dropped the number of valid signatures on the
petitions to just 36,874. A total of 50,686 signatures were needed
to get the measure on the ballot.
   But Meyer had placed the proposed amendment on the general
election ballot despite Carrigan's ruling, hoping that her appeal
would be accepted by the 10th Circuit Court.
   After the court ruled today, Meyer said, ``This one will be
voted on. We're through as of today.''
   Carrigan had based his ruling on a portion of the U.S. Voting
Rights Act that requires election literature to be distributed in a
second language in areas where more than 5 percent of the
population has a limited knowledge of English.
   His ruling had been watched closely in other states besides
Colorado, because of concern that it could affect not only other
initiatives on this year's ballot, but laws passed by previous
initiatives.
   In Florida, opponents of an official English amendment in that
state went to federal court to get the measure removed from the
November ballot, citing Carrigan's ruling on bilingual petitions.
   Proposed Amendment 1 says simply: ``An amendment to the Colorado
Constitution to declare that the English language is the official
language of the state of Colorado.''
   Critics have called the proposal racist, while proponents say
that English is a bond that helps hold America's ``melting pot''
together.
   In announcing its decision today, the appeals court said a
written ruling giving details on the reasons for overturning
Carrigan's decision would be issued later.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
