<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Politics     10-12 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Politics,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Pledges Crime Crackdown but Opposes Death Penalty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIGHTON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Wednesday promised a
crackdown on rising crimes of violence, but refused to restore the
death penalty.
   Home Secretary Douglas Hurd told his ruling Conservative Party's
annual convention he would recruit more police, build more prison
space, impose further curbs on drunkenness and introduce electronic
tags to keep track of alleged offenders.
   But his rejection of the death penalty clearly bucked sentiment
at the convention.
   With Hurd and Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher looking on,
delegate Lionel Stanbrook ended his pro-death penalty speech by
unexpectedly asking pro-hanging delegates to raise their hands. A
majority did.
   Hanging was abolished in 1969, and attempts to restore it have
been repeatedly defeated ever since.
   ``Don't let's get stuck just in this groove,'' Hurd urged the
delegates. ``Capital punishment can't be the answer to all crime,
or even to violent crime in general.''
   The second day of the convention also dealt with the environment
and energy, and included a pledge by Energy Minister Cecil
Parkinson to sell the state-owned coal industry to private
ownership after the next election, which must be held by 1992.
   But the day's dominant issue was law and order, which is
increasingly preoccupying Tories as police reported a 12 percent
increase in violent crime in England and Wales last year and an 11
percent increase in sexual offenses.
   Electronic tagging would enable authorities to free suspects
instead of locking them in prisons, which already are rated the
most overcrowded in Western Europe.
   The Home Office said the tagging trials would take place in
England and Wales only, and the specific test areas had not been
selected.
   ``The apparatus is relatively simple,'' Hurd explained. ``It
looks ike an electronic bicycle clip, and it works ... If this
project proves successful then we shall take the idea further.''
   He said it could be used for offenders who would otherwise be
remanded in custody, and to enable judges to hand down more
community service sentences.
   ``There should be restrictions on the young thief's leisure
time,'' Hurd said. ``It would do him good to be made to stay at
home during pub opening hours, or on Saturday afternoon while the
football is going on. Electronic monitoring fits in here.''
   The tag, attached to the ankle, transmits a signal to a police
receiver. If the suspect violates his curfew hours, the signal is
broken and he can be rearrested.
   The Howard League for Penal Reform attacked the scheme as
``unnecessary, expensive, ineffective and uncivilized,'' while the
National Association of Probation Officers said U.S. tagging
programs had not reduced the prison population.
   The Tories insist crime is up because school and parental
discipline has declined, while the opposition Labor Party blames it
on Mrs. Thatcher's free-market doctrines, which it says foster
greedy individualism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881012-0139 </DOCNO>
