<DOCNO> AP881012-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ProducerMurder     10-12 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Producer Murder,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Men Plead Innocent in `Cotton Club' Murder Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men charged with the 1983 murder of a New
York producer who was trying to finance ``The Cotton Club'' movie
have pleaded innocent, denying allegations that could bring the
death penalty.
   William Molony Mentzer and Alex Lamota Marti are accused of
gunning down producer Roy Radin, who authorities say was targeted
for death in connection with his unsuccessful attempt to finance
the film.
   Mentzer and Marti pleaded innocent Tuesday to murder and special
circumstance allegations of committing murder for financial gain
and lying in wait for the victim. They could face the death penalty
if convicted.
   Municipal Court Judge David S. Milton set a Nov. 7 hearing for
motions preceding a preliminary hearing.
   Five defendants, including Mentzer and Marti, are named in a
complaint dealing with the murders of Radin and of a prostitute,
June Mincher. Marti and Karen DeLayne Greenberger are not charged
in the Mincher killing, which was unrelated to Radin's death.
   Mrs. Greenberger, a key figure in the Radin allegations, is
fighting extradition from Florida. Another defendant, Robert Ulmer
Lowe, is awaiting extradition proceedings in Maryland.
   Robert Leroy Deremer, charged only in the Mincher killing, was
returned here from Indiana on Tuesday after waiving extradition.
   Prosecutors allege that Mrs. Greenberger, formerly known as
Elaine Jacobs, ordered Radin's execution after a dispute over her
financial cut of the movie, ``The Cotton Club.''
   Mrs. Greenberger, who authorities said was involved in cocaine
dealing, allegedly introduced Radin to movie producer Robert Evans,
who was then seeking financing for the film about the legendary
Harlem night spot.
   Radin, 33, who had produced vaudeville shows in New York, saw
``The Cotton Club'' as his chance to enter the Hollywood big time,
prosecutors said. He was embroiled in a deal to raise $35 million
for the film from Puerto Rican investors when he disappeared May
13, 1983.
   Radin failed to show up that night for a dinner at a swank
Beverly Hills restaurant. A month later, his bullet-riddled body
was found dumped in a rural area 60 miles from Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
