<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1411EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HongKong     10-12 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hong Kong,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Gives Optimistic Picture of Hong Kong</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Sir David Wilson on Wednesday delivered an
optimistic review on conditions in Hong Kong, but said problems
exist and they must be solved to retain the prosperity and dynamism
of this British colony.
   In an annual address opening a new session of the Legislative
Council, Hong Kong's chief lawmaking body, Wilson said he was
confident about the colony's economic growth despite public concern
over its return to China in 1997 when a territorial lease expires.
   He said Hong Kong's Gross Domestic Product was expected to grow
by 6 percent this year, or half the 1987 figure, but explained this
was the result of economic consolidation following earlier years of
double digit growth.
   ``Hong Kong has prospered over the past decades by maintaining
an open economy,'' he said. ``Nevertheless, we have to recognize
that we are dependent not just on ourselves but on the economic
performance of our major overseas markets and on our continued
access to them.''
   As an example of concern, Wilson singled out an unsuccessful
attempt by the U.S. House of Representatives earlier this month to
override President Reagan's veto on legislation to tighten curbs on
textile imports to the United States.
   ``We must continue to be aware of, and guard against,
protectionist sentiment in the U.S. Congress,'' he said.
   Hong Kong exported roughly $4.3 billion worth of apparel and
textile goods to the United States last year. It was the single
largest category in exports that totaled $9.2 billion.
   Wilson said Sino-Hong Kong relations are developing well.
   Wilson said Hong Kong still faces a problem over the
resettlement of Vietnamese boat people, who continue to arrive
despite a government policy to repatriate to Vietnam those regarded
as economic migrants and not genuine refugees.
   He said 133,00 boat people have arrived in Hong Kong since the
fall of Vietnam to the communists in 1975. There are roughly 25,000
still in Hong Kong, but Wilson said their rate of resettlement to
other countries has dropped sharply in recent years.
   ``The tragedy is that doors are no longer open for them,'' he
said. ``They are people on a journey to nowhere.''
</TEXT>
