<DOCNO> AP881012-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1432EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VenusProbe     10-12 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Venus Probe,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Shows Off Spacecraft Scheduled For Venus Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA officials hope that a
disassembled spacecraft sitting in crates at a hangar Wednesday
will be en route to Venus by April as America's first
interplanetary explorer in 11 years.
   The National Aeronautics and Space Administration showed off the
scattered pieces of the Magellan spacecraft to reporters and
photographers four days after the spacecraft's arrival by truck
from the Martin Marietta plant in Denver.
   If all goes well, the parts will be assembled and checked out
over the next few months and then transported to the launch pad in
March to be loaded aboard the space shuttle Atlantis, said Jo Ann
Morgan, the Kennedy Space Center's director of payloads projects
management.
   The scheduled launch date is April 28.
   NASA will have only 25 days, until May 23, to get Atlantis off
the pad before Venus moves out of its favorable alignment with
Earth. Otherwise the Magellan voyage will have to be delayed about
two years, said Charles Brown, Magellan program manager for Martin
Marietta, which built the probe for NASA's Jet Propulsion
Laboratory.
   Once the shuttle is in orbit, the crew will release Magellan
from the cargo bay and a rocket will start it on the 466-day trip
to Venus.
   It will be the first planetary probe launched from a shuttle as
well as the first U.S. planetary mission since two Pioneer
spacecraft were dispatched in 1978 to study Venus' atmosphere.
   Magellan is to settle into an elliptical orbit around Venus
ranging from 155 miles to 1,180 miles above the surface. Each
circuit of the planet will take 3.1 days, and during the 40 minutes
the craft is nearest the surface, an advanced radar will peer
through the constant cloud layer and obtain images of the surface,
which will be relayed to an Earth station.
   During each orbit, the radar, supplied by Hughes Aircraft Co.,
will map a swath of surface 15 miles wide and 10,000 miles long.
Brown said it would take 1,853 such swaths, recorded over 243 days,
to chart the entire planet.
   ``The spacecraft will be conducting basic research about how
Venus was formed,'' Brown told a news conference. ``To find out, we
need to know the topography of the planet.
   ``We now have the topography of Earth, the moon, Mars and
Mercury, but we don't have the topography of Venus because of the
cloud cover,'' he said. ``The imaging radar will give us that
topography.''
   Brown said Magellan will enable scientists for the first time to
study detailed images of Venus like those formed by wind or flowing
liquid, craters and large landslides.
   While Venus is Earth's closest neighbor in the solar system, the
two planets are vastly different. Venus has a surface temperature
of about 900 degrees Fahrenheit, its atmopshere is almost entirely
carbon dioxide, and its atmospheric pressure is 90 times that of
Earth.
   Brown said one goal of the mission is to try to learn why the
two planets evolved so differently.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881012-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1434EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan-Chad     10-12 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Chad,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Joint Delegation To Consider Security Problems in West Sudan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chad and Sudan are joining forces against
bandit gangs from both countries whose looting and robbing rampages
in recent months have resulted in hundreds of deaths in western
Sudan.
   Among targeted warlords is Acheikh Ibn Omar, once designated by
Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi as Chad's president, whose army
of 2,000 renegades is said to be hiding out in Sudan.
   A Chadian-Sudanese committee went this week to Fasher, capital
of the west's main region Darfur, to meet with Ibn Omar and leaders
of other armed Chadian factions. The Chadian delegation has been in
Sudan since Saturday, discussing ways to improve security near the
frontier to stop infiltration of armed bands.
   Border insecurity has bedeviled Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi's
civilian government almost ever since it took power in Sudan in
1986 from a junta that had ruled for a year after a coup.
   Brigadier Mahmoud Haren Hamad, Darfur's chief of police, said
more than 3,000 civilians and at least 100 policemen have been
killed by armed robbers in the region since 1984. Early this year,
he said, six or seven armed robberies were occurring every day.
   Mahdi and others have complained bitterly of the spillover of
the war between Libya and Chad. They have charged that soldiers
from both countries have sought in Sudan a haven from the fighting,
with easy pickings for robbery, or have used Sudanese territory as
a short cut between Libya and the battle fronts in Chad.
   Despite his outwardly friendly relations with Gadhafi, the prime
minister ordered Libyan troops out of Sudan in 1985 and again the
next year. Some of the 2,000 originally in Sudan are thought still
to remain.
   Gadhafi declared the prolonged war ended in May and resumed
diplomatic relations this month with the government of Hissene
Habre, formerly his bitter enemy.
   Sudanese officials have announced several times that the members
of Ibn Omar's troops had surrendered their weapons to the army.
Last week, however, Cabinet Affairs Minister Salah Abdul-Salam
admitted that only 955 men had turned in their weapons and said the
government doesn't know the whereabouts of the rest of the 2,000
men.
   But Tigani Sysi, Darfur's governor, told The Associated Press
they have entered the Jabal Mara mountains near Fasher, where they
are looting and robbing Sudanese villages and travelers.
   He said there are 32 different bandit gangs in western Sudan.
   The cooperative Sudanese-Chadian effort follows a series of
fruitless tries by the Sudanese alone.
   Last month, the cabinet committee decided to close Sudan's
frontiers with both Libya and Chad, but such a task is almost
impossible considering that the 1,000-mile border is almost all
desert.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
