<DOCNO> AP881012-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-NegativeCampaign     10-12 0855</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Negative Campaign,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Negative Campaign in '88 Is Both `Disgraceful and Effective,'
Expert Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was just two months ago that Michael
Dukakis stood in the Massachusetts Statehouse and scorned
Republican George Bush for having ``some of the highest negatives
ever recorded in American politics.''
   He was referring to the percentage of people who rated the
candidate unfavorably in public opinion polls.
   Two months later, it is Dukakis who has the high negatives.
Polls released this week show the Democratic nominee's unfavorable
rating now tops 40 percent, exceeding that of Bush.
   Republicans say that means Americans don't like what they see as
they learn about Dukakis. In no small way, though, they've learned
about Dukakis through strongly negative television ads and other
attacks by Republicans.
   Dukakis has begun responding with his own negative assaults. On
television commercials and in speeches, he belittles Bush's running
mate Dan Quayle, accuses Bush of plotting a ``raid'' on Social
Security and says the vice president is a failed leader who lacks
good judgment.
   All this is part of what frequently is lamented as the negative
nature of the 1988 presidential race.
   Minor issues or outright distortions are given high-decibel
treatment while hardly a whisper is heard about the national debt,
relations with the Soviets, the AIDS epidemic or the hostages still
held captive in Lebanon.
   Some blame Bush for trivializing the presidential campaign. He
has devoted weeks to attacking Dukakis over the Pledge of
Allegiance, weekend furloughs for prison inmates, membership in the
American Civil Liberties Union and the governor's slowness in
moving to clean up polluted Boston Harbor.
   ``It is true _ it's a very negative campaign, and I say most of
the blame lies with Bush,'' said William Schneider, poliical
observer at the American Enterprise Institute, a conservative think
tank.
   ``I say his campaign is probably the most disgraceful in modern
American history,'' Schneider says. ``It is also working. It is
both disgraceful and effective.''
   The negative campaign shouldn't come as much of a surprise,
though.
   Look what happened to two bad-luck candidates who talked about
the deficit. Democrat Bruce Babbitt and Republican Robert Dole,
like Walter Mondale four years earlier, discovered to their chagrin
that voters didn't want to hear about unpleasant realities.
   The negative campaign is hardly a 1988 phenomenon.
   ``It is more negative at an earlier stage than any presidential
campaign I've seen,'' said Democratic consultant Frank Greer, who
has been advising Dukakis on the debates. ``The 1980s have seen a
real escalation in the use of negative advertising.''
   Greer says it follows the pattern in Senate and gubernatorial
races. Democrats have become accustomed over the past eight years
to facing intensely negative campaigns centered on a few emotional
issues in state races.
   NCPAC, the National Conservative Political Action Committee, ran
a series of campaigns in which Democratic incumbents were targeted
with intensive negative television commercials on a few emotional
issues. In 1984, Sen. Jesse Helms of North Carolina ran negative TV
ads about his opponent for more than a year.
   The Democrats have learned to deal with such campaigns by
responding forcefully.
   Dukakis' running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, faced a NCPAC
campaign in Texas in 1982, when he was seeking re-election. He
fired back and won easily.
   On his campaign plane last weekend, Bentsen expressed relief
that Dukakis had finally begun responding with his own hard-hitting
ads.
   ``Where have they been?'' he asked, holding out his arms in an
expression of frustration at the delay.
   Bentsen said the Dukakis campaign should have responded
immediately when, after the Democratic convention in July, the
Republicans began attacks on Dukakis's record and even his
patriotism.
   Bush had some help, too.
   President Reagan's reference to Dukakis as an ``invalid'' was
quickly retracted _ but he succeeded in thrusting onto newspaper
front pages the rumors that Dukakis had hidden mental problems in
the past. The rumors were false, by all evidence. But the episode
coincided with the beginning of Dukakis' summer slide in the polls.
   Some say Dukakis and his advisers are to blame for failing to
anticipate many of the attacks, to recognize the visceral impact
some were having and to respond before lasting damage was done.
   Dukakis, after all, has never run against a serious,
conservative Republican campaign.
   ``One reason why he frittered away 17 points was because he
didn't respond and didn't go hard negative himself,'' said Larry
Sabato, political scientist at the University of Virginia.
   ``You have to fight fire with fire. You can't sit there and take
it. And you can't just occasionally respond and be defensive. You
have to give your response immediately, in tough terms, and then go
on the attack yourself. That's modern politics in a nutshell.''
   The reason campaigns have grown increasingly negative is that
such attacks work. The issues the Bush campaign selected seemed to
resonate with voters as symbols of something larger and unsettling.
   ``Bush attacked Dukakis' values,'' Schneider said.
   He said Dukakis hopes to score similarly with his attacks on
Quayle, hoping it will register as a symbol of Bush's judgment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
