<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Council-Arson     10-12 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Council-Arson,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Torchings Plague City Council</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TITUSVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City Council postponed its monthly
meeting after a third councilman reported that vehicles were
torched at his home and a bomb threat was called in to City Hall,
officials said.
   The burnings began in May, when Mayor Truman Scarborough's 1985
Dodge Aries station wagon was set on fire and destroyed. On Oct. 2,
fire destroyed a 1986 Cutlass Supreme and a 1983 Pontiac 6000 owned
by Vice Mayor Jim Brown.
   Councilman Tom Mariani was the latest victim, with fire
destroying his daughter's 1987 Dodge Shadow and damaging his 1980
Datsun and a small truck he had borrowed to haul campaign signs.
   A bomb threat was reported at City Hall later in the day.
   The two other council members in this city near Cape Canaveral
worry they're next.
   ``I'm not nearly as frightened for myself as I am for my
family,'' said Nathan Brown, who is moving an antique Ford to
another location as a precaution. ``If someone should come to my
residence, I am prepared to do what I have to do. I am not a sheep.
I'll leave it at that.''
   Police patrols will be increased around the homes of all five
council members, said City Manager Randall Reid. Tuesday's council
meeting was rescheduled for next week.
   Police and fire investigators say they have no suspects and no
motive, which could be something as simple as anger over a zoning
decision.
   ``To me, it's really hard to grasp what the motive is,'' Fire
Chief Richard Cherry said. ``Is it because it's an incumbent
council or because they're candidates or what?''
   Mariani was awakened to the blaze in his driveway shortly after
3 a.m. Tuesday by a neighbor's barking dog. On his way outside,
Mariani said, he heard a door slam and a car speed away. With help
from neighbors and passers-by, Mariani kept the flames from
reaching his house until firefighters arrived.
   ``This is crazy. You just don't do things like this,'' said
Mariani, who has been on the City Council off and on for 11 years
and is running for mayor this year. ``I'm just numb. I just can't
believe there are people in our Titusville community who would do
this.''
</TEXT>
