<HEAD>Two Students Found Guilty For Loud Pledge of Allegiance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Miami University seniors decided to pay
fines and court costs rather than fight charges that students
partying at their house chanted the Pledge of Allegiance too loudly.
   Police broke up the Sept. 10 party once, but issued a noise
violation ticket when they returned a second time and were greeted
by students chanting the pledge, tongue in cheek.
   Karen Stevens said she and her roommate, Kimberly Mart, had been
prepared to contest the misdemeanor charges, but decided to end the
case Tuesday rather than drag it out. Judge Mark Conesc found them
guilty and ordered them to pay a combined total of $76 in fines and
court costs.
   The judge asked whether they wanted to contest the manner in
which Oxford's noise ordinance is enforced. He said he could
postpone the case and appoint a lawyer to represent the women, but
they declined the offer.
   The women said they had been careful to ensure that the
``welcome back to school'' party would not disturb neighbors and
had checked with neighbors and police ahead of time.
