<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1502EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ArsonTown 3rdLd-Writethru a0672 10-12 0844</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arson Town, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0672,0862</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Charged In One of Series of Arson Fires That Plagued Town</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs with detail from charge, which is in
connection with just one fire; bail set, other detail. CORRECTS
suspect's age to 23 sted 24. Picks up 8th graf pvs, `Lance
Lalumiere...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY MITMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JEFFERSON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former volunteer firefighter was
arrested and charged in connection with one of the arson fires that
have brought months of fear and sleepless nights to this town,
police said today.
   Plainclothes police officers hustled Lance Lalumiere, 23, into
the police station in neighboring Lancaster this afternoon, and he
was arraigned in district court there later on a single felony
arson charge.
   Since May, 21 fires have been set in the White Mountains town of
850 people _ months marked by anger, sadness, worry and suspicion.
No one has been injured, but there have been some close calls.
   The fire for which Lalumiere was charged occurred Aug. 23 at his
brother's home. It was the 19th in the series of fires.
   Officials declined to comment on whether Lalumiere was a suspect
in any other of the fires. State police scheduled a news conference
for later in the day.
   The charge filed today was based on a state police complaint. At
arraignment in Lancaster District Court, Judge Paul Donovan set
bail at $50,000 cash.
   State police have released few details of their investigation,
which includes members of the state fire marshal's office, the
federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms and help from the
FBI.
   On Tuesday, Lalumiere was taken to a nearby state police
barracks, his brother Michael told the weekly Coos County Democrat.
   After the fire broke out at Michael's home in August, Lance
Lalumiere reported it and was trying to put it out when others
arrived. He was questioned for eight hours and police searched his
home and car, but he was not arrested at the time. In interviews
with the Democrat, he denied involvement in the fires.
   Lance Lalumiere was asked to quit Jefferson's volunteer fire
deparment when he moved to nearby Groveton. He has since moved back
to Jefferson where he works nights as a dishwasher at a restaurant.
   The blazes changed the rhythm of life in Jefferson. Many
families began sleeping in shifts and abandoned vacation and social
plans. Some residents began nighttime patrols to try to catch the
arsonist. Guns were left by the door in many homes.
   As the months passed, the initial shock became tempered by anger
and, for some, resignation. The vigils persist but have in recent
weeks been tinged with the knowledge that this exhausting nocturnal
life cannot continue forever.
   ``I have a feeling we're developing the same callus you develop
in Belfast or Beirut,'' said Charles Bond, a state senator and
Jefferson resident, before today's arrest was announced. ``If a car
bomb is going to blow up in front of your house, it's going to
happen. You're scared, but you have to live with it.''
   The volunteer fire department's 32 current members and 12 other
people have taken polygraph tests. Jefferson has no police force.
   In all of the village's 52 square miles of scenic meadows, woods
and hills, there are only 363 residences and three blocks. Now the
vistas are pockmarked by burned-out shells, some on back roads and
many on main thoroughfares.
   Most of the fires were set late at night, many at the back of
the buildings. They began with brush and fields, then escalated to
barns, empty homes and occupied homes. No one has been killed or
seriously hurt, though some barely escaped with their lives and
some have lost their homes.
   A mother of two, normally softspoken, now bites off her words
with anger. ``I want this person to suffer. I want him caught so he
can hurt a little, like we have,'' said the woman, who like many
residents spoke on condition of anonymity for fear of reprisal.
   Jefferson's families have prepared for each restless night by
activating lights around their homes that come on automatically
when they sense motion and letting porch lights burn through the
darkness. Some settle in for nightlong vigils of coffee, nerves and
sleeplessness.
   Unmarked patrol cars cruise the village on their way to back
roads. Police routinely stop cars traveling through town at night
and ask for license and registration.
   Tourists flocking to see New Hampshire's famous fall foliage are
surprised to learn this is the town they've seen on national
television and have read about in newspapers.
   Despite the natural beauty, many residents are hoping autumn
will pass quickly and winter snowfall will either make it easier to
track down the arsonist or deter him. But John Harrigan, publisher
of the Democrat, disagrees.
   ``I don't want it to snow and I don't want the fires to stop,''
said Harrigan, whose home was damaged by a fire set in early
August. ``One more fire could mean one more mistake'' by the
arsonist, leading to an arrest.
</TEXT>
