<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PedestriansKilled     10-12 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pedestrians Killed,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Schoolgirls Mourned At Funeral Services</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Final service scheduled to begin 3 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PULASKI, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sobs rose to the choir loft of a small-town
church as caskets were closed at a funeral service Wednesday for
three of the five seventh-grade girls killed when a speeding car
jumped a curb and struck them.
   About 1,000 people, many of them young, filled the Assumption of
Blessed Virgin Mary Roman Catholic Church for the joint funeral for
Laura Karcz and Brenda Hylok, both 13, and Nicole Watia, one month
shy of her 13th birthday.
   Services were scheduled later Wednesday for the other two
victims, Jodi Prokop and Jessica McKeefry, both 13.
   The Rev. Jordan Kuczwara told mourners they could cry and then
go back to their lives, or thank God for the gift of the girls'
short lives and learn something from them.
   ``Thirteen years young, but old enough to achieve something,''
he said, adding that the girls needed no drugs or alcohol but found
happiness in their friends, family and faith.
   ``Remember students, don't cry for them. ... Cry for those who
are looking for other ways to find happiness,'' Kuczwara said.
   Many sobbed as the three caskets were closed.
   The girls were killed Friday night when a Cadillac traveling at
an estimated 70 mph jumped a curb, sheared a utility police and
struck them on a sidewalk along a residential street about two
blocks from the police station.
   Investigators planned to check the car for possible mechanical
problems and to investigate whether the 17-year-old driver, a
diabetic, may have suffered a seizure, said Police Chief Reed
Woodward. No alcohol was involved, he said.
   The driver, who was a distant relative of Laura Karcz, was
listed in critical condition Monday at a Green Bay hospital.
Hospital officials said his parents had asked them not to release
further reports on his condition.
   His 11-year-old sister, who was a passenger in the car, was also
seriously injured.
   At a memorial service for the girls Tuesday night, 2,000 people
who gathered at the Pulaski High School gymnasium heard condolences
from President Reagan and a tape of one of the victims singing rock
star Tiffany's song, ``Could've Been.''
   ``The flowers you gave me are just about to die. When I think of
what could have been, it makes me want to cry,'' sang the
high-pitched young voice of Nicole Watia.
   Mourners hugged and sobbed as the recording was played.
</TEXT>
