<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PanamaCommission     10-12 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama Commission,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panamanian Members Boycott Canal Commission Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The four Panamanian members of the commission
that operates the Panama Canal boycotted the quarterly meeting
Wednesday in protest of U.S. policies toward the military leader
Manuel Noriega's rule.
   It was the second time since January the four have refused to
attend, but the five U.S. members were able to conduct business.
   ``It does deprive the commission of the input of the Panamanian
members with regard to Panamanian interests,'' commission Chairman
William Gianelli said.
   At Wednesday's daylong, closed session, he said, members
discussed the commission's $500 million budget and details of
moving dependents of some 1,100 canal commission employees back
home to the United States should they decide to voluntarily leave
during the current tensions between the U.S. and Panama.
   The commission was formed as a result of the 1977 treaty in
which the United States agreed to turn over ownership of the canal
to Panama by the year 2000.
   The Panamanians' boycott followed the indictment of Noriega on
U.S. drug charges, pressure from the Reagan administration for
Noriega to step down, imposition of economic sanctions against
Panama, refusal by the United States to recognize Noriega's chosen
president and this country's continued recognition of ousted
Panamanian President Del Valle.
</TEXT>
