<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SportAid     10-12 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sport Aid,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Organizers of Charity `Race Against Time' Go Into Liquidation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The future of the biennial ``Race Against Time,''
which raised millions of dollars for the world's poor, hung in the
balance Wednesday when its sponsor went into voluntary liquidation.
   Sport for Sport Aid Ltd., which organized the series of six-mile
road runs in 128 countries, relied on sales of T-shirts, entry fees
and television videos to pay for administrative costs.
   Sport Aid blamed its collapse on an August mail strike in
Britain that hampered the distribution of sponsorship forms. Only
215,000 Britons, one-third the expected turnout, took part in the
Sept. 11 event.
   The charity backed by the company, Sport Aid Foundation, ``is
unaffected and is still receiving money,'' said company spokesman
Nick Cater.
   The company owes creditors $3.9 million, Cater said.
   The accounting firm Deloitte, Haskins and Sells has been
appointed to clear the company's debts. Money raised by people who
took part in the Race Against Time won't be used to pay off
creditors, said a spokeswoman who requested anonymity.
   ``The question of whether we will be back and do it all again
depends on the people on the ground and those who took part,'' he
said. ``They put heart and soul into the event. They will decide
what is to happen.''
   The first Sport Aid race, on May 25, 1986, attracted nearly 20
million runners in 89 countries and raised more than $35 million
for African famine victims.
   The amount raised by Sport Aid '88 will not be known until the
end of the year, Cater said. A third race had been planned for 1990.
</TEXT>
