<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1843EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Nordstrom     10-12 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Nordstrom,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ursula Nordstrom, Innovative Editor Of Children's Books, Dead At
78</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW MILFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ursula Nordstrom, an award-winning
editor of children's books who handled the works of E.B. White,
Maurice Sendak and Laura Ingalls Wilder, has died. She was 78.
   Nordstrom, formerly publisher and editor in chief of juvenile
books at Harper & Row, died Tuesday at New Milford Hospital of
ovarian cancer, hospital officials said. She lived in Bridgewater.
   In 1945, Nordstorm edited White's first children's book,
``Stuart Little.'' Seven years later, White presented her with his
only copy of what became his classic ``Charlotte's Web.''
   ``I was overwhelmed,'' she wrote in a 1974 article in The New
York Times. ``I didn't dare take a chance on losing the manuscript
on the train home, or whatever, so I sat down and began to read.''
   She also published Sendak's ``Where the Wild Things Are,''
filled with the aggressive beasts of children's fantasies, after
other publishing houses had rejected it.
   ``With her incomparable editorial genius, Ursula Nordstrom
transformed the American children's book into a genuine art form,''
Sendak said Tuesday.
   ``I was there, one of her eager apprentices, profiting immensely
from her intuition and her generous heart. She was the best of
mommas, the best of teachers, the best of friends.''
   Her other authors included Wilder, who wrote the
autobiographical ``Little House on the Prairie'' series.
   Nordstrom went to work at Harper & Row in 1936. She became head
of the children's book department in 1940 and in 1960 became the
publishing company's first female vice president.
   Her books have won numerous awards, including three Newbury
Medals and two Caldecott Medals, the most prestigious children's
book awards.
   Nordstrom had no survivors.
   There was no funeral for Nordstrom, whose remains were cremated,
said a spokesman for the Lillis Funeral Home in New Milford.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
