<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush     10-12 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Plans To Use Fewer Statistics, Will Reveal `Heartbeat'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush engaged in some
light preparation on Wednesday for a second nationally televised
presidential debate he said would show Americans ``what my
heartbeat is, what I really care about.''
   Bush sandwiched several hours of debate preparation in between a
morning jog and a baseball playoff game at night.
   The Republican presidential nomineee expressed confidence about
Thursday's second nationally televised debate with rival Michael
Dukakis and told reporters: ``We do seem to be looking a little
stronger politically these days.''
   Bush spokeswoman Sheila Tate said the vice president planned
only several hours of debate preparation with aides Wednesday and
would not have any further mock debates. The last such sessions
occurred Tuesday morning and last Saturday in Washington with
sparring partner Richard Darman, a former deputy treasury secretary.
   Bush planned to take off the rest of the day to attend the
seventh and deciding game at Dodger Stadium in the National League
Championship series between Los Angeles and the New York Mets.
   Asked by reporters what he hoped to accomplish in the second
debate, Bush said: ``What I want to is have them (Americans)
understand what my heartbeat is, what I really care about.''
   He said those areas included ``foreign affairs, the defense of
this country, world peace, how I as president would build on that.''
   Bush added that he planned to cite fewer statistics in the
debate and talk more on ``how I would like to lead this country,
where I'd like to see us be in the nineties if I'm elected
president.''
   ``So I want to spell it out on that broader sense this time, and
let the others nitpick on all these other little numbers and
statistics,'' he said.
   He denied anew that he had been engaging in negative campaigning
against Dukakis, saying: ``What I have to do is make him be what he
is, and that he seems reluctant to do, and then I've got to be what
I am. And that second part is what I really want to concentrate on
at this debate.
   ``He can't run away from his past, he can't say today that he's
mainstream when he's been on the left-hand spectrum of the American
political process.''
   The vice president also jogged for about 20 minutes in a
municipal park with about a dozen students from the University of
California, Los Angeles, who all wore Bush-Quayle T-shirts.
   In a briefing for reporters, Ms. Tate said that Bush wasn't
worried about the possibility of a surprise blow from Dukakis.
``He's pretty good at dodging and weaving,'' she said. ``I don't
think we'll worry too much about unexpected blows.''
   She also said she doubted Bush would rely heavily on one-liners
in this debate. ``It ought not to be reduced to some kind of
show-business sting of one-liners,'' she said. ``And if it is, the
voters won't get as much out of it.
   ``Weeks of stories about handlers and crafting one-liners and
strategic responses takes a toll. I think they lose some
credibility.''
   Comparing this debate with the last one, she said, ``we rate
them pretty much the same.''
   And, she warned, don't expect to see a different Bush this time
around.
   ``What you see pretty much is what you get,'' she said. ``You're
not going to see an entirely different type of debate from his
standpoint.''
</TEXT>
