<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Shultz-Cambodia     10-12 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Cambodia,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sihanouk Says Khmer Rouge ``Moderates'' Are Acceptable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Cambodian head of state Prince Norodom
Sihanouk said Wednesday after meeting with Secretary of State
George P. Shultz that moderate elements of the Khmer Rouge should
be included in a new coalition government in Cambodia once
Vietnamese troops withdraw.
   While restating his view that Khmer Rouge leaders who were
responsible for ``genocide'' against the Cambodian people a decade
ago must be excluded, Sihanouk said moderate elements could be
included in a new ``collegial system.''
   ``Then we could control them,'' Sihanouk told reporters at the
State Department, adding that to exclude all elements of the Khmer
Rouge would ``make them bandits.''
   The Khmer Rouge, which is believed to have killed between 1
million and 2 million Cambodians during their 1975-78 rule, is one
of three factions fighting the Vietnamese-backed government in
Phnom Penh.
   Based on his talks here, which included a meeting Tuesday with
President Reagan, Sihanouk said his view of the situation in
Cambodia and that of the United States are ``practically the same.''
   Shultz reaffirmed the longstanding U.S. position that elements
of an acceptable settlement include a complete withdrawal of
Vietnamese forces and the emergence of a coalition government ``not
dominated by any faction.''
   ``We simply cannot see a return to power of the Khmer Rouge,''
Shultz said.
   Sihanouk, who was deposed in a 1970 military coup, reaffirmed
his view that leaders of the Khmer Rouge should be exiled, perhaps
in China.
   ``But they must not participate in the new government. Only the
ones who are the moderates who are not responsible for the genocide
should be accepted,'' he said.
   The Reagan administration is providing $5 million in non-lethal
assistance to the two anti-communist rebel groups and is consulting
with members of Congress about the possibility of an increase.
Vietnam has set a 1990 deadline for completing a withdrawal of its
troops.
   The Khmer Rouge is said to be the strongest of the three
factions fighting the pro-Vietnamese government and a major
international effort is under way to ensure that that group does
not play a dominant role in Cambodia's future political evolution.
   Particularly active in this effort have been the six members of
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations _ Thailand, Indonesia,
Malaysia, Singapore, the Philippines and Brunei.
   One of the measures being discussed to limit the Khmer Rouge
role is the establishment of an international peacekeeping force.
Other measures under discussion include the disarming of all
Cambodian factions and removing leading Khmer Rouge figures from
Cambodia.
</TEXT>
