<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     10-12 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KO2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends of Ruth Dowdell predicted she would
``scream and squeal'' when she returned home from vacation and
found her newly refurbished house.
   They were right.
   ``Oh man, this is neat!'' Mrs. Dowdell yelled Tuesday as she
walked through her home in northeast Oklahoma City. The cabinets
were neat. The dishwasher was neat, the curtains were neat, the
carpet was neat.
   ``This is God's doing,'' she hollered. ``God is neat, buddy.''
   And so, it seems, are many of Mrs. Dowdell's fellow Faith
Tabernacle church members. When she left town on vacation last
month, the congregation moved in to fix her dilapidated house.
   When Mrs. Dowdell, 63, left to visit relatives, the house had a
leaky roof, holes in the walls, gaps in the plumbing and hazards in
the wiring. When she returned, her house smelled of fresh paint and
hummed with new appliances.
   The church traditionally does such projects in other states and
in Mexico, said mission team leader Caroline Callahan. This time,
the church decided to do its work closer to home, for one of their
own, favorite members.
   Her friends first put on a new roof and installed new sheetrock.
Then a carpenter decided he could repair the windows, and a mason
took a look at the brick, and someone brought by a new water heater.
   D.A. Counce, who supervised the project, estimates the donations
included between 3,000 and 4,000 working hours and cash
contributions of $1,100. Counce figured the job, if contracted out,
would have cost $30,000.
</TEXT>
