<1ST_LINE>r w AM-TaxBill     10-12 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tax Bill,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Squabble Delays Negotiations on House-Senate Tax Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With time running out on the 100th Congress, a
House dispute over non-tax amendments delayed negotiations
Wednesday on a compromise package of tax cuts and increases.
   Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee, said he doubts the bill can become law this year
unless negotiators complete their work on Friday.
   But squabbling over some Senate amendments delayed even the
appointment of the House negotiators, who would be led by
Rostenkowski. The delay forced cancellation of a scheduled
negotiating session Wednesday.
   At issue are amendments protecting the Manassas Battlefield in
Virginia against some commercial development, and proposed
sanctions against Iraq for using poison gas against some minority
citizens.
   The Manassas amendment is under jurisdiction of the House
Interior Committee; the Iraq amendment falls under the House
Foreign Affairs Committee. Those committees could be expected to
demand representation among the House negotiators, which
Rostenkowski opposes.
   Wilson Morris, a spokesman for House Speaker Jim Wright, said he
expected the problem to be worked out, possibly in time for
negotiators to begin work Thursday.
   The House and Senate bills are designed primarily to correct
errors in the 1986 tax overhaul. They also include dozens of other
amendments that cut some taxes and raise others. The Senate bill
would raise about $3 billion over three years; the House version,
between $7.1 billion and $7.5 billion.
</TEXT>
