<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BabySwap     10-12 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baby Swap,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Ends Kidnapping Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI has closed its monthlong
investigation into allegations of a 1978 baby swap at a rural
hospital after finding no evidence that federal laws were broken,
an agency spokesman said.
   Ernest and Regina Twigg, a Langhorne, Pa., couple who sought the
inquiry, can ask state officials to investigate whether violations
of law occurred, FBI spokesman Russ Wood said Tuesday.
   The Twiggs claim their newborn was stolen at Hardee Memorial
Hospital in Wauchula nearly 10 years ago. Mrs. Twigg maintains her
healthy baby girl was switched for a sickly child and that records
were altered to hide the swap.
   Genetic blood tests this summer showed that the child they
raised for nearly 10 years, Arlena, was not their real daughter,
the Twiggs said. Arlena suffered from a heart defect and died
following surgery Aug. 23.
   The Twiggs filed a $100 million suit against the hospital and
some employees two weeks later.
   Wood declined to give details of the FBI investigation.
   But records show that during its probe the FBI interviewed the
Twiggs, subpoenaed documents from the hospital, and talked with the
father of a Sarasota girl who the Twiggs think may be their
daughter. The couple claim she was the only other white girl born
at Hardee Memorial at the same time.
   The Sarasota girl has not been identified to protect her from
publicity.
</TEXT>
