<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0660,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Predicts ``Clean Sweep'' of Debates by Democrats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 17 grafs with Dukakis appearance, aides'
comments, picking up in 3rd graf pvs, The Massachusetts; cuts last
5 grafs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis on Wednesday declared
Democrats the winners in the two debates thus far in the
presidential campaign and promised to ``make it a clean sweep''
with a win in his final showdown with Republican George Bush.
   Dukakis interrupted his preparations for the debate to toss a
baseball around with an aide and, sticking to sports metaphors,
described the pitches he planned throw at Bush during their
nationally televised debate starting at 9 p.m. EDT Thursday at the
Pauley Pavilion on the UCLA campus.
   ``A fastball, curve, slider _ maybe a knuckler,'' was the
Democratic nominee's description of his planned debate repertoire.
``We're ahead 2-0, we're going to make it a clean sweep.''
   Dukakis, sporting a UCLA sweatshirt, reacted firmly to a
question as to whether he thought it possible he would win the
popular vote but lose to Bush in the Electoral College count, which
decides the election.
   ``We're going to win, period,'' Dukakis said.
   Various polls have suggested that Dukakis is close to Bush in
the overall race but that Bush is further ahead in potential
electoral votes.
   Asked how Bush should handle any debate questions about running
mate Dan Quayle, Dukakis, who has been highly critical of the
Indiana senator, answered in a single word, ``Gingerly.''
   Dukakis shook hands with several people eating their lunch on
the pool deck of his Los Angeles hotel before returning to daylong
meetings with aides and advisers who traveled to the debate city
with him Tuesday night.
   Quayle is likely to be a prime debate target for Dukakis, who
aides say also will try to portray Bush as an insensitive and
failed leader who has offered no realistic solutions to the major
problems facing average Americans.
   Earlier in the day, Dukakis strategists from the California and
national campaigns assessed the campaign so far and what Dukakis
still must do.
   ``I hope we don't look at presidential elections as personality
contests,'' said Ron Brown, a former Jesse Jackson aide who now
advises Dukakis.
   ``We hope the American public will judge Michael Dukakis on what
he says and not on how he looks,'' Brown said. ``We think that the
American people, the more they see of Michael Dukakis, the more
thay are going to be persuaded by his view of the future.''
   As for California, Dukakis' state campaign manager, Tony
Podesta, said the Democratic ticket held a small lead in this
crucial state and hoped to expand on it through televisions ads
that counter what Podesta called ``some of the slime and lies the
Bush camp has been putting forth'' about the Dukakis record on
crime and the environment.
   Brown disputed Republican assertions that Bush has wrapped up
most of the South, West and Rocky Mountain states, but he added
that while Dukakis publicly speaks of a 50-state campaign,
targeting decisions will be made in the next few days.
   ``Obviously we are focusing on the areas where we think we've
got to win,'' Brown said. ``I think you see a scenario, a very
reasonable scenario, that indicates this thing is nowhere near
over.''
   Added Podesta:
   ``The Electoral College lock theory has about as much truth as
George Bush's television spots.''
   The Massachusetts governor, at airport rallies Tuesday in North
Dakota and Los Angeles, said he was looking forward to the
confrontation.
   ``One of the nice things about debates is they get people out
from behind the balloons and out of the flag factory and it gets
them to address the issues,'' the Democratic nominee said.
   On the flight here, his aides promised that Dukakis would be
ready to exchange one-liners with the vice president. More
importantly, they said, Dukakis hopes to convince voters that he
cares more about them and their children than Bush does.
   To underscore that point, Dukakis will discuss his recent
proposals on health care, housing and helping pay college expenses.
   ``This is not a pingpong match of one-liners,'' said John Sasso,
vice chairman of the Dukakis campaign and the candidate's closest
adviser. ``I think people are fed up with the meaningless labels.
Who's offering the leadership?''
   Sasso said Dukakis must convince the public that, under a
Democratic administration, they will get ``the benefit of the doubt
when the door of the Oval Office closes.''
   ``I think it's very important that the American people know his
values, know what he cares about,'' Sasso said.
</TEXT>
