<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GrapeLawsuit     10-12 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grape Lawsuit,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California Growers Sue Over Preservative Rule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California grape growers sued Oregon over a
state rule that requires restaurants to post warnings when they
serve fresh foods treated with sulfite preservatives.
   The California Table Grape Commission, which represents 1,000
growers, fear restaurants will stop serving grapes rather than post
the warnings, said Bruce Obbink, commission president.
   That could cost growers and food distributors several hundred
thousand dollars, Obbink said by telephone from Fresno, Calif.
   Kristine Gebbie, director of the Oregon Health Divison, said she
could not comment on the lawsuit, filed the lawsuit Tuesday in
Marion County Circuit Court. until the state attorney general's
office reviewed the case.
   She said, however, that health officials made the right decision
when they ordered restaurants to warn customers when foods have
been treated with sulfites.
   ``We've got allergic people who can react to any level (of
sulfites) and the only way to protect them is to either ban all
products with sulfites, or warn them that it is present,'' Gebbie
said. ``As I understand it, for a very sensitive person, any level
of sulfite is a problem.''
   The emergency rule, which expires in February, was approved Aug.
26 by Health Division officials after they learned that restaurants
were serving California table grapes and other items that treated
with sulfites.
   The rule accompanies a 1985 regulation that prohibits
restaurants from treating fruits, vegetables and other salad items
with sulfite-based preservatives.
   The restriction was pushed by the Legislature after the death of
a 10-year-old girl who died after eating sulfite-treated guacamole
at a restaurant.
   The girl's family sued the maker and distributor of the sulfite
product used at the restaurant. The Oregon Court of Appeals ruled
last week that the maker and distributor were not liable for
damages.
</TEXT>
