<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1731EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FarmCrops     10-12 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Crops,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USDA Estimates of Corn and Soybean Crops Up Slightly</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This year's drought-reduced corn crop is
expected to yield 4.55 billion bushels, an increase of 2 percent
from last month's estimate, the Agriculture Department said
Wednesday.
   The figure was still 36 percent below last year's harvest,
reflecting the heat and lack of rain that cut sharply into this
summer's production and still represented a five-year low.
   Soybean production was forecast at 1.5 billion bushels, another
gain of 2 percent from September's estimate, but still 22 percent
below 1987.
   The estimate was based on surveys made Oct. 1. A month ago, USDA
put the corn harvest at 4.46 billion bushels and the soybean crop
at 1.47 billion bushels.
   Corn is the largest and most important crop grown by American
farmers and as a feed is essential to the production of meat,
poultry and dairy products.
   Soybeans, which provide high-protein meal and quality vegetable
oil used in food processing, also are vital to U.S. food production.
   USDA's Agricultural Statistics Board forecast the cotton crop at
14.7 million bales, slightly below last year's harvest but above
the Sept. 1 estimate.
   Wheat production was reported at 1.8 billion bushels, about the
same as last month.
   The average yield for corn was estimated at 80.2 bushels per
acre, a sharp plunge from last year's figure of 119.4 bushels per
acre.
   ``Harvest was ahead of normal in the central and northern Plains
states,'' the report said. ``Crop maturity and harvest continued to
lag behind normal in most of the East.''
   In Chicago, influential analyst Conrad Leslie estimated soybean
production at 1.48 billion bushels and forecast a corn harvest of
4.55 billion bushels.
   His forecasts, which came out Monday, were higher than USDA's
September estimates. But analysts said Leslie's soybean production
figure was lower than expected and it sparked some buying of
futures.
   They said his corn production forecast was higher than expected
and sparked some selling of corn futures.
   Despite lowered production as a result of the drought, USDA
officials say stockpiles of corn are sufficient to prevent any
shortages. They have been estimating that the drought would add one
percent to the consumer price index for food this year and two
percent next year.
   The report said the ``all crops'' production index as of Oct. 1
averaged 89 percent of the base year of 1977, up 1 percent from
September.
   Crop production averaged 106 percent of the base last year. The
record was 117 percent reached in 1985 as well as 1982 and 1981.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
