<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Obit-Warren     10-12 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Warren,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lucian C. Warren Dies of Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lucian C. Warren, a correspondent who headed
three of the capital's most prestigious press organizations, died
of cancer early Wednesday at his Maryland home.
   Warren, 75, was former president of the National Press Club and
the Gridiron Club and was once chairman of the Standing Committee
of Correspondents, which regulates the congressional press
galleries. He had a 43-year career as a Washington journalist.
   As president of the press club, Warren led the campaign for
admission of the first black member.
   Warren served as Washington correspondent for newspapers in
Buffalo, N.Y., for 33 years, and since 1978 he worked as a
freelance journalist and Washington correspondent for the Frederick
(Md.) News-Post. He also wrote for Esquire and Parade magazines and
appeared on television and radio news programs.
   Warren, who was born in Jamestown, N.Y. and graduated with Phi
Beta Kappa honors from Denison University in Granville, Ohio, is
survived by his wife Katherine, four children; Sylvia, Lucian
James, Katherine Sites and Nancy Warren-Stringos and 12
grandchildren.
   A memorial service for Warren, to be announced later, is planned
at the Press Club.
</TEXT>
