<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Marcos 1stLd-Writethru a0699 10-12 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marcos, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0699,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Indicates It Might Wait On Charging Marcos</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS grafs 1-3 for clarity; PICKS up 4th pvs `Marcos and'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philippine government might delay
filing charges against Ferdinand E. Marcos until U.S. authorities
decide whether to prosecute the exiled former president, an
official said Wednesday.
   Mateo Caparas, chairman of the Presidential Commission on Good
Government, said President Corazon Aquino's administration would
not ``seek to obstruct justice in other lands'' or permit filing of
charges here ``to be used as an excuse by Mr. Marcos to escape his
indictment abroad.''
   He spoke after reports that the U.S. State Department's legal
officer recommended Marcos be offered a deal to avoid prison by
surrendering millions of dollars allegedly embezzled during 20
years in power.
   Marcos and his family live in exile in Hawaii. The Philippine
government alleges Marcos ad his associates stole up to $10 billion
before his administration was toppled in the 1986 uprising that
swept Mrs. Aquino to power.
   On Tuesday, the Los Angeles Times reported that State Department
adviser Abraham Sofaer recommended the plea bargain to avoid
indicting and prosecuting a former head of state.
   The newspaper said U.S. officials feared Marcos would seek to
embarrass American and Filipino authorities by disclosing improper
or illegal conduct if he were indicted.
   The plea bargain proposal reportedly involves an investigation
of Marcos by U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani in New York into
alleged illegal money transfers and other activities.
   Caparas told reporters that even if Marcos accepted a plea
bargain, he would still face prosecution in the Philippines.
   Filipino officials have filed no criminal charges against Marcos
for fear he would demand his right to return to the Philippines for
trial. Philippine law bars criminal trials in absentia.
   Caparas' commission is in charge of recovering money allegedly
taken by Marcos. He told reporters that Mrs. Aquino had asked him
to issue the statement.
   Mrs. Aquino has repeatedly refused to allow Marcos to return to
the Philippines, citing national security.
   Caparas said efforts by Marcos to return were ``either an excuse
to get out of America or a part of his campaign to destabilize the
present government.''
   Caparas also said American FBI agents seized $6 million worth of
paintings and other art objects during a raid last week on the
Woodside, California estate of Marcos' son-in-law, Gregorio Araneta.
   He said he expected the objects to be turned over to the
Philippine government because ``those paintings were purchased with
the Filipino peoples' money.'' Araneta is married to Marcos'
daughter, Irene.
   In San Francisco, U.S. Attorney Joseph Russoniello confirmed the
raid and said agents hauled away paintings, sculptures, Ming
Dynasty vases and antique furniture.
</TEXT>
