<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0655 10-12 0800</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0655,0820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Premier Wants Settlement with Guerrilla Field Commanders</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 20th graf pvs, More than ... UPDATING
with report of fighting. Picks up 21st graf pvs, Since then ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Mohammad Hasan Sharq said
Wednesday the government prefers a settlement with guerrilla field
commanders to a deal with leaders who direct the Moslem insurgency
from neighboring Pakistan.
   In a 90-minute meeting with five Western reporters, he made no
new offers that might persuadethe U.S.-supported guerrillas to stop
fighting.
   President Najib, the Communist Party chief, appointed Sharq on
May 26. The 63-year-old premier, who has close ties to Moscow but
is not a party member, has become increasingly visible as the
government spokesman.
   Najib has said he would broaden the base of his Soviet-backed
government by including non-party members.
   Speaking to the reporters Wednesday about negotiations with the
insurgents, Sharq said: ``If we are not able to have ways of
negotiating with all of them, we will have negotiations with some
of them. Those who are sharing the miseries of the people of
Afghanistan will come first.''
   Moslem insurgents began fighting after a communist coup in April
1978 and the Soviet Union sent military forces to Afghanistan in
December 1979. Under a U.N.-mediated agreement signed last April,
the Soviets are withdrawing their estimated 115,000 soldiers.
   The guerrillas were not a party to the agreement between
Pakistan and Afghanistan, which the Soviet Union and United States
signed as guarantors, and conmtinued fighting.
   Najib's regime is trying to establish provincial ``coalition
governments'' including representatives of the insurgents. If
successful, the strategy could neutralize the guerrillas on a
piecemeal basis by persuading them to stop fighting in exchange for
local power.
   That would return Afghanistan to its pre-Soviet situation: a
weak central government that survives largely through coexistence
with powerful local leaders who fight to the death for their
villages, valleys or hilltops but do not threaten the capital.
   Sharq expressed willingness to talk with Afghan leaders inside
and outside the country, including deposed King Zahir Shah, to
establish a new government and end the war.
   Zahir Shah lives in Italy and his return as a constitutional
monarch is proposed periodically proposed as means of ending the
current impasse.
   The premier would not say whether Asadabad, capital of eastern
Kunar province, fell to the insurgents Monday night as their
leaders in Pakistan claimed.
   Referring to government forces in the town 12 miles from the
frontier, he said: ``Maybe they are now under control of the
coalition government.''
   He said he spoke by telephone Wednesday morning to the Kunar
governor in Asadabad, who was ``trying to establish a coalition
(provincial) government and he assured me of progress that he will
be able to establish it.''
   Sharq said Asadabad's defenders were local militiamen paid by
the government, not army troopers. He spoke in Dari, the Afghan
language, and government officials translated his comments into
English.
   Urging the United States and Pakistan to stop aiding the
guerrillas, he expressed the hope that elections in both countries
next month would bring policy changes and ``the smell of blood of
innocent people will no longer be to the liking of the leaders of
the United States of America.''
   Soviet resupply of the Afghan army is not the same, according to
Sharq. He said the Soviets had been providing arms to Afghanistan
for 35 years, since the time of Zahir Shah, who was overthrown in
1973 by his cousin and former prime minister, Mohammad Daoud.
   Daoud was killed in the coup five years later.
   U.S. aid to the guerrillas began in earnest when Soviet troops
entered Afghanistan.
   More than 5 million Afghans have fled the country during the
civil war and 3 million are in Pakistan, living in border towns and
refugee camps that serve as guerrilla bases and supply points.
   Kabul radio said the army had killed two foreigners and 319
``criminal extremists'' _ guerrillas _ in an attack on insurgents
in Zabul, a southeastern province.
   It did not identify the foreigners, but much of the broadcast
was devoted to charges of Pakistani involvement with the insurgency
and the radio claimed Pakistani army officers were fighting
alongside guerrillas inside Afghanistan.
   Since his apointment, Sharq has visited Moscow and meets
regularly with foreign reporters allowed to visit Kabul.
   Najib's photograph appears less frequently in Kabul newspapers
and nightly television newscasts no longer are dominated by lengthy
videotapes of the president's activities.
   Sharq served as chief of staff Daoud's government during the
monarchy.
   ``In spite of the fact that I was the second person who waged
the coup against King Zahir, I have never been opposed to Zahir
Shah personally, but only to the kingdom, to the monarchy,'' he
said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
