<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Women-CivilRights     10-12 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Women-Civil Rights,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women Leaders: Women's Job In Social Reform Still Unfinished</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women helped launch the nation's major social
reforms of the 20th century, but now they need more political
power, speakers said Wednesday as they opened a first-ever
conference on women's role in the civil rights movement.
   Coretta Scott King, widow of civil rights leader Martin Luther
King Jr., said women continue to be a great moral force for social
change in the civil rights movement.
   She said during the opening session of the conference that the
next mission in the women's rights movement is to get more women
elected to political office, pointing out that only 23 of 435 House
seats and two of 100 Senate seats are held by women.
   She added that only one of those 25 women, Rep. Cardiss Collins,
D-Ill., is black. Three women are governors.
   ``Human survival in the future will depend on the political
empowerment of women. We women stood in the background and held
things up, to keep them going, over the years,'' Mrs. King said.
``We have a tremendous job to do each time we communicate with
younger people to help them understand what the conditions were so
that they can appreciate the progress that's been made and is
continuing.''
   Dorothy Height, president of the National Council of Negro
Women, said a forum to address issues concerning black women is
particularly necessary during the current political climate.
   ``It is needed today more than ever before,'' she said.
   About 75 participants attended the session, which was held in
historic Ebenezer Baptist Church, and sang songs from the civil
rights movement. The participants included female ministers,
activists, educators and students.
   The conference, being held at the Martin Luther King Center for
Nonviolent Social Change, was convened by Mrs. King and Rosa Parks,
who in 1955 refused to sit in the back of a Montgomery bus and
sparked protests that grew into the civil rights movement.
   The planners of the ``Women In The Civil Rights Movement'' say
it is the first such national conference and will be used as a
forum to address issues that affect women worldwide.
   Among those expected to participate are Molly Yard, president of
the National Organization of Women; author Margaret Walker
Alexander; Vivian Malone Jones, who integrated the University of
Alabama; Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young and Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga.
</TEXT>
