<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HousewifeRobbery     10-12 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Housewife Robbery,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mom Who Spent Family Savings Arrested for Robbing Bank</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRANT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother of three held Wednesday for robbing
a bank was apparently frightened that her husband would discover
she'd squandered the family's savings, police said.
   The 36-year-old Kent City woman, whose only past scrape with the
law was a speeding ticket, was arrested at her mobile home Tuesday
less than two hours after robbing the Grant City Bank, 25 miles
north of Grand Rapids.
   ``The only thing I can say is she was having some financial
problems, and she did not care to face her husband about it,''
Police Chief Stan Osmolinski said. ``They had some money set aside
to purchase something, and it was squandered away.''
   ``I don't believe she's your everyday criminal. I believe she
deeply regrets doing this,'' he said.
   The woman was being held in the Montcalm County Jail on $5,000
bond, the chief said. She was expected to be arraigned Thursday on
armed robbery charges. Authorities said her name would be released
at that court appearance.
   Ross Scott, the bank's president, said the woman walked into the
bank about 3 p.m. and handed a teller a note that read: ``I want
all your money. Give me the $100s and $50s first. I have a gun.''
   Scott said the teller gave the woman an undetermined amount of
money but triggered a silent alarm.
   Police arrested the women at her mobile home after tracing a
license plate number scribbled down by a witness. Money was found
scattered throughout the woman's bedroom, police said. Authorities
also found a pellet gun at the scene.
   Authorities said the woman cooperated with police and told them
she was nervous during the robbery. ``She didn't think her legs
were going to hold up,'' Osmolinski said.
   Beverly Norvell, who lives next door to the woman, was home with
her family when police arrived. The suspect's children, aged 16, 14
and 13, were just returning from school, Norvell said.
   Norvell said the woman was silent as police led her to a squad
car, but said the woman's youngest daughter was crying.
   ``The children were kind of mystified,'' Osmolinski said,
calling the robbery a spur of the moment act. ``They were wondering
why. They had no idea why she would do something like this.''
</TEXT>
