<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PitBullTrial     10-12 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pit Bull Trial,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pit Bull Becomes Cause Celebre, Escapes From Pound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAARLEM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dutch, a pit bull terrier who
narrowly escaped being put to death for killing another dog, was
sprung from jail by someone with a love for animals and a pair of
sharp wire cutters.
   The case involving Dutch has pitted a district court judge
against a homemaker who claims Dutch should not be punished for
killing a small terrier in June.
   Judge Cornelia Terwee ruled Tuesday that Dutch should be taken
from his owner, 28-year-old Saskie Van Poeteren, and placed in a
new home. But hours later, Dutch was spirited away from an
Amsterdam kennel.
   Ms. Van Poeteren said she wasn't involved in the breakout but
that an anonymous caller telephoned her late Tuesday assuring her
Dutch was safe.
   ``The gentleman just said, `Don't worry, it'll be all right,'''
Ms. Van Poeteren told The Associated Press on Wednesday.
   Dutch's reprieve from death made him famous.
   Police ordered Dutch destroyed after he bit another dog to
death. But a local magistrate ruled that biting another dog did not
make Dutch a threat to the general public and ordered him returned
to Ms. Van Poeteren.
   The prosecutor's office appealed.
   Judge Terwee ruled the fault was with Ms. Van Poeteren, not
Dutch, because the pit bull was not on a leash at the time of the
attack.
   She ordered Dutch placed with a new owner and fined Ms. Van
Poeteren $36 for violating leash laws.
   Dutch television interviewed Ms. Van Poeteren Tuesday as she
wept outside the courthouse over the confiscation order.
   ``He was just the cutest little thing,'' she said. ``I was sure
I'd get him back.''
   The broadcast showed a family snapshot of Dutch wearing his
owner's sunglasses, and a close-up of Ms. Van Poeteren's goldfish,
apparently to illustrate her fondness for pets.
   Even the authoritative NRC Handelsblad newspaper published an
article on Dutch's trial under the headline, ``Judges Chewing Over
Pit Bull Case.''
</TEXT>
