<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PreschoolMolest     10-12 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Preschool Molest,0582</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Dismisses 27 Counts in McMartin Molestation Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge dismissed nearly a third of the
charges in the McMartin preschool molestation trial Wednesday and
prosecutors moved to drop other counts, apparently because of
insufficient evidence.
   The 17-month prosecution case against Raymond Buckey and his
mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, ended last week with three children
failing to testify.
   Superior Court Judge William Pounders immediately granted a
prosecution motion to dismiss 27 counts based on their unheard
allegations. Prosecutors said the youngsters had refused to appear
because they were too traumatized.
   Deputy district attorneys Lael Rubin and Roger Gunson, who
sought to drop a total of 35 counts, said the judge should resolve
other matters before dismissing the eight counts based on testimony
of children who did appear at the trial.
   But defense attorney Danny Davis accused prosecutors of
attempting to ``cut their losses,'' by eliminating from the case
children who told incredibly bizarre stories of alleged
molestations.
   ``The truth of the matter is the evidence these childen
presented at the preliminary hearing was unbelievable,'' Davis said
outside court.
   Ms. Rubin and Gunson filed a new complaint listing 52
accusations against the 30-year-old Buckey, and 12 charges against
his 61-year-old mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, as well as one joint
conspiracy count.
   They cut the number of children allegedly molested from 14 to
11, nine of whom testified at the trial.
   Ms. Rubin told reporters the remaining evidence was sufficient
to convict the defendants.
   ``We've had testimony from nine children in this case and
medical evidence which strongly supports our position that children
were molested at the McMartin school,'' she said.
   Mrs. Buckey's attorney, Dean Gits, said the prosecution's action
was ``highly unusual,'' and said he'd never seen a similar
situation before.
   Davis called the development ``heartening,'' saying, ``Thirty
five counts are out without a breath wasted by the defense.''
   He added, ``It's a face-saving device. But it looks like major
plastic surgery is going on ... There is a major surgical slashing
of the prosecution case and it's by their own knife.''
   He equated it to ``the making of a $35 million settlement to a
$100 million lawsuit before the opposition has put on a case. I've
never seen that before.''
   Davis said he would move to excise even more charges in
arguments Thursday. He contends that at least four children who
testified spoke of acts that allegedly occurred beyond the six-year
statute of limitations for prosecution.
   If his argument succeeds, he said, 60 to 70 percent of the
charges would be gone. Pounders said he would study the law on
statute of limitations overnight.
   The McMartin case has been troubled from its inception and has
gone through repeated upheavals that diminished its scope.
   It began in 1984 with seven defendants and originally involved
claims that 41 children had been molested at the now defunct
McMartin Pre-School in Manhattan Beach.
   After a two-year preliminary hearing, District Attorney Ira
Reiner dismissed charges against five former teachers, saying the
evidence against them was ``incredibly weak.''
   The trial began in April 1987. Prosecutors called their final
witnesses last week, and the defense is scheduled to begin next
week.
   On Wednesday afternoon, Pounders went to the the site of the
closed preschool to see whether jurors should be taken to view the
scene.
</TEXT>
