<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0693 10-12 0616</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0693,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Puts GOP Team In Last Place</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Arkansas appearance, INSERT four grafs after
5th pvs, ``You don't..., picking up 6th pvs, ``At rallies...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate
Lloyd Bentsen said Wednesday the Republicans ``refuse to stand up
for the American economy'' and are avoiding issues important to
keeping the nation competitive.
   Bentsen, stalking votes in Missouri and Arkansas on the eve of
the second debate between George Bush and Michael Dukakis, also
aimed new barbs at Dan Quayle and accused Bush of trying
``character assassination'' against Dukakis.
   The Texas senator said the Democrats had no argument with
Quayle's assertion that other nations envy the United States.
   ``America is still the envy of the world,'' Bentsen told a crowd
of more than 2,500 outside the Columbia courthouse, many waving
tiny flags, ``but not because of people like Dan Quayle and George
Bush, who refuse to stand up for the American economy.''
   ``You don't stay number one by coasting,'' he said, responding
to Bush's assertion that the Democrats were trying to scare people
about foreign ownership of U.S. industries. Bentsen, chairman of
the Senate Finance Committee, pushed through the trade bill earlier
this year.
   ``America needs leaders who will stand up for the working people
of America,'' he said later at a rally at the University of
Arkansas at Fayetteville.
   He told the student audience that the Republicans consider
higher education a privilege of wealth, while Dukakis has proposed
a program so all qualified students could attend college.
   A strong contingent of pro-Bush students in the crowd of about
3,000 heckled as he spoke. They shouted ``Bush in `88'''and, when
Bentsen attacked the Republicans, ``Tell the truth, Lloyd.''
   Bentsen told the crowd it was a sign of how united the Democrats
are that he was ``saying nice things'' about Razorbacks just before
the Texas-Arkansas football game. The University of Texas alumnus
received an Arkansas football jersey that had his name over the
number ``88.''
   At rallies and in interviews Wednesday, Bentsen worked to make
sure Quayle remained a live issue for for Thursday night's debate.
   ``Today I read in the newspaper that Dan Quayle says he's going
to be his own campaign manager ... his own ``Dr. Spin Control,'' he
said at the Columbia podium. ``That may be his pitch, but I'll bet
it's thrown George Bush a real curve ball.''
   Extending the baseball metaphor, Bentsen said Bush's choice of
Quayle was another example of how the vice president ``swings and
misses.'' In the war against drugs: ``No runs, no hits, no
progress.''
   The crowd held up ``wanted'' posters with unflattering photos of
George Bush. He was ``missing in the war on drugs,'' the posters
said.
   ``And now Dan Quayle. He's no JFK and he's no candidate for
rookie of the year,'' Bentsen said. ``At some point, George Bush
has to take some responsibility for the quality of his decisions.''
   In interviews with local reporters, Bentsen rebelled at the
notion that Quayle might be getting sympathy because of the debate
outcome.
   ``Mike Dukakis is a man who's been subjected to a virtual
character assassination'' by a Republican campaign afraid to face
the issues,'' he said. ``There ought to be some sympathy for Mike
Dukakis.''
   As for backlash from his attack on Quayle during the debate,
Bentsen said it was ``minimal.'' If people felt sympathy for
Quayle, he said, ``That would be misplaced.''
   Bentsen said Dukakis would do ``an excellent job'' in his debate
Thursday night. After the first two debates, he and Dukakis ``were
2-0,'' he said.
   ``I think we'll go 3-zip,'' he predicted.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
