<2ND_LINE>AM-Citrus,000</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10 Percent Increase In Orange Crop Forecast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's orange harvest for the 1988-89
crop season is forecast at 217 million boxes, 10 percent more than
last season, the Agriculture Department said Wednesday.
   In its first forecast for 1988-89 production, USDA estimated
Florida's orange harvest at 152 million boxes, 10 percent above the
figure for 1987-88.
   California production was forecast at 61 million boxes, 8
percent higher than last year's harvest. Arizona's crop was put at
2.4 million boxes, a 33 percent gain over 1987-88 output.
   The report said Texas production was expected to be 1.65 million
boxes, compared with 1.43 million boxes last season.
   California's grapefruit production was estimated at 66.7 million
boxes, a 5 percent increase over last year. The Florida forecast
was for a record high of 57.0 million boxes, 6 percent above last
year.
   The Arizona crop was forecast at 1.3 million boxes, down 13
percent, and the Texas estimate was for 4.5 million boxes compared
with 3.8 million boxes last season.
</TEXT>
