<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-12 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sunny Skies Warm Much of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sunny skies warmed much of the nation Wednesday, although rain
and some snow hit a few areas of the West, and the East, from the
Appalachians to New England.
   Showers in eastern Nevada and western Utah turned to occasional
thundershowers by late morning and snow showers continued into the
afternoon over the mountains of both West Virginia and north
central Pennsylvania and in central New England.
   About 3 inches of snow fell by Wednesday morning at Clymer,
N.Y., and 2 inches at Great Valley, N.Y.
   Cold northwest winds were expected to continue to bring freezing
temperatures Wednesday night from the Great Lakes and the Ohio
Valley into the Appalachians.
   Frost or freeze advisories were posted for Wednesday night over
much of Michigan, Indiana, southern Illinois, Ohio, western West
Virginia, Kentucky, western Virginia, the Maryland Panhandle,
inland New Jersey, eastern Pennsylvania, the inland portions of the
Carolinas, the mountains of northeast Georgia, and northern Alabama.
   A light freeze was expected in northern and eastern Tennessee,
with frost scattered over the remainder of the state.
   Frost and freeze warnings were posted Wednesday for much of
lower Michigan, Indiana, Ohio, Kentucky, western West Virginia,
South Carolina, inland North Carolina and the mountains of
northeast Georgia.
   Temperatures were unseasonably chilly and more than a dozen low
temperature records for October 12 were broken or tied.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 33
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 92 degrees at Needles, Calif. The
low temperature Wednesday was 8 degrees in Embarrass, Minn.
   The forecast for Thursday called for scattered snow showers in
the higher elevations of northern Maine. Rain was expected from the
northern Pacific Coast across the Idaho Panhandle and northwest
Montana, with cloudy skies over the central Pacific Coast. Strong,
gusty winds were expected in the northern half of the Rockies.
   High temperatures in the 30s were forecast for northern Maine,
in the 40s and 50s from central Maine into northern South Carolina,
through the Appalachians, the Ohio Valley and the Great Lakes.
Temperatures were expected to reach the 80s in southern Florida,
and southern and western Texas. Highs through the desert Southwest
were forecast from the 80s to the mid 90s. High temperatures in the
remainder of the nation were forecast for the 60s and 70s.
</TEXT>
