<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-China 1stLd-Writethru a0647 10-12 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-China, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0647,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israel, China Sign Trade Deal, Plan Diplomatic Relations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with announcement by Foreign Ministry and
new detail</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel and China will establish diplomatic
relations soon, but the timing depends on progress in Middle East
peace negotiations, the Israeli Foreign Ministry said Wednesday.
   Israel television said officials of the two governments signed a
trade agreement Wednesday in Beijing. State radio said each side
established government-run corporations to promote trade.
   Avraham Tamir, director-general of the Foreign Ministry, said on
Israel television that diplomatic ties with China hinged on how the
Middle East peace process advances. He added that efforts to
achieve peace in the region would continue and ties with China
would be a reality ``in the very near future.''
   He confirmed news reports that Israel would establish an
academic center in Beijing but denied the first official Israeli
institution to be set up in China would have a political purpose.
   The state television report said Yitzhak Minervi, the ministry's
top economic official, signed the trade agreement on behalf of
private Israeli companies.
   It said the governments soon would begin negotiating an
agreement for Chinese coal exports to Israel. In the past, China
has rejected requests to sell coal directly to Israel.
   Maariv, an independent daily newspaper, said the new Israeli
trading company was called Copeco and 20 possible projects were
under study. A government official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said they focused on agriculture, medicine and medical
technology.
   Israel radio described the two companies as ``virtual chambers
of commerce or interest sections.''
   Three Israeli academics are in China to discuss the Middle East
situation. One of them, Professor Galia Golan of Hebrew University,
said in a radio interview the moves toward cooperation represent a
Chinese effort ``to increase contacts with Israel and to try to
warm relations on a semi-official basis.''
   ``The signal they are definitely giving is that, short of
diplomatic relations, they would like to improve contacts with
Israel,'' she said.
   On Tuesday, the daily Jerusalem Post said 30 members of the
Peking Opera will perform in Israel next May under a contract
signed in Belgium by Israeli and Chinese officials.
   There have been reports of arms trade between the two countries,
not confirmed by either side. The Sunday Times of London has said
Israeli military technicians were modernizing Soviet-built tanks
and heavy artillery used by the Chinese army.
</TEXT>
