<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Debate-Scene 1stLd-Writethru a0691 10-12 0618</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Debate-Scene, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0691,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Scramble to Prepare Debate Site on Six Days' Notice</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with LA City Council approving some funds for
debate, INSERT two grafs after 10th pvs, Commission director...,
picking up 11th pvs, At the...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers scrambled Wednesday to transform
UCLA's basketball arena into a television studio where the debate
between George Bush and Michael Dukakis could help decide the
Election Day choices of millions of voters.
   Debate organizers trucked in sets, lecterns and equipment
straight from the Oct. 5 vice presidential debate in Omaha, Neb.
They said things were going smoothly despite the time crunch.
   As the Republican and Democratic nominees spent a quiet day
preparing for their second and final debate, Ed Fouhy, executive
producer for the bipartisan Commission on Presidential Debates,
said the frenzy was ``intense'' inside the Pauley Pavilion on the
UCLA campus.
   Fouhy said his job was made easier because this university of
34,000 students is accustomed to handling big events.
   ``They have a whole special events staff that's used to doing
these things,'' he said. ``We plugged into that.''
   UCLA served as the athletes' housing center and site of the
gymnastics competition for the 1984 Olympic Games, and last year
entertained Britain's visiting Prince Andrew and the Duchess of
York.
   Vice Chancellor Alan Charles said the debate was ``a pretty big
deal'' but nothing the university can't handle.
   The University of California campus in Los Angeles was selected
last Friday after the League of Women Voters withdrew as debate
sponsor in a dispute with the Bush and Dukakis campaigns.
   The debates commission, established by both campaigns to handle
the first presidential debate in Winston-Salem, N.C., on Sept. 25,
quickly succeeded the league as sponsor of the Los Angeles event.
   Commission director Janet Brown said the league's original
debate site, the old Shrine Auditorium near downtown Los Angeles,
was vetoed when the league demanded reimbursement of $90,000. She
said UCLA offered free use of its 13,000-seat basketball arena.
   And on Wednesday, the Los Angeles City Council voted 11-2 to
give $25,000 to help fund the presidential debate.
   ``I would have supported it if it was open to the public,'' said
Councilman Ernani Bernardi, who dissented because only 1,500 people
will be allowed in the 12,500-seat arena and the audience of chosen
Republicans and Democrats would be waiting to cheer their
candidate's ``hot shot statements.''
   At the sprawling West Los Angeles campus, the floor of the arena
was being covered and carpeted Wednesday and partitioned off from
the rows of bleachers that will go unused during the debate.
   Organizers said 2,000 tickets will be distributed for the debate
audience in keeping with the intimate, TV studio atmosphere that
characterized the Winston-Salem debate and the Oct. 5 vice
presidential matchup in Omaha, Neb.
   The red-carpeted stage, the deep blue backdrop and oak lecterns
that were used in the previous debates were installed in the arena.
A press center was set up in the nearby student union building for
an estimated 3,000 journalists and crews covering the event.
   The debate format also will be the same. Each candidate will
have two minutes to answer a question and one minute for rebuttal,
with brief closing statements. The panelists will be moderator
Bernard Shaw of Cable News Network, Andrea Mitchell of NBC, Ann
Compton of ABC and Margaret Warner of Newsweek magazine.
   Janet Brown asked the Los Angeles City Council on Wednesday to
contribute funds to defray debate costs, which she said probably
would be substantially more than the $500,000 required for the last
debate.
   Raising private money for the debate has ``been a hustle,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
