<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle 2ndLd-Writethru a0750 10-12 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0750,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle: `I'm My Own Handler' Now</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To give new quote from Baker, SUB three grafs for 13thpvs, He
said..., picking up 14th pvs, Bush spokesman...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAPID CITY, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican vice presidential candidate
Dan Quayle, saying he had reached a ``snapping point'' over control
of his campaign by Bush aides, declared Wednesday that from now on
``I am my own handler.''
   ``I'm going to have fun, and I'm going to say what's on my
mind,'' Quayle told reporters as he left Indianapolis en route to
South Dakota for a fund-raiser and speech.
   The Indiana senator said he was ``not mad at anybody in the Bush
campaign.'' However, he had previously expressed irritation at
published reports quoting unidentified aides to GOP presidential
nominee George Bush as calling him a liability for the ticket. Over
the weekend, he complained to Bush campaign chairman James A. Baker
III.
   Quayle also has chafed at the rigid format dictated by the
``handlers'' from the Bush campaign, limiting his access to the
press, scripting prepared texts for him to read and even
determining when he would wave as he got off his campaign plane.
   He told reporters ``that's all been thrown away.''
   Aides said the decision to publicly assert control of more
aspects of his campaign was Quayle's alone and was not yet another
new script handed down from Bush officials. But Quayle's aides,
many of them Baker intimates, were openly delighted that the story
was dominating Quayle's campaign day.
   Beyond his speaking out, it was unclear what changes might be
seen in Quayle's campaign. His schedule is still determined by Bush
strategists, and even Quayle said he would continue to deliver the
speeches prepared for him. Those are cleared, at least in early
draft form, by the Bush campaign.
   ``There'll be some off-the-cuff (remarks), but there'll be some
scripted. I've learned that there is a certain value in having a
script,'' Quayle said.
   He said he will still coordinate with Bush officials and ``stay
in close communication with them.''
   ``They're going to suggest things that I say, suggest things
that I do, and I'm going to take that under consideration,'' he
said.
   Quayle said that as one who has successfully run for elective
office in the past, ``I know how to get votes and I know what's
best for George Bush.''
   ``I've done it their way this far and now it's my turn,'' he
added.
   He said he has cordial relations with Baker, the campaign
chairman. The two men spoke at length on Tuesday night.
   Baker said Wednesday in Los Angeles: ``These things are really
very regrettable and I certainly understand why he would be steamed
up about them. If I could find out who was putting them out, we'd
have fewer people working in the campaign.
   He said ``we're going to make a little effort'' to find out who
on the staff was talking to the media.
   Bush spokeswoman Sheila Tate said Baker had told a senior staff
meeting last Friday ``at the vice president's recommendation'' that
any member of Bush's campaign staff who criticized Quayle faced
possible dismissal.
   The matter had come to a head last Friday, two days after the
vice presidential debate, when anonymous Bush aides were quoted as
saying Quayle had not done well in the debate and was a liability
to the ticket.
   ``I think there is a snapping point that everyone goes through
and it snapped about Friday sometime, last Friday,'' Quayle said.
   This week Quayle started telling reporters, ``I don't anybody to
say well, here's what some campaign aide said about it. You ask me
and I'll give you the answer.''
   Although Quayle has been more accessible to reporters since the
debate, he has still not held a formal news conference since Sept.
15. He said he will try to have one soon.
   
</TEXT>
