<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Mondale     10-12 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Mondale,0329</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mondale Decides Against Seeking University Presidency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Vice President Walter F. Mondale said
Wednesday he declined an invitation to be interviewed for president
of the University of Minnesota, a decision that disappointed his
top backer for the post, Gov. Rudy Perpich.
   ``I've told the selection committee that I will not be a
candidate,'' Mondale said. ``You know, I love our university, what
it's meant to me and to so many of us ... but I just could not
persuade myself that this was the best role I could play. It's a
different world, you know, administering an academic community, and
it just didn't seem the right thing for me to do.''
   Mondale, a lawyer, had not expressed interest in the job
publicly, but Perpich had promoted him as the successor to Kenneth
Keller, who resigned as the university's president last March.
   Perpich said by telephone from his home in Gilbert that he was
disappointed by Mondale's decision but added, ``life goes on.''
   Perpich said he didn't try to persuade Mondale to reconsider
after Mondale told him of his decision Tuesday.
   ``You have to really want that; it's a difficult job,'' Perpich
said.
   The governor said persuading lawmakers to approve his budget
requests for the university would have been much easier with
Mondale at the helm.
   ``I was a little bit selfish,'' Perpich said. ``I wanted someone
to help carry that burden, and he would have done it and I think
very successfully.''
   The university's credibility has been damaged by turmoil over
spending on the university president's residence and office, which
led to Keller's resignation, and other problems during the year.
   Mondale, a former U.S. senator from Minnesota who returned to
the state to practice law following his unsuccessful 1984
Democratic presidential bid, said he has no current plans to run
for political office in the future.
</TEXT>
