<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HomelessRats     10-12 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless Rats,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Well-Bred Rats Orphaned as Researchers Squabble</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dispute between scientists has left 200 rare
and pampered rats without a hole to call their own.
   Carefully bred for up to 125 generations by Gordon Harrington of
the University of Northern Iowa, the rats represent rare genetic
strains. Some are masters at racing through rat mazes, while others
were bred with various personalities, or are drunks or drug addicts.
   The rats have bounced between Iowa and Michigan since they were
evicted last month from Lafayette Clinic, a state mental health
facility, The Detroit News reported Wednesday.
   ``I'm not sure what is going on,'' said Harrington, a psychiatry
professor. ``I have devoted my career to the rats. They are the
product of from 75 to 125 generations of precise breeding and
considerable study. But I suppose if we don't resolve it, this will
bring it to an end.''
   For years, the rats were bred in Harrington's lab in Cedar
Falls, Iowa. But in March 1986, a lab fire wiped out half his 1,800
rats. The lab was closed.
   Harrington took some of the luckless rodents home with him, and
sent others to laboratories around the world.
   In January 1987, the Lafayette Clinic hired Harrington on
condition that he bring along at least 100 of his special rats. He
brought 200, and the rats enjoyed a warm welcome.
   But they fell out of favor when Harrington was dismissed after
spending a month at overseas medical conventions. Clinic officials
contend Harrington had no research plans for the rats.
   ``He was parading around Australia, completing ignoring these
rats,'' said Dr. Norman Rosenzweig, acting chairman of Wayne State
University's psychiatry department. The Lafayette Clinic is run by
the state but staffed by psychiatry professors from Wayne State.
   Harrington denies neglecting his rats. He maintains that his
troubles stem from rejecting a Lafayette colleague's request to
receive credit on any research material published by Harrington.
   After dismissing Harrington, the clinic tried to send his rats
packing as well. But when the rodents arrived in Cedar Falls,
Harrington refused to accept them.
   The rodents spent part of last week in a shipping office until
the Humane Society in nearby Waterloo, Iowa, offered the rats
temporary shelter.
   Wayne State officials said they felt sorry for the rats, and
sent a truck on Saturday to pick them up. The rats are now in an
animal research facility while school officials ponder their fate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
