<HEAD>Reagan Tells Students Their Future Depends Election Outcome</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs to show speech delivered; INSERTS 2 grafs
after 11th graf pvs, bgng: ``His trip ...'' to UPDATE with planes
coming too close.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST ORANGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said the Republican
Party has become ``the party of working people'' as he carried his
campaign for George Bush into the battleground states of the
industrial Northeast Wednesday.
   ``The party that so many of us grew up with still exists, except
today it's called the Republican party, and I'm asking all of you
to come home and join me,'' Reagan said at a Columbus Day dinner
here.
   Earlier, the president told students and teachers at Upper Darby
High School in the suburbs of Philadelphia that he is concerned
about young people's future and ``the decisions we Americans make
at the polls this year will determine whether or not that future
will be bright.''
   The president mingled public speeches with private Republican
fund-raising sessions, meeting with 70 people who paid $5,000
apiece for a reception at a Philadelphia restaurant and attending a
similar function at an airport hotel after arriving in Newark on
his way to West Orange.
   In Philadelphia, he also met with Archbishop Anthony J.
Bevilacqua, head of the city's 1.3 million Roman Catholics, and
with the family of a policeman gunned down in the line of duty.
   In his West Orange speech, he reminded the audience that in his
earlier years he was a Democrat, and ``it is often said that the
once-proud Democratic party of FDR and Harry Truman is dead and
gone, that the Democratic party has been taken over by the left,
that the departure from the mainstream that we began to see at
their 1968 convention now defines the party at the national level,
especially the liberal leadership in Congress.''
   ``But there is something you should know,'' he added. ``The
party of FDR and Harry Truman couldn't be killed.
   ``You see, the secret is that when the left took over the
Democratic party, we took over the Republican party. We made the
Republican party into the party of working people, the family, the
neighborhood, the defense of freedom, and, yes, the American flag
and the Pledge of Allegiance to `one nation under God.'''
   The menu for the $20-a-plate Columbus Day dinner was salad,
ziti, meatballs, sausage, dessert and coffee. The affair was
co-sponsored by Italian Americans of Essex County and the Italian
Tribune, a Newark-based weekly newspaper.
   When he left the archbishop's home in Philadelphia, Reagan met
with the family of Edward M. Setzer, a policeman who was killed
Sept. 30 in Bryn Mawr while investigating a burglary.
   His trip Wednesday took him to two hotly contested Northeastern
states where Bush and Democrat Michael Dukakis are slugging it out
for a combined total of 41 electoral votes.
   Federal Aviation Administration officials said that as Reagan
was en route to New Jersey, Air Force One and a commuter plane may
have flown too close to one another, but the president was in no
danger.
   The president's plane and a Bar Harbour Airlines plane came no
closer than two miles horizontally and 500 feet vertically, but
should have been three miles apart, said FAA spokesman Bob
Buckhorn. The FAA is investigating the incident, he said.
   Telling the Upper Darby students that ``America's prosperity is
both an opportunity and a challenge,'' Reagan said:
   ``I am dedicating myself this year to making sure that this
future of hope built on opportunity and traditional values remains
open to each of you. I believe that the decisions we Americans make
at the polls this year will determine whether or not that future
will be bright.''
   Besides praising Bush, Reagan recognized the vice president's
controversial running mate, Dan Quayle, by quoting his comment in
last week's vice presidential debate that America is ``the envy of
the world.''
   The president also reminded the students that ``when you vote
for a candidate for the Senate or the House, you're voting for the
direction of the country and the world as much as when you vote for
president.''
   ``In the last eight years we have set our sights once again on
the enduring values of family, faith, neighborhood, opportunity,
and freedom,'' the president said.
   ``I believe prosperity and economic growth are the products of
strong values,'' he said.
</TEXT>
