<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Siege,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishop in Besieged Town: Pray For Peace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops and rebels are fighting
house-to-house in the besieged southern Sudan town of Torit and a
Roman Catholic bishop there sent a plea: ``We implore you to pray
for peace,'' a newspaper reported Wednesday.
   The English-language newspaper Sudan Times did not say how it
received the written plea from Archbishop Paride Taban. It
published the appeal Wednesday.
   The army meanwhile confirmed reports by the rebel Sudan People's
Liberation Army that the rebels had captured Ikotos, a town near
Torit. It said soldiers made a ``tactical withdrawal'' from the
town, 45 miles north of Uganda.
   The army claimed its 108-man garrison inflicted many casualties
among more than 3,000 rebels attacking from east, west and north
but gave no figures for either side. The rebels said Friday that 62
soldiers died in the three-day battle and that 300 fled into Uganda.
   The fall of Ikotos gives the rebels control over three towns
that form a triangle around Torit, capital of East Equatoria
province, 85 miles east of Juba, the largest city in the south.
Liberation Army fighters captured Kialla and Katire weeks ago.
   The Sudan Times said street fighting was reported this week in
Torit and that the archbishop has been sending appeals for food and
other relief supplies for the besieged populace.
   ``This is my last message to you,'' Taban's message read,
according to the newspaper. ``We implore you to pray for peace.''
   He said Catholic agencies in his diocese have nothing else to
offer Torit's thousands of hungry people, but the town has given up
on expecting help from the outside, the newspaper reported.
   It quoted the archbishop as saying he told his parishioners
``everybody should decide for himself'' what he should do, and ``we
cannot do more than pray for the will of God for you.''
   The Liberation Army began its rebellion in 1983 in an effort to
win autonomy for the south and now controls 90 percent of the
southern countryside and an increasing number of villages and towns.
   Despite heavy rains in southern Sudan this year, many areas
remain plagued by famine because fighting has forced farmers from
their land.
   Relief operations are hampered because rebels control
checkpoints on many roads, railways and the Nile River and
threatened to shoot at planes flying in the area without rebel
permission.
   Two civilian planes were shot down in 1986-87 with a loss of
more than 70 lives. A relief plane carrying about 100 people was
hit last month as it landed at Juba.
</TEXT>
