<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 2257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BoatPeople     10-12 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boat People,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain and Vietnam Agree To Repatriate Hong Kong Refugees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain and Vietnam agreed Wednesday to repatriate
Vietnamese refugees who want to return home from Hong Kong, with
financial assistance from the British government if needed.
   Britain said about 350 Vietnamese boat people who expressed a
desire to return home will be sent back in a phased program that
will start immediately.
   The agreement was announced at the end of a second round of
talks between a joint British-Hong Kong delegation and a Vietnamese
delegation led by the assistant foreign minister, Vu Khoan.
   The accord says both sides accept ``the need for comprehensive
arrangements'' for Vietnamese boat people who arrived in Hong Kong
after June 16, when the British colony moved to curb a steep rise
in refugees by ending its open door policy.
   A Foreign Office spokesman, who by custom was not identified,
said the 9,500 Vietnamese refugees in question are classified as
illegal immigrants and will remain in detention centers pending
outcome of further talks with Vietnam.
   Forcible repatriation of refugees who do not want to return home
has not been discussed with the Vietnamese, he said, adding:
   ``We will concentrate on the first 350. We hope others will come
forward and realize that their future is in Vietnam.''
   Vu said the returning refugees would be received in a
``humanitarian way.''
   Under Hong Kong policy now in effect, Vietnamese who cannot
prove they are fleeing political persecution are labeled illegal
immigrants subject to repatriation. Hong Kong holds that most are
actually economic migrants.
   The total number of Vietnamese boat people now in camps there is
25,000.
   Two weeks ago, Hong Kong began broadcasts aiming at Vietnam
explaining the new tough policy in a move to discourage Vietnamese
from heading there.
   The delegations also called on other countries to increase their
efforts to accept Vietnamese eligible for resettlement from Hong
Kong.
   They invited the U.N. High Commission for Refugees to take part
in putting into effect the accord to repatriate those Vietnamese
who want to return home.
</TEXT>
