<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Congress-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0735 10-12 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0735,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Still Working on Problem Amendments to Drug Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with tentative agreement on proceeding with
bill; picks up 7th graf pvs, bgng: ``He took...''; SUBS 11th graf,
bgng: ``The focus ...'' with new compromise on limiting criminal
appeals</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bipartisan group of senators working on the
$2.6 billion election-year drug bill agreed late Wednesday on a
formula for paring down the more than 100 amendments to the
catchall measure.
   Under the procedure, about 56 of the amendments would either be
folded into the bill, offered as amendments or killed by the
chamber's leaders. The remaining amendments would not be offered at
all.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., said the Senate
would vote Thursday on whether to follow the proposed formula and
begin debating the bill.
   Byrd said that if lawmakers agreed to follow the procedure, the
Senate could complete work on the bill by Friday. Congressional
leaders have been hoping that the House and Senate could adjourn
for the year by Friday.
   Byrd said that if the procedure for considering the amendments
was not adopted, ``It may mean we'll have no drug bill.''
   The majority leader said the drug bill would be amended to
include provisions giving prosecutors tougher powers to crack down
on child pornography, creating a new position of federal ``drug
czar,'' and stiffening sentences for some drug offenses.
   The agreement would allow votes on about eight other amendments,
including language stripping a provision establishing the death
penalty for certain drug offenders who commit murder, requiring
states to randomly test new drivers license applicants, and
allowing some drug offenders to lose federal benefits they might
receive.
   Byrd took to the Senate floor Wednesday morning to urge his
colleagues to refrain from offering amendments ``trying to indicate
who can be the toughest, who can be the John Wayne in the drug war.
   ``We can all be tough, but we've got a good tough bill,'' he
said.
   But some lawmakers were holding out for guarantees that votes
would be allowed on their own amendments. Included among them were
Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who was insisting on votes on proposals
to toughen sentences for drug offenders convicted of dealing with
children, and to deny many federal benefits to some people found
guilty of drug sales.
   ``I'm going to offer those two amendments if I'm here and
alive,'' Gramm said before entering one of the day's negotiating
sessions.
   The focus of much of Wednesday's discussion was an amendment by
Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., to limit appeals by convicted
criminals who claim procedural errors in their trials. By late
Wednesday, lawmakers thought a compromise might involve delaying a
final decision until after a commission appointed by Supreme Court
Chief Justice William Rehnquist presents its findings next year.
   Another controversial proposal, also advanced by Thurmond, would
allow some illegally obtained evidence seized in good faith by
police officers to be admitted in court. Lawmakers said a possible
compromise would involve writing into law the language from a 1984
Supreme Court decision that allowed the use of evidence seized by
police armed with a defective court warrant.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh came to the Capitol to urge
Senate Republicans to seek a bill resembling a tough version passed
last month by the House. That legislation included the death
penalty and many other provisions stiffening penalties and
increasing the anti-drug powers of the authorities.
   Lawmakers also had to decide how to deal with other amendments
that have nothing to do with illicit drugs. These proposals,
written by senators realizing that the drug bill could be the last
one to pass Congress this year, included language requiring warning
labels on alcoholic beverage containers and imposing sanctions on
South Africa.
   One thing the legislation lacked was a way to pay for itself.
Lawmakers say $1.4 billion of the bill's pricetag would be spent in
1989, but concede that the government can currently only scrape
together no more than $450 million to pay for it. The Senate has so
far voted down efforts to raise taxes or slash other spending to
provide the money.
   Even if the Senate should approve a bill, House-Senate
negotiators would have to agree to an identical version of the
legislation before it could be sent to President Reagan for his
signature.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
