<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Columbus     10-12 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Columbus,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexican Indians Protest Columbus Day Celebration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALBERTO ALVAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian demonstrators who say the discovery of
America led only to slavery and impoverishment broke up a Columbus
Day celebration Wednesday, and 12 people were reported injured in
the resulting street brawl.
   ``Long live Cuauhtemoc!'' demonstrators shouted, referring to
the last Aztec emperor of Mexico, who battled in vain against the
Spanish Conquest. ``Death to Columbus!''
   The Excelsior news service said several women, one police
officer and a boy were among those hurt in a brawl between
demonstrators and ceremony organizers.
   No arrests were reported during the ceremony to honor
Christopher Columbus, who came upon the New World on Oct. 12, 1492
while in search of the Orient.
   The demonstrators were led by a group calling itself the
Confederation of Indigenous Peoples and included residents of Lomas
de Seminario, an area in south Mexico City taken over by squatters
in recent years.
   Some threw sticks and rocks at ceremony organizers. Several
gardeners working nearby joined in and began throwing clods of dirt.
   The demonstrators ripped down flower arrangements in front of a
statue of Columbus and interrupted singing of the Mexican national
anthem and Columbus Day speeches during the short-lived ceremony
attended by about 300 people.
   Another Indian group, the Center of Pre-American Culture,
demonstrated peacefully on Tuesday in the Zocalo, a downtown plaza.
The coalition of 52 organizations held a celebration of Indian
dances, music, art and poetry in asking for abolition of Columbus
Day as a holiday.
   Excelsior quoted Center president Miguel Angel Mendoza as saying
Tuesday that Columbus' arrival ``began the enslavement, the
destruction of our ancient cultures and the stealing of our riches,
something that hasn't stopped in 500 years.''
   ``What the whites want to believe is that Indian children aren't
born in our country anymore,'' Mendoza said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
