<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0737,0737</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trump To Buy Eastern Shuttle for $365 Million Cash</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 18th graf pvs `Neither Pan...' to UPDATE with earnings
for Eastern shuttle, picks up 19th graf `The shuttle...'; a version
moved on financial wire. Stands for story datelined ATLANTIC CITY
on news advisory.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY97</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Real estate mogul Donald Trump announced
Wednesday he has agreed to buy Eastern Airlines' profitable
Northeast air shuttle for $365 million in cash and will rename it
after himself.
   ``I want to run it as a diamond, an absolute diamond,'' Trump
proclaimed to reporters at a news conference with Texas Air Corp.
Chairman Frank Lorenzo at the Plaza Hotel in New York, another
recent Trump acquisition.
   He said the three-city service would be renamed ``The Trump
Shuttle'' and its blue-silver Boeing 727s would be redecorated and
emblazoned with red, black and gold stripes.
   The deal is expected to be completed by mid-December, if it
survives government scrutiny and a legal attack by Eastern's
unions, who said the sale would be the death of the airline and
vowed a fight to overturn the deal.
   The announcement followed a week of speculation about the
billionaire developer's interest in buying the shuttle from ailing
Eastern, which is a major subsidiary of Texas Air.
   The price was well above previous estimates of what Trump would
pay.
   ``It's top dollar,'' said Robert Joedicke, an airline analyst
for the investment firm Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Many analysts and other observers had estimated that the shuttle
_ which serves New York, Boston and Washington, D.C., and is the
most profitable of Eastern's operations _ could fetch $200 million
to $300 million. Texas Air had tried earlier this year to transfer
the shuttle operation from Eastern to a new subsidiary for $225
million, but Eastern unions blocked that attempt.
   Standard & Poor's Corp., in announcing that it was keeping a
close eye on Eastern in the wake of the shuttle sale, said $365
million was ``a generous price.'' The interest on that sum could
recover more than half the cash flow that would be lost by selling
the shuttle, the credit-rating agency said.
   For the image-conscious Trump, the purchase could be viewed more
as a way to enhance his prestige and influence than a straight
business deal.
   Earlier this year, Trump bought the legendary Plaza Hotel for
$400 million following a heated battle with other suitors. Trump
has admitted that he was ``in love'' with the hotel for more than a
decade and ``tore himself up'' to get it.
   But there also could be compelling business logic behind Trump's
latest acquisition. Many analysts said Trump might use the shuttle
to help draw people to his hotel and casino properties in Atlantic
City, N.J., on the weekends.
   ``It's something that we're looking at,'' Trump said.
   Trump now operates a helicopter service from New York to
Atlantic City. The resort city's Bader Field is too small to handle
the Boeing 727s operated by the shuttle, but the Atlantic City
Airport 10 miles from the city can accommodate them.
   Trump noted a report that he intended to sell the land earmarked
for a huge commercial development in Manhattan to help finance the
shuttle deal, but he did not directly address its accuracy. No
interested party could afford to pay him what the 100-acre site is
worth, he joked to reporters.
   Trump and Lorenzo said the shuttle would maintain fares
competitive with the shuttle service of Pan Am Corp. and would not
lay off any employees. The $365 million includes landing rights at
airports in the three shuttle cities plus 17 planes.
   Pan Am said it welcomed Trump into the shuttle market. Pan Am
claims its share of that market has jumped from around 24 percent
in October 1986 to roughly 45 percent.
   Eastern said the airline's shuttle service had net income of
around $16.8 million in 1987 on revenue of $40.3 million, down from
a 1985 profit of $28.2 million on revenue of $49.2 million,
according to spokesman Robin Matell. Pan Am has not disclosed
earnings from its shuttle operations.
   The shuttle deal marks another tumultuous chapter in the saga of
Eastern, the Miami-based carrier that has been scarred by
management-labor feuding and $1 billion in losses over the past
decade.
</TEXT>
