<2ND_LINE>AM-Kidnapping Plea,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Church Janitor Pleads Guilty To Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deaf former church janitor pleaded guilty
Wednesday to charges of kidnapping and molesting two girls, keeping
one in a dirt crawl space under the church's altar for as long as
six weeks.
   Kenneth Alvin Michel, 32, entered the plea to two counts of
kidnapping, one count of attempted kidnapping and seven counts of
child molestation, said prosecutor Ken Peterson. Michel uses sign
language and head nods to speak through an interpreter.
   Prosecutors filed an amended complaint that dropped another
molestation charge, Peterson said.
   ``He freely admitted molesting both children but would not admit
to one particular molest on (one of the girls),'' Peterson said,
explaining why prosecutors decided to drop one count.
   Michel was accused of kidnapping 4-year-old Candi Talarico on
June 4 as she played with friends outside her downtown apartment.
Her disappearance drew national television attention.
   Six weeks later, Michel attempted to kidnap a 6-year-old girl in
suburban Elk Grove and then kidnapped a 5-year-old girl, Muey Han
Saefong, outside her downtown Sacramento apartment.
   A passing motorist saw the attempted kidnapping and followed
Michel's car and got his license number. Police used the number to
trace Michel to the United Methodist Church in Elk Grove.
   Officers found Saefong tied and gagged in the back of Michel's
car. They found Talarico in the church, in a 7-by-9-by-3-foot space
under the floor.
   The space was furnished with blankets, stuffed animals, books,
food, lights, a television, and newspapers that contained articles
about the kidnapping, which was featured on Fox Broadcasting Co.'s
``America's Most Wanted.''
   Michel faces up to 62 years in prison. Sentencing was scheduled
for Dec. 7.
</TEXT>
