<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1432EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-AmericanCampaigners ADV17   10-12 1048</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American Campaigners, ADV 17,1084</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Oct. 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>American Advisers Export Yankee Campaign Know-How</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oscar Arias Sanchez was making a big mistake in
his 1986 campaign for the presidency of Costa Rica, said his
campaign manager from the United States.
   Play down domestic economic issues, New Yorker Joe Napolitan
urged Arias. Instead, emphasize the need for peace in Central
America.
   Arias turned around his losing campaign, won the election and
went on to father a Central American peace plan that won him the
1987 Nobel Peace Prize.
   The election was one more victory for the peripatetic Americans
who are finding more and more work these days as advisers to
foreign political campaigns.
   For 20 years, Americans have traveled the world to help
candidates in both fledgling and longstanding democracies decide
which issues are the key to success in their races. They also tutor
them in the latest U.S. electioneering techniques and technology.
   Sensitive to any suggestion that they change the nature of the
political systems they intervene in, U.S. campaign firms and
advisers keep a low profile. But Americans have been deeply
involved in national elections in more than 30 nations, including
Australia, Canada, Panama, Spain, Britain, France, Ireland,
Nigeria, Mexico, the Philippines, Japan and Greece.
   In Israel, with a presidential election scheduled for Nov. 1,
Labor Party leader Shimon Peres is getting presidential campaign
advice from David Sawyer of the Sawyer-Miller Group, based in New
York.
   Sawyer's firm also advised members of the opposition in Chile,
where a well-organized campaign against the president, Gen. Augusto
Pinochet, resulted this month in voters rejecting his bid for
another term.
   While the Americans claim credit for electing their clients,
most of them strenuously deny having any influence in the
subsequent policy of the government.
   The theme of a campaign, however, invariably determines the
public's expectations of the winner's policy.
   ``I think it's the same as in America,'' acknowledged Joe
Cerrell, president of the International Association of Political
Consultants. ``I don't see much difference. They can impact policy;
they can change governments.''
   Some might think Americans in foreign campaigns would be
controversial, with opposition candidates claiming U.S.
manipulation. There's good reason why that rarely happens.
   ``All the sides use them, so it would be the pot calling the
kettle black,'' said Larry Sabato, a professor of political science
at the University of Virginia. For instance, both Corazon Aquino
and Ferdinand Marcos had U.S. advisers in their presidential
election.
   ``Actually, to people assessing whether to take us or not, it
doesn't appear to be a question of `Are we compromising on our
values by taking in outsiders?''' said Mark Malloch-Brown, a
British adviser from Sawyer-Miller, who advised Mrs. Aquino in her
1984-85 presidential campaign.
   ``The way they see it is, `If we bring in state-of-the-art
techniques, is there a way we can win this election more
effectively, more honestly?'''
   Cerrell agreed that Arias' campaign on the Central American
peace issue was a prime example of a campaign strategy that had
far-reaching implications long after the election.
   Oddly enough, Arias was opposed to that campaign strategy,
Napolitan recalls.
   ``His argument was that everybody's in favor of peace; nobody is
in favor of war,'' Napolitan said.
   ``We agreed with that, but pointed out that the more he started
talking about peace, the more he would become identified as the
peace candidate. And that's what happened, and to his credit he
carried through after the election by coming out with his peace
plan.''
   Advisers are evasive about how much they earn. They say it is a
business secret and that their charges vary widely, depending on
the length of a campaign and what services a client needs.
   Published estimates of charges suggest a national campaign by a
top U.S. adviser costs about $150,000 for the basic consultant's
fee, with expenses tripling the bill.
   Sawyer said his firm advises some candidates, such as Mrs.
Aquino, for free.
   Sawyer-Miller maintains contracts with some clients even after
the election.
   ``To keep a high enough level of mobilization and enthusiasm for
the (political) goals you're trying to achieve,'' said
Malloch-Brown, ``requires a constant political campaign-type
dialogue with the population.''
   Napolitan has longstanding contracts with Venezuelan parties,
where he has been running campaigns since the early 1970s.
   Campaign advisers typically go to a country, conduct polls to
find out what the key issues are among uncommitted voters, then
target those ``swing'' issues, which may not be the concerns of the
majority of the public.
   Sabato, an expert on campaign advisers, believes reliance on
advisers and polls to chose campaign themes leads to passive,
reaction-oriented government.
   ``I think there's a natural tension between a representative's
role as a delegate, a faithful mirror of the constituency, and as a
trustee, someone who is charged with making the right decisions,
even if they are unpopular,'' said Sabato.
   ``If you are wedded to polling results, and if they are readily
available to you and consultants are constantly whispering in your
ear and telling you what people are demanding, you're much more
inclined to fulfill your delegate's role to the detriment of your
trusteeship.''
   The consultants flatly disagree.
   ``You can't have it both ways. Sometimes you have presidents in
this country and others who are criticized because they are poorly
advised or don't have advisers,'' said Napolitan.
   ``You can't say the guy should not have advisers; what is the
whole government for, really, but to advise the president? What's
the difference if he gets expertise inside the country or outside
the country?''
   The International Association of Political Consultants has about
125 members, more than half of them American. Most of the rest are
from Europe, but there are also Australian, Japanese, South and
Central American and Middle Eastern members.
   American advisers draw on the experience they gain in the
elaborate U.S. campaigns for Congress and the presidency.
   ``This year, we'll have 400 or 500 elections in America, many of
them very hard-fought campaigns with a lot of money being spent,''
said Napolitan. ``Venezuela has one every five years. ... I work on
more elections in a two-year period, for example, than any Latin
American has worked on in his life.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Oct. 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
