<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WeekendTV-Williams ADV21-23   10-12 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekend TV-Williams, ADV 21-23,0814</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Oct. 21-23, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Steven Williams Is `Father Figure' of `21 Jump Street'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA2 of Oct. 10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's a familiar role: the voice of wisdom and
experience prevailing over headstrong young charges eager to take
on the world.
   Lorne Greene was the father figure, as well as the father, in
``Bonanza.'' Tige Andrews looked after hippie cops in ``The Mod
Squad.'' Harry Morgan was the gruff but forgiving leader of the
misfits in ``M-A-S-H.''
   In the case of Fox Broadcasting Co.'s hard-driving, pulsating,
young crime drama, ``21 Jump Street,'' the job goes to Steven
Williams.
   Williams, as Capt. Adam Fuller, oversees a squad of rookie cops
whose baby-faced looks allow them to pose as teen-age toughs and
ferret out high-school criminals. The show also stars Johnny Depp,
Holly Robinson, Dustin Nguyen and Peter DeLuise. Richard Grieco
joins the cast in the new season as a rebel policeman partnered
with Depp.
   ``I'm the daddy of `Jump Street,''' said Williams in an
interview the day before he returned to Vancouver, Canada, to
resume filming on the series.
   ``Peter calls me `the eye of the storm.' I'm the big cheese in
charge. The Fuller we like to see is the consummate professional
cop. That's his job. He teaches these young people. He's their
friend, but he's also a student himself. He learns from them. His
first duty is to make sure his wards become good cops and survive.
Undercover work is dangerous, both physically and mentally.''
   The tall, slender actor, with a beard and moustache, took over
the role from Frederic Forrest after about six episodes. Forrest's
role was written as a throwback to the 1960s. But the producers
felt the young people who watch the show couldn't relate to that.
Fuller is a very contemporary character.
   Williams previously starred as Lt. Jefferson Burnett on the
first season of CBS' ``The Equalizer'' and was the policeman in hot
pursuit of John Belushi and Dan Aykroyd in ``Blues Brothers.''
   Prior to taking over the role, he rode with officers from the
Los Angeles Police Department.
   ``I learned from that how dangerous undercover work is,'' he
said. ``They put their lives on the line every day. They deal with
the worst element. And when you're undercover it can be emotionally
tough because you lose your identity. You start to identify with
the other side.''
   Williams said he also asked policemen what they think when they
see officers portrayed on television. ``They said they hate seeing
cops do dumb things,'' he said. ``You always see a cop stick his
finger in dope and taste it. Real cops never do that. It could be
some bad stuff and they'd die. You see cops check their weapons
with all the sound effects _ click, click, click! Cops know their
weapons; they don't have to do that.''
   ``21 Jump Street'' is currently Fox's third highest-rated show,
behind ``America's Most Wanted'' and ``Married ... With Children.''
It was the fledgling network's top show before the debut of
``America's Most Wanted.''
   The show recently received a Presidential Citation for tackling
such issues as teen-age drug abuse, AIDS, gang violence, runaways,
child abuse and pornography. It has also frequently provided
hotline numbers where youths can find help.
   ``My character has gone undercover a few times,'' Williams said.
``Once as a uniformed cop and once as a man looking for a loan. I
could go undercover as a teacher to look for guns in a school. The
show provides an opportunity for me to stretch as an actor.
   ``I'd like to work undercover as a priest, as a bum, a nightclub
singer. You can play a lot of different attitudes. Fuller could
even go undercover and do a school production of `Othello.'''
   Williams was born in Memphis, Tenn., but he spent time with his
father in Flint, Mich., his mother in Chicago and his maternal
grandparents in Millington, Tenn. He discovered acting while in the
Army in West Germany. He was a boxer, and he and a friend began to
stage mock fights to develop their timing and reflexes. That led to
an interest in acting.
   On his return to Chicago, he became a model, then got into local
theater when he returned to Chicago. He also appeared in a number
of movies filmed in Chicago _ ``Mahogany,'' ``Cooley High,''
``Dummy'' and ``Blues Brothers.''
   He moved to Los Angeles in 1980 and immediately was cast in
various series and feature and TV movies.
   His role as the father figure in ``21 Jump Street'' is not a new
one. He has two grown daughters. His wife, Ann Geddes, is a talent
agent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Oct. 21-23</NOTE>
