<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WeekendTV-Loggia ADV28-30   10-12 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekend TV-Loggia, ADV 28-30,0900</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv30</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Oct. 28-30, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Robert Loggia Is Maverick FBI Agent in NBC's `Favorite Son'</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The political coverup in the NBC miniseries
``Favorite Son'' might have worked if the conspirators hadn't
underestimated the cynical, jaded, veteran FBI agent assigned to
the case.
   An unknown sniper has assassinated a Contra leader and wounded a
U.S. senator on the Capitol steps, and the president's chief of
staff doesn't want the case solved.
   So the case goes to Nick Mancuso, an FBI agent on the verge of
retirement, and David Ross, an inexperienced young agent.
   ``He's not over the hill,'' said Robert Loggia, who plays
Mancuso. ``He's being forced to retire at 55, because that's FBI
policy. He's a maverick agent, which exists in the FBI. They're not
all plastic men. The heavies pick him, because they think he's past
his prime, and the kid's a greenhorn. A couple of stiffs who'll
botch the job.
   ``Mancuso's the conscience of the piece. I guess in his own way
he's the real patriot of the piece. He's a man doing his job well,
serving his country well. He can make a difference as an
individual.''
   ``Favorite Son,'' which centers on a plot to win the
presidential nomination, will air just one week before the real
presidential election. The six-hour, three-part miniseries, based
on the best-selling political thriller by Steve Sohmer, runs
Sunday, Monday and Tuesday, Oct. 31-Nov. 2.
   Harry Hamlin stars as an ambitious young senator, Linda
Kozlowski as his even more ambitious image-maker, Lance Guest as
Loggia's FBI partner, James Whitmore as the president, Stepfanie
Kramer as the producer of a TV morning show, Ronny Cox as the head
of the CIA, Kenneth McMillan as the head of the FBI and Mitchell
Ryan as the vice president. Jeff Bleckner directed from Sohmer's
screenplay.
   ``Favorite Son'' is a powerful story of corruption in high
places, and as the suspense builds, viewers will be guessing until
the end which are the good guys and which are the villains.
   The complex story functions on several levels. It's a thriller
about a murderous plot to capture the presidential nomination. It
examines the power of television in making or breaking a candidate.
And it's a vehicle that could lead to a series for Robert Loggia,
one of the hottest and most talented character actors in movies and
television.
   ``It could be a pilot, but there are a few other steps,'' said
Loggia. ``We might do a movie-of-the-week on Mancuso. It's a really
a case of wait-and-see. See what kind of ratings numbers it gets.
Nick Mancuso is a good character, but I don't know if it can be
projected into a series.''
   Mancuso is similar to Sam Ransom, the rumpled detective that
earned an Oscar nomination for Loggia in the feature film ``The
Jagged Edge.'' Loggia calls Nick an Italian version of Sam.
   ``We didn't do this picture with FBI cooperation,'' said Loggia.
``But when we did `An Officer and a Gentleman,' the Navy was very
apprehensive and didn't cooperate. Then afterward, it came to be
used by the Navy as a recruiting film. I wouldn't be surprised if a
lot of young guys sign up for the FBI after seeing this miniseries.
We see Mancuso go full out. You see what makes him tick. In the
end, the resolution of this character is very positive.''
   Loggia's acting career goes back to the days of live television.
He starred in two series, ``The Nine Lives of Elfego Baca'' in 1958
on the Disney show and ``T.H.E. Cat'' in 1966-67. But in recent
years, his career has exploded.
   It started with his role as a boozing sailor in ``An Officer and
a Gentleman.'' He was a Cuban drug kingpin in ``Scarface,'' a Mafia
lawyer in ``Prizzi's Honor,'' a detective in ``The Believers,''
Anwar Sadat in ``A Woman Called Golda,'' a beachcomber in ``Hot
Pursuit,'' the murderous school principal in ``Echoes in the
Darkness'' and a warmhearted toy manufacturer in the current hit
``Big.''
   ``I got a nomination for `Jagged Edge,' which wasn't expected,''
he said. ``The producer and director didn't expect the role to have
that kind of impact. It's not a bad way to work, to give more than
they expect. The best thing is you're not trapped in a heavy or
ethnic role.
   ``I think you aim for this kind of thing. You can be a one-trick
pony or have a whole bag of tricks. I guess what we're at now is to
go from character supporting actor to character leading man. I'd
certainly rather carry the ball. I think `Favorite Son' will help
in this.''
   Loggia recently returned from Sri Lanka where he co-starred with
David Warner, Brian Kerwin and Alice Krige in a spy movie. A
permanent title hasn't been selected, but it's been known as
``Spies on Ice'' and ``Spooks.''
   Next, he goes to Chicago to play the father in a family drama
for CBS called ``The O'Connors.''
   ``It's a morality conflict,'' he said. ``We're an Irish Catholic
family. One son's a priest, one's in real estate at a heavy level.
Hal Linden plays a big real estate operator.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Oct. 28-30</NOTE>
