<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kroger Co.'s stock slumped after buyout
specialist Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. withdrew a $5.03 billion
takeover bid, saying it concluded the supermarket chain isn't for
sale.
   Kroger stock fell $2.62{ a share to $55 in trading Tuesday on
the New York Stock Exchange, far below Kohlberg's cash-and-stock
offer that was valued at $64 a share.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State regulators have approved
Merv Griffin's offer to buy Resorts International Inc., its casinos
and property, despite lingering questions about whether Griffin
will complete the deal.
   The Casino Control Commission's decision Tuesday came a day
after Griffin's company announced it had allowed a deadline for its
$36-per-share tender offer to Resorts' stockholders to expire. The
move gave rise to speculation that Griffin was trying to back out
of the deal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consolidated Gold Fields PLC and Newmont Mining
Corp. say they have filed a federal suit to block a $3.5 billion
hostile buyout bid by a South African conglomerate, on grounds the
offer violates federal laws.
   The suit filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court suit was the
latest action the companies have taken to thwart the overture by
South African-controlled Minorco SA, which has offered $3.5 billion
for the 70.6 percent of Consolidated Gold Fields it does not
already own. London-based Gold Fields owns a 49.3 percent stake in
Newmont.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developer Donald Trump reportedly has agreed to buy
Eastern Airlines' Northeast air shuttle, with one estimate putting
the price at more than $350 million.
   But neither Trump, a New York developer who owns casino property
in Atlantic City, N.J., nor officials at Eastern's Miami
headquarters would comment on separate reports Tuesday in the Miami
News and Dow Jones Professional Investor Report.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SPRINGDALE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tyson Foods Inc., the nation's largest
poultry processor, has made a $1 billion buyout offer for Holly
Farms Corp., hours after Holly Farms announced it had received
unsolicited buyout proposals and had activated a takeover defense.
   Tyson offered $45 cash and a quarter share of its Class A common
stock for each of Holly Farms 18.1 million outstanding shares, the
company said late Tuesday.
   Based on Tyson's closing stock price of $17.62{ a share, the
deal would have an indicated value of about $1 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bank holding company with branches in 72
countries has been indicted in what federal agents described as the
first drug-related money-laundering case involving a global banking
institution.
   In a two-year undercover sting, Customs agents were able to
infiltrate powerful Colombian money-laundering syndicates and help
launder an estimated $32 million in drug proceeds.
   Indictments unsealed Tuesday named nine banking officials along
with a Luxembourg-based bank holding company as well as two
subsidiaries.
</TEXT>
