</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. and would-be buyer Roy E.
Disney keep battling for support of the company's workers, with
Disney publishing a letter of reassurance about his plans for
employee stock ownership.
   Disney, who through his Shamrock Holdings Inc. is pressing an
unsolicited $2.6 billion offer for the instant film maker, also
suggested Tuesday that a buyout would increase job security by
making Polaroid ``a vigorous, productive and more progressive
company.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GROTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking submarine builders at Electric
Boat have voted to accept a new four-year contract, ending a
103-day walkout without achieving most of their demands.
   The vote Tuesday was 3,752 to 1,822, and casme after pressure
mounted on union negotiators to reach a quick settlement to end the
prolonged strike by the 10,200-member Metal Trades Council, which
represents 10 trade unions.
   The contract provides a three percent pay raise in the third
year of the four-year pact and bonuses in the other years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese automaking giant Toyota plans to
increase U.S. sales to about 1.5 million cars and trucks annually
by the mid-1990s _ a twofold sales boost fueled by a new truck
plant.
   At the introduction of the automaker's 1989 models, Bob McCurry,
executive vice president for sales and operations for the U.S. arm
of the company, said Tuesday it would take about about 2{ years
from site selection to production at a new truck plant.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan says
broad new guidelines for increasing banks' capital are the key to
maintaining stability in the financial world.
   ``Capital acts as a buffer against unexpected shocks to a firm,
and thereby helps to insulate both individual firms and the system
from risk,'' Greenspan said Tuesday at the annual convention of the
American Bankers Association.
   Greenspan also assured bankers that the repeal of the
Depression-era Glass-Steagall Act, which separates commercial and
investment banking, remains one of the Fed's highest priorities.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices edged lower Tuesday. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials fell 2.49 to close at 2,156.47.
   The dollar fell amid speculation the government would report a
big increase in the trade deficit on Thursday.
   Bond prices fell, with the yield on the bellwether 30-year
Treasury bond rising to 8.85 percent from 8.79 percent Friday.
   Precious metals futures prices fell sharply, cocoa futures
plummeted; grains and soybeans advanced; livestock and meat futures
were mixed; and energy futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
