<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 0042EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     10-12 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Slip in Volatile Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures trading has been volatile amid
rumors about OPEC production, and analysts predict the market will
remain nervous as long as the cartel's problems remain unresolved.
   The price for the November contract for West Texas Intermediate
oil changed course several times during Tuesday's session, trading
as high as $13.74 and as low as $13.30 a barrel. The contract for
the benchmark U.S. crude settled at $13.55, down 5 cents from
Monday's close.
   Like Monday's session _ when November West Texas Intermediate
climbed 66 cents _ Tuesday's trading was dominated by rumors and
speculation about production by the 13-members Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries, analysts said.
   Prices rose Monday as Saudi Arabia, the world's largest oil
exporter, reaffirmed it would stick to its production quota if
other members of OPEC did.
   On Tuesday, prices again moved higher, said Richard Redoglia, a
trader with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures. But the market turned
lower when Saudi King Fahd failed to discuss OPEC member's
inability to stay within their output quotas during an address,
Redoglia said.
   Rumors that the United Arab Emirates was willing to cut its
production then hit the market, and prices advanced again before
finally slipping lower at the end of the day, he said.
   Redoglia, who described trading as volatile, attributed
Tuesday's brief rallies to short covering, in which investors buy
contracts to offset those they sold earlier.
   He said the market's underlying fundamentals remained negative.
   ``The bearishness about OPEC overproduction is still there,'' he
said, predicting, ``the market is going to continue trading like
this'' until OPEC can resolve its differences.
   In other trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange, the
November contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline fell 0.62 cent to
settle at 40.79 cents a gallon, while home heating oil rose 0.12
cent to 39.08 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
