dealers said. Gold prices also drifted lower.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 129.65 yen, down 1.50 yen. It was
the first time the dollar closed below the 130-yen level since June
24. Later, in London, it was quoted at 129.45 yen.
   Traders said they expected the dollar to trade in a narrow range
until U.S. trade figures for August are released on Thursday.
   Dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday's quotes,
included: 1.8452 West German marks, down from 1.8512; 1.5625 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5690; 6.2915 French francs, down from 6.3070;
2.0801 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0850; 1,375.75 Italian lire,
down from 1,379.00; and 1.2140 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2075.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7255, more expensive for
buyers than late Tuesday's $1.7175.
   London's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price
for gold of $404.70 a troy ounce at midmorning today, down from an
opening bid of $406.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $404.75, down from $406 bid late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $3.06 to close at a bid $408.53.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid $6.25 a troy ounce, down
from Tuesday's $6.31.
