<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar dropped sharply against the Japanese yen
today for the second straight day, while share prices edged down on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar finished trading at 129.65 yen, down 1.50 yen from
Tuesday's close of 131.15 yen. This is the lowest since Jun. 24,
when it closed at 129.70 yen. Opening at 131.12 yen, the currency
moved between 129.60 yen and 131.38 yen.
   On Tuesday the dollar plummeted 2.35 yen, dropping from Friday's
close of 133.50 yen.
   ``Speculative investors' dollar-selling dominated the trading,
and hardly anybody was buying the dollar,'' a dealer with Daiwa
Bank said today.
   The release in Washington of unemployment in September, which
fell to 5.4 percent, ended concern over inflation and lowered U.S.
interest rates, he said.
   ``So it is no longer profitable for investors to buy the
currency with lower interest rates,'' the dealer said.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Exchange lost 60.23 points, or 0.22
percent, closing at 27,409.37. It lost 212.69 points during the
morning session but gained most of that back.
   The volume traded on the first section was estimated at a light
600 million shares.
   ``Participants' uncertainty due to the emperor's illness and a
new development in the Recruit-Cosmos scandal were the two major
reasons of the market's loss today,'' said Manji Ueda with Nomura
Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   ``There was no negative factor around the market otherwise. The
recent ideal economic factors have contributed to higher share
prices at overseas markets,'' he added.
   On Tuesday, Japan's Communist Party displayed documents it said
showed Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa was among the political
figures who purchased shares of the Recruit-Cosmos real estate firm
in 1986 before they were offered publicly, and later sold them for
a huge profit.
</TEXT>
