<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Laundering-Bank     10-12 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Laundering-Bank,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Look At The Bank Accused In Money-Laundering Scheme</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Money Laundering, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bank of Credit and Commerce
International, which as been accused of participating in an
international drug money-laundering scheme, has 14,000 employees in
400 offices in 72 countries.
   BCCI Holdings, which reports assets of $20.6 billion, and two
subsidiaries were among the 85 defendants named in federal
indictments unsealed Tuesday.
   While the bank, which was started in 1972, is based in
Luxembourg, it has central offices in London. It is owned by a
large group of shareholders, but its stock is not publicly traded,
said Tampa branch spokesman Marvin Hancock.
   Although a two-year U.S. Customs undercover sting operation was
based in Tampa, no local employees were named in the indictments.
Hancock said the branch continues normal operations.
   ``We're not a retail `street bank,''' said branch manager Raghu
Bahdur. ``We have no walk-in trade at all.''
   A typical transaction would be to help a company in Alabama
export frozen chicken to clients in the Middle East, Hancock said.
   The banks' clients are typically companies and individuals in
the export-import business.
   ``We're permitted to lend money to anybody,'' said Hancock.
``We're just not permitted to take deposits from anybody unless the
funds are used for international transactions.''
   Like most banks, the U.S. offices of BCCI are subject to audits
by state and federal regulators, its outside auditing firm of Price
Waterhouse and internal auditors, Bahdur said.
   Besides Tampa, BCCI has U.S. offices in Boca Raton, Miami, New
York, Los Angeles and San Francisco.
   Its other U.S. operations are non-banking offices in Washington,
D.C., Chicago, Houston and Beverly Hills.
</TEXT>
