<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Laundering-Wedding     10-12 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Laundering-Wedding,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fake Wedding Snags Suspects</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Money Laundering, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wedding invitations, printed in delicate
script, were mailed to a select group of international bankers
promising a grand affair.
   But the ``bride'' and ``groom'' were really undercover federal
agents and the nuptials were a charade which resulted in the arrest
of 11 party-goers linked to an alleged international drug and
money-laundering operation.
   Seven of the 11 were nabbed Saturday night as they rolled into
Tampa in chauffeured limousines for what was supposed to be a wild
bachelor party in a penthouse suite.
   ``They thought they were really going to a stag party. Not a one
of them had any idea of what was going on,'' Joseph P. Ladow Jr.,
assistant special agent in charge of the U.S. Customs office in
Tampa, said Tuesday after indictments were unsealed naming 85
defendants, including an international bank.
   Individuals in 10 U.S. cities and Paris and London were accused
of participating in a ring that laundered profits for the Colombian
cocaine trade through the Luxembourg-based Bank of Credit and
Commerce International, or BCCI Holdings.
   BCCI, two subsidiaries and nine bank officials were charged with
laundering $14 million in drug profits collected in seven U.S.
cities.
   The elaborate wedding ruse began months ago when federal
authorities tried to come up with a way to arrest as many suspects
at once to reduce the chances they would escape.
   ``A wedding was a perfect opportunity,'' Ladow said.
   An undercover Customs agent had infiltrated the alleged money
laundering operation posing as a financier and investor. As his
relationship with suspects developed, he introduced a woman he said
was his fiancee and business partner.
   The couple became a part of the suspects' social and business
scene, traveling to parties, dinner engagements and sporting
events, including a championship boxing match in Miami, authorities
said.
   Six months ago they announced their engagement.
   Invitations went out for the marriage of Kathleen Corrine
Erickson and Robert L. Musella, the agents' fictitious names.
   The affair was set for Sunday at the exclusive Innisbrook Resort
and Golf Club near Tarpon Springs, 35 miles northewest of Tampa.
Federal agents did not tip the resort to their plan.
   As guests and their families arrived they were greeted by
undercover agents posing as friends of the happy couple and were
wined and dined at cocktail parties.
   Eight to 10 limousines ferried party-goers to Tampa for the
bachelor bash.
   ``We had undercover agents in the cars,'' Ladow said. ``All the
way over, there were comments about, `Hey, we're going to party
tonight.' ''
   When the bankers stepped off an elevator into the arm of waiting
agents they didn't understand what was happening, officials said.
   One suspect apparently had been to a recent striptease party
where a dancer placed handcuffs on him before her bump-and-grind
routine. So when the handcuffs were slapped on him Saturday night,
he didn't get upset, according to agents.
   ``He was all smiles. He said, `All right, let's party!' '' said
Ladow. ``He thought it was a prelude to the same thing.''
   But as things began to sink in, another suspect moaned: ``I
thought they could only do this in the movies.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
