<1ST_LINE>r f BC-OPEC     10-12 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-OPEC,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>OPEC Committee Meetings Scheduled In Madrid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subroto, one name, is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two OPEC committees will meet in Madrid
on Oct.20, apparently to discuss tumbling oil prices at a time of
overproduction and disarray in the world oil market, OPEC Secretary
General Subroto announced Wednesday.
   The announcement, carried by OPENA, the news agency of the
13-member Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries, did
not provide an agenda or other details.
   It said the two committees will hold their first joint meeting
in the Spanish capital.
   They are the Committee on Price Evolution, comprising the oil
ministers of Algeria, Indonesia, Nigeria, Saudi Arabia and
Venezuela, and the Long-Term Strategy Committee consisting of the
oil ministers of Algeria, Iran, Iraq, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia and
Venezuela.
   World oil prices have plunged recently, running more than $5 a
barrel below the cartel's benchmark of $18 for a 42-gallon barrel.
   Several OPEC member countries have considerably exceeded their
production quotas. Their conduct and longterm energy saving
measures introduced in many industrialized countries have triggered
a decline in prices.
   Subroto said recently prices could plummet to $5 a barrel if
Saudi Arabia _ the world's largest oil exporter _ exploited its
production capacity to force other OPEC members to obsderve their
quotas.
   A full ministerial conference of the organization is scheduled
to take place in Vienna on Nov. 21.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
