<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Eastern 5thLd-Writethru   10-12 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern, 5th Ld-Writethru,0760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Trump Buys Eastern Shuttle for $365 Million, Says He'll Name It
After Himself</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: ADDS new 8th graf with speculation that Trump could sell new
real estate site; picks up 8th graf pvs bg'ng, The sale ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Trump has bought the profitable Eastern
Airlines shuttle from Texas Air Corp. for $365 million cash and
will rename it after himself, it was announced today, but Eastern's
militant union leaders called the sale the death of the airline and
vowed a fight.
   ``I want to run it as a diamond, an absolute diamond,'' the
flamboyant real estate-gambling mogul proclaimed to reporters at a
joint news conference with Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo at the
Plaza Hotel in New York, another recent Trump acquisition.
   ``You're going to be flying with something that's quality and
good,'' Trump said of the moneymaking commuter service between the
heavily traveled cities of Boston, New York and Washington.
   He said the shuttle will now be called ``The Trump Shuttle'' and
its blue-silver Boeing 727s will be redecorated and emblazoned with
red, black and gold stripes. The deal is expected to be completed
by mid-December.
   Lorenzo told reporters the sale was ``not our preferrred
course.'' But he said Eastern's militant unions had created a
situation that deprived management of the right to negotiate.
   The Texas Air chief also confirmed speculation he had talked
with takeover strategist Carl Icahn, head of Trans World Airlines
Inc., about selling him other operations of Eastern, which
Lorenzo's company bought two years ago, creating the nation's
biggest airline company. Texas Air also owns Continental Airlines,
a non-union carrier based in Houston.
   Trump and Lorenzo said the shuttle will maintain fares
competitive with the Northeast shuttle service operated by Pan Am
Corp. and won't lay off any employees. The $365 million cash
acquisition, substantially above previous estimates of the
shuttle's sale price, includes landing rights at airports in the
three shuttle cities plus 17 planes.
   Trump noted recent reports that he intends to sell the land
earmarked for a huge new commercial development in Manhattan to
help finance the Shuttle deal. No interested party could afford to
pay him what the 100-acre site is worth, Trump joked to reporters.
   The sale marks another tumultuous chapter in the saga of
Eastern, the Miami-based carrier that has been scarred by
management-labor feuding and $1 billion in losses over the past
decade.
   The shuttle is considered Eastern's crown jewel. Eastern
officials testified recently that the shuttle is the airline's only
remaining profitable operation.
   When word of the deal leaked earlier today, Eastern's machinists
vowed to seek a federal court order against it.
   In Washington, attorney Joseph Guerrieri, representing the
Machinists union, said he was readying a request to U.S. District
Court in Washington to grant an injunction against the sale and
would file it later this week.
   ``The sale of the shuttle is the death knell of Eastern Airlines
as we know it. We just can't allow the employees to be walked over
in this manner. We intend to keep Eastern Airlines a viable entity
by seeking to enjoin this sale,'' Guerrieri said by telephone.
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak confirmed pilots and flight
attendants unions were informed of the sale today but did not
disclose details.
   Nancy Currier, vice president of the Transport Workers Union
local representing Eastern flight attendants, said Eastern
management had told the union a copy of the agreement would be sent
to the unions later.
   Ron Cole, spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association local
representing Eastern pilots, said earlier that his union opposes
the sale and ``we will take whatever legal means is possible.''
   The shuttle was made into a separate division last year,
clearing the way for a possible sale.
   In February 1988, Eastern announced plans to sell the new
division for $225 million cash and marketable securities to
Air-Shuttle L.P., a new subsidiary of Texas Air.
   U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt blocked the plan with a
contempt of court finding against Eastern in March. A federal
appeals court reversed the contempt order in June but left the door
open for the unions to continue legal action. In July, Eastern
announced the cancellation of the plan.
   Reports surfaced recently that the shuttle was again for sale _
this time to an outside buyer.
   Trump's desire for the shuttle became known last week.
</TEXT>
