<HEAD>London Shares Off 24 Points</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing prices</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on the London stock exchange finished
a jittery session sharply lower Wednesday, pulled down by sinking
prices on Wall Street.
   The markets were battered by rumors that U.S. trade figures for
August, due j5w Thursday, could show a significant widening in the
country's trade gap.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 24
points, or 1.3 percent, to 1,814.3, near its worst level for the
session of 1,811.8. The index opened at its highest point, down 7.1
points.
   Volume was modest, as 475.9 million shares changed hands,
compared with the 462.9 million shares traded Tuesday.
   Dealers said the market came unglued by Wall Street's overall
decline, with the Dow Jones industrial average dropping as much as
25 points within the first 15 minutes of trading.
   By the close of trading in London, the average was 30.23 points
lower at 2,126.24.
   Attention focused squarely on the U.S. trade figures, which are
expected to show a widening of the trade deficit in August to $11.3
billion from July's $9.5 billion, according to several economists.
   But market watchers suggested that the shortfall could surge to
as much as $15 billion.
