<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Walgreen-Dart     10-12 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Walgreen-Dart,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Walgreen Announces Haft Family Purchase Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walgreen Co. said today the Haft family, which
already has a bid outstanding for supermarket owner Kroger Co., is
seeking federal permission to acquire at least $15 million of the
drug retailer's stock.
   Walgreen, the nation's largest drugstore chain, also reported a
22 percent increase in its fourth-quarter net income and a 25
percent profit gain for the 1988 fiscal year.
   The Hafts applied for federal clearance to purchase the Walgreen
stock, the retailer said in a statement. Walgreen, based in
Deerfield, Ill., north of Chicago, said it did not know how much,
if any, Walgreen stock the Hafts already own.
   ``We will monitor the Haft situation carefully and take all
actions necessary to protect the company and its shareholders,''
said Chairman Charles R. Walgreen III.
   Neither the Hafts nor their company, Dart Group Corp., would
comment today on any plans regarding Walgreen.
   Walgreen stock rose $1.37{ a share to $34 in New York Stock
Exchange trading after today's announcement.
   The Hafts, based in Landover, Md., sold Dart's discount
drugstore chain in 1984. Since then, the family has said they want
to acquire and operate another retailing company, but they have a
string of unsuccessful takeover bids behind them that have cast
doubt on their sincerity.
   Last month, Dart chairman Herbert Haft and his son, company
president Robert Haft, offered to buy Kroger for $55 a share, or a
total of about $4.32 billion. The status of the bid was in doubt
after the New York investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts Inc.
withdrew a $5.03 billion offer for Kroger.
   The Hafts offered last week to help Kroger fight the Kohlberg
bid by proposing to provide additional equity for Kroger's
previously-announced restructuring.
   Robert Haft reiterated Tuesday the family ``remains interested
in working with Kroger to strengthen the company and enhance their
restructuring by providing additional equity.''
   He declined to comment on whether the Haft offer for Kroger was
withdrawn.
   The Hafts have bid unsuccessfully in the past for retailers
including Stop & Shop Cos., Safeway Stores Inc. and Supermarkets
General Corp. However, they have made millions of dollars in
profits from the sale of their stock in their targets, and have
been labeled corporate raiders in the process.
   In its earnings report today, Walgreen said it had net income of
$31.9 million, or 52 cents a share for the three months ending Aug.
31, compared with $26.2 million, or 42 cents a share, for the
fourth quarter a year ago.
   Sales during the period increased to $1.2 billion from $1.1
billion.
   For the fiscal year ending Aug. 31, Walgreen reported net income
of $129.1 million, or $2.10 a share, compared with $103.5 million,
or $1.68 a share, in fiscal 1987.
   Sales in fiscal 1988 totaled $4.9 billion, up from $4.3 billion
in fiscal 1987.
   Walgreen has 1,400 Walgreen's drugstores in 29 states.
</TEXT>
