<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1353EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Ford     10-12 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Ford,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Probing Ford, Others In Spare Parts Antitrust Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community
Commission said Wednesday it has resumed an inquiry into alleged
anticompetitive practices in the spare parts market by Ford Motor
Co.'s British subsidiary and other car makers based on a court
ruling last week.
   The European Court of Justice said two car makers, Sweden's AB
Volvo of Sweden and Renault of France, could refuse licenses to
spare parts makers if they did not abuse this power of refusal.
   On Wednesday, the EEC Commission said its probe must show if
Ford and others, which it did not name, engaged in ``abusive
practices'' violating EEC antitrust rules.
   The court said illegal practices included arbitrary refusal to
supply spare parts, charging unfair prices or not making parts for
models that were still on the road in large numbers.
   The EEC's inquiry was begun several years ago following
complaints by independent spare parts makers that car makers used
their copyright and design rights to prevent them from making and
selling components.
   The Commission threatened to sue Ford U.K. Ltd. in 1985 after a
complaint by British spare parts makers but suspended its action
when Ford agreed to change some of its practices.
   Investigation of the substance of the complaint against Ford is
continuing, the Commission said.
</TEXT>
