<1ST_LINE>r f AM-APAppointments     10-12 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Appointments,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Temple, Yake Named to New Positions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wick Temple, director of human resources for The
Associated Press since 1985, has been appointed director of
newspaper membership, and D. Byron Yake has been named to replace
him, AP President Louis D. Boccardi announced Wednesday.
   Temple, 50, succeeds James W. Mangan, who is retiring effective
Jan. 1 after a 36-year career with the news cooperative. Yake, 48,
has been assistant to the president.
   Before taking over AP personnel and labor policies, Temple had
been managing editor for four years and sports editor for seven. He
joined the AP in Little Rock, Ark., in 1959, later serving as
correspondent in St. Louis and as chief of the Helena, Mont., and
Seattle bureaus, before moving to AP headquarters in New York in
1973. He is a vice president of the cooperative.
   Mangan, 60, has directed AP sales to the U.S. newspaper industry
since 1978, a decade of expansion in the cooperative's membership.
It now stands at a record high of 1,467 newspapers.
   He joined the AP in San Francisco in 1952, transferring to New
York in 1954 to supervise the AP World Service news report to
Europe, Africa and Asia. In 1963, he moved to Dallas as assistant
chief of bureau. One of his assignments there: coverage of the last
speech John F. Kennedy made, in Fort Worth, before the Dallas
motorcade in which he was assassinated.
   He became chief of bureau in New Orleans in 1965, returned to
Dallas as bureau chief in 1969, and later served a year as chief of
the bureau in Frankfurt, West Germany. Mangan, an AP vice
president, requested early retirement.
   Yake, succeeding Temple as human resources director, joined the
AP in Pittsburgh in 1968 after working for five years as the editor
of three weekly newspapers in western Pennsylvania.
   Yake was named correspondent in charge of the Pittsburgh office
in 1976 and became bureau chief in Newark, N.J., in 1978. He
transferred to New York as sports editor in 1980, and Boccardi
appointed him assistant to the president in 1985.
</TEXT>
