<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-FirstBoston     10-12 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-First Boston,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Boston Reports Third Quarter Net</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First Boston Inc. on Wednesday reported
marginally higher profits for the third quarter as fixed-income
operations kept pace despite difficult market conditions.
   For the quarter ended Sept. 30, the investment firm reported net
income of $41.7 million, or $1.12 a share, up 2 percent from $40.8
million, or $1.15 a share a year ago.
   Revenue during the period totaled $374.9 million, up 1 percent
from $369.6 million a year ago.
   First Boston announced on Sunday that it has agreed to merge
with Credit Suisse First Boston, its European affiliate. The
combined firm will be taken private in a deal valued at about $1.1
billion.
   Peter T. Buchanan, First Boston's president and chief executive
officer, noted that the government securities and high-yield bond
departments led the fixed-income group.
   Revenue from principal transactions, which include fixed-income
operations, more than doubled to $142.8 million, from $66.2 million
in the year-ago period.
   Buchanan also noted that the firm's financial advisory and
merger and acquisition activity ``maintained its momentum'' despite
what he termed ``difficult market conditions.''
   Still, investment banking revenues slipped to $175.1 million
from $240.8 million in the third quarter of 1987. Commission
revenue also declined during the period, to $40 million, from $46
million a year ago.
   For the year to date, First Boston reported net income of $127.3
million, or $3.42 a share, up 2 percent from $103.8 million, or
$2.95 a share in the year-ago period. Revenue during the first nine
months totaled $1.08 billion, up 2 percent from $1.06 billion a
year ago.
</TEXT>
