<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1445EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Smoker'sSuit     10-12 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smoker's Suit,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorneys for Nathan Horton Family Don't Expect Cigarette Trial
Until Spring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $17 million wrongful death suit filed by
a cancer victim's family against the maker of Pall Mall cigarettes
probably won't be scheduled for retrial until next spring at the
earliest, the plaintiffs' attorney predicts.
   Circuit Judge Gray Evans of Greenwood probably will st the
second trial date soon _ now that the Mississippi Supreme Court has
refused to rule on issues in the case before it is heard by a
second jury, attorney Don Barrett said in a telephone interview
Wednesday from his Lexington office.
   Barrett represents the family of now-deceased Nathan Henry
Horton of Durant in a case against American Tobacco Co., the maker
of Pall Malls, and New Deal Tobacco and Candy Co. of Greenwood, a
local cigarette distributor. The first Circuit Court trial in
Lexington, which attracted dozens of Wall Street analysts and
national news media, ended Jan. 29 in a hung jury.
   ``We hope it's real soon,'' Barrett said of the second trial
date. ``We've had a problem of course with the death of one of our
circuit judges, Arthur Clarke, so Judge Evans is really snowed
under and the Horton family understands that. But we believe he'll
give us a setting as soon as his schedule will permit.''
   National anti-smoking advocates had hailed the first Horton
trial as a chance to ruin cigarette manufacturers' long string of
victories in cases seeking damages for cancer victims who smoke.
Horton died of cancer on Jan. 26, 1987, and his family contends the
two packs of Pall Mall cigarettes he smoked each day for 35 years
caused his death.
   Since the hung jury in Lexington, a federal court jury in New
Jersey held a cigarette company partially responsible for the 1984
death of Rose Cipollone and awarded $400,000 in damages to her
widower, Antonio Cipollone.
   Barrett said the New Jersey case ``may be psychologically
important'' in the Horton retrial. However, he added, ``We're going
to win our case on the evidence we present.''
   Attorneys for the tobacco company have repeatedly said they
won't comment on any aspect of the pending case.
   The Mississippi Supreme Court, without a written opinion,
refused on Sept. 21 to hear an appeal filed by Horton's family. The
plaintiffs had wanted the high court to rule on 15 legal issues in
the case before it went to a second trial.
   One of the main issues the high court was asked to determine is
whether the Horton family can introduce evidence of advertising
they contend might have encouraged Horton's smoking habit.
   Defense attorneys wanted the state Supreme Court to decide
whether federal tobacco labeling laws warning of health risks would
make the advertising arguments moot.
   Horton's family counters that he began smoking the cigarettes in
1955, 10 years before the U.S. Surgeon General required a warning
label on cigarette packages. However, they say the cigarette maker
knew then that its product was harmful and addictive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
