<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ErieFoundry     10-12 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Erie Foundry,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Erie Foundry Sold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ERIE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   EMI Co., a ductile iron foundry with projected
1988 sales of $33 million, was sold Wednesday to its management,
Charterhouse Group International and Hitachi Metals International.
   EMI, which has 280 employees, is a supplier of castings,
manifolds and transmission cases for heavy-duty truck and
off-highway equipment.
   The purchase price was not disclosed.
   Kurt Van Vlandren, spokesman for the new owners, said there will
be no layoffs at the Erie plant and there are ``preliminary plans
being looked at to expand the facility.''
   President George Metcalf and five other officers of EMI Co. are
partners with Charterhouse Group International and Hitachi Metals
International in the venture, Van Vlandren said.
   Charterhouse Group International, headquartered in New York, is
owned by five European financial companies, Chairman Merril M.
Halpern and President Jerome L. Katz. A subsidiary last year
acquired Carpenter Enterprises, a supplier of machined components
to the same truck and off-highway equipment markets.
   Hitachi Metals International is a subsidiary of Hitachi Metals
Limited of Tokyo, Japan, and owns the largest independent ductile
iron foundry in Japan.
</TEXT>
