<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1539EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Budget     10-12 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Budget,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC To Revise 1989 Budget Forecast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European Economic Community budget
Commissioner Henning Christophersen said Wednesday the 1989 draft
budget would be some 2 billion European currency units, or $2.26
billion, less than initial projections.
   He said the revised budget would be presented to the European
Parliament, which must approve it, and to the decision-making EEC
Council in early November.
   Christophersen said about 1 billion Ecus could be cut from the
budget ``mainly due to higher world market prices for cereals and
oilseeds.''
   He added that ``the 1988 budget is likely to produce a surplus
of another (one) billion Ecus due to a growth-induced increase in
customs duties and the effect of applying the new budget discipline
rules.''
   The new budget discipline rules are the guidelines on
agricultural expenditure, fixed by the 12 EEC heads of state at the
Brussels summit in February.
   Next year, farm expenditure is set at $27.7 billion Ecus.
</TEXT>
