<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CounterfeitPerfume     10-12 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Counterfeit Perfume,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Put The Lid On Phony Perfume Ring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FONTANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have sniffed out what they
say is a major perfume counterfeiting ring that made millions by
slapping look-a-like labels on phony bottles of Giorgio, Chanel,
Jean Patou and Christian Dior perfumes.
   Investigators served search warrants in recent weeks at a
Fontana printing plant and a bottling firm in Indio, both east of
Los Angeles, and on a home in Milpitas, in the San Francisco area.
An undisclosed number of empty perfume bottles, boxes and other
evidence were seized, officials said Tuesday.
   ``No arrests have been made, so I wouldn't say it's been brought
to justice yet. But obviously, it's a counterfeiting ring that has
been interrupted,'' said Lt. Mike Stodelle of the San Bernardino
County Sheriff's Department.
   ``This is the largest (perfume) counterfeit operation in the
country, possibly the world,'' said Jacqueline Cohen, spokeswoman
for Giorgio Beverly Hills, who estimated that $20 million in fake
perfume was sold.
   Ms. Cohen said the company has been investigating the ring for
two years after one of the phony perfumes came to the attention of
its security director.
   The perfumes were sold around the country at retail outlets not
authorized by the companies and at flea markets, said Ms. Cohen.
   Additional details about the search warrants weren't released
and Stodelle refused to identify the people or companies named,
saying the investigation was continuing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
