<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close 1stLd-Writethru 10-12 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close, 1st Ld-Writethru,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mixed Ahead Of USDA Production Report</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf to UPDATE with USDA corn and
soybean production estimates; picks up 5th graf: Those numbers ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain futures closed mostly higher while soybean
futures finished mostly lower Wednesday on the Chicago Board of
Trade in light, cautious trading ahead of the government's revised
crop production report.
   ``It was very quiet all the way around,'' said Walter Spilka, a
grain analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co. in New York.
   Soybean prices were pressured by expectations that the
Agriculture Department would project a larger soybean crop than the
1.47 billion bushels it predicted in last month's report, due to
better-than-expected yields in the advancing harvest.
   But little change was expected in the USDA's September corn
production estimate of 4.46 billion bushels.
   The report, issued shortly after the close, pegged soybean
production at 1.5 billion bushels and corn production at 4.55
billion bushels.
   Those numbers compare with 1987 production of 1.9 billion
bushels of soybeans and 7.1 billion bushels of corn.
   Both corn and wheat futures prices were boosted by indications
of increased export business, Spilka said. Wheat for December,
March and May deliveries hit new life-of-contract highs.
   At the close, wheat was \ cent lower to 1{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.34{ a bushel; corn was {
cent lower to 1{ cents higher with December at $2.96 a bushel; oats
were unchanged to 2 cents higher with December at $2.56} a bushel;
soybeans were 4{ cents lower to 1{ cents higher with November at
$7.89 a bushel.
