<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Appliances,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Whirlpool Third Quarter Earnings Down 29.3 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BENTON HARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Appliance maker Whirlpool Corp.
reported a 29.4 percent drop in third quarter earnings Wednesday,
primarily because of the higher costs of materials.
   The company said it earned $31.5 million, or 45 cents per share,
on sales of $1.2 billion in the July-September period this year,
compared with $44.6 million, or 63 cents per share, on $1.1 billion
in sales during the same three months last year.
   The third-quarter sales, up 5.4 percent from the third quarter
of 1987, set a company record, and were attributed to increases in
shipments of Whirlpool's KitchenAid and Kenmore products.
   During the third quarter of 1988, Whirlpool announced some price
increases and acquired Emerson Electric Co.'s dishwasher and trash
compactor manufacturing business.
   For the first nine months of the year, Whirlpool earned $106.1
million, or $1.53 per share, on sales of $3.4 billion. During the
July-September period last year, the company earned $151.5 million,
or $2.09 a share, on sales of $3.2 billion.
   Whirlpool said the drop in third quarter earnings and the 30
percent decline so far this year was due largely to higher material
prices not covered by price increases.
   A weak kitchen-cabinet business and a $10.8 million addition to
the 1987 figures because of an accounting change also played roles
in the earnings weakness this year, the company said.
</TEXT>
