<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1541EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Mexico-Economy Bjt   10-12 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Economy, Bjt,0663</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Oil Glut Prompts Budget Cuts in Mexico</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The plunge in prices for oil, Mexico's
leading export, has prompted the government to announce painful
budget cuts, consider an International Monetary Fund contingency
loan and renew calls for a better deal on the foreign debt.
   It also highlights a stubborn battle against inflation and an
ambitious trade liberalization program meant to diversify Mexico's
export earnings and wean the nation from dependence on
oil-generated revenues.
   Pemex, the government oil monopoly, said on Oct. 7 that average
spot market prices for Mexican crude had sunk to about $9 a barrel
and that revenues for this year would fall below 1987's $8.6
billion.
   Last year, oil accounted for 41 percent of total Mexican export
revenues and helped the country post an overall $8.4 billion trade
surplus.
   Reacting to the drop in oil-based earnings _ estimated by one
Energy Department official at $2 billion below official projections
so far this year _ President Miguel de la Madrid's administration
announced more than $200 million in budget cuts last Friday.
   The administration took pains to assure Mexicans, whose
paychecks are worth half what they were in 1982, that the cuts
would spare social programs.
   ``We can manage the problems (caused by falling oil prices) with
some sacrifices,'' Agustin F. Legorreta, president of the private
Business Coordinating Council, said Tuesday.
   The falling price of oil has spurred new calls for renegotiation
of Mexico's $104 billion foreign debt. Legorreta said interest
payments on the debt are sucking funds away from economic
development.
   The government has been using its foreign reserves to support a
7-month-old peso currency exchange rate freeze as part of an
anti-inflation wage and price stabilization program. If the price
of oil keeps dropping, however, the government may actually be
forced to add to the debt burden.
   Most analysts believe the government when it says inflation is
its No. 1 economic priority and say President-elect Carlos Salinas
de Gortari will try to maintain the fight. Salinas takes office
Dec. 1.
   ``The danger of hyperinflation is so big that the effort should
continue,'' said Jacobo Zaidenweber, president of the Mexico-United
States Chamber of Commerce, in a recent interview. ``It could take
between one and three years in one form or another.''
   Under terms of a 1987 foreign debt rescheduling agreement with
the IMF, Mexico has the option to draw up to $1.2 billion in
contingency loans if the price of crude oil drops below the $9
barrier.
   Hard currecny reserves, which reached a high of $16 billion in
April, dropped to an estimated $12 billion in July as the
government propped up the peso against the dollar.
   The government has resisted fresh calls to devalue and give
Mexican entrepreneurs a new export advantage that could help offset
the shrinking trade surplus. A devaluation would generate new
inflationary pressures; the anti-inflation plan has, officially,
reduced annualized inflation from a record 159.2 percent in 1987 to
about 45 percent this year.
   Although resisting the calls to devalue, the administration has
stressed the importance of non-oil exports to make up for the
shortfall in oil revenues.
   Through June, Mexico's first-half merchandise trade surplus
totalled $2.4 billion, well below 1987's first-half surplus of
$4.76 billion, according to the Center for Private Sector Economic
Studies. But non-petroleum exports, at $7.1 billion, were up 20
percent over the same period in 1987.
   However, the surplus was hurt when merchandise imports surged by
53 percent between January and June to $8.3 billion. That was
encouraged by trade liberalization aimed at forcing domestic
industry to become competitive and lower prices.
   On Monday, Tomas Rodriguez Weber, director general of Capital
Goods and Petrochemical Industries affairs at the Commerce
Department, reiterated the government's position that
manufacturers' exports are the best way to compensate for the weak
oil sector.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881012-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 2016EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-MarketGridlock Adv16   10-12 1161</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Market Gridlock, Adv 16,1199</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Oct. 16 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Credit comes for the Latin word for ``believe.''
One year ago, as the stock market went down in flames, America's
lenders almost stopped believing.
   The credit crisis that nearly imposed gridlock on the financial
system is one of the least understood yet most important aspects of
last October's historic plunge.
   In human terms, the crisis sprang from a loss of faith that
participants in the market would honor their commitments. Markets
are founded on that belief and cannot function without it.
   The stock market depends on the banking system because every
trade involves money passing from a seller's bank to a buyer's.
Banks also provide lines of credit for investors.
   Instead of making fresh loans during the crash, some big New
York banks actually demanded more collateral on existing loans from
desperate customers that had to meet margin calls.
   Only decisive action by the Federal Reserve prevented the banks'
response from triggering a wave of defaults that could have ushered
in a full-fledged panic.
   A year later, in spite of numerous studies, little has been done
to rebuild the financial system so the next stock market collapse
does not bring the circulation of money to a deadly standstill.
   ``All financial panics result from the withdrawal of credit by
the banks. It's the grease in the engine, and the engine seizes up
without it,'' said Martin Mayer, a veteran banking writer.
   The survival of the markets through Black Monday proved the
financial system can withstand a major shock, but a bit of luck was
involved.
   If the crash had occurred one week earlier, banks and the money
transfer wires would have been closed for Columbus Day. Traders
would have piled up huge debts with no way to pay them.
   ``It would have been horrendous. The system would not have
worked. It would have stopped,'' said Paul Allen, a partner in the
consulting firm of McKinsey & Co.
   To a degree, the banks' caution on lending last year is
understandable: Banks have a duty to both federal regulators and
their own shareholders not to throw money away on loans that will
not be repaid.
   Complicating credit decisions last year were deficiencies in the
back offices _ the operations that work out who owes what to whom
and then carry out deliveries of securities and payments for them.
   These back offices, known as clearing and settlement systems,
have grown haphazardly into a disjointed network that is unsuited
for a world of global trading and tightly interconnected markets.
   A clearing and settlement network consists of organizations that
help stock exchanges sort out the terms of a trade and then make
the swap by taking in the securities from the seller and the
payment from the buyer. If one side or the other defaults, the
system is supposed to make good on the deal.
   In spite of safeguards, some regulators feared last October that
a single default in the back offices could have set off a chain
reaction of defaults.
   The worriers included New York Fed President E. Gerald Corrigan,
who many regard as a hero of the crash because he oversaw the Fed's
emergency lending and arm-twisted bankers into supplying credit to
financial institutions.
   The possibility of a major default in one of the clearing and
settlement systems was ``the greatest threat to the stability of
the financial system as a whole in that period,'' Corrigan said
last May.
   Most proposed reforms have dealt with highly visible matters _
an express lane for individual investors, coordinated circuit
breakers for stocks and futures.
   Far less attention has been paid to clearing and settlement, the
invisible side of the financial system.
   ``It's not a subject that people have considered sexy. It is
sexy. You're talking about well over a trillion dollars a day,''
said Mayer, the banking writer and author of a new book,
``Markets.''
   Each of the major exchanges has its own system for clearing and
settling, and each system has different rules. The fragmentation
was acceptable when Chicago stuck to beans and bellies, but it does
not work in the era of index arbitrage, when traders simultaneously
do business in multiple markets.
   Delays in settlement keep traders guessing about whether their
sales and purchases will actually go through. It takes five days to
be paid for stocks sold on the New York Stock Exchange. Some
foreign exchanges take months.
   Changes are coming, but slowly. The NYSE says it will not reduce
the lag in payment and delivery from five days until sometime in
the next decade.
   The irony is that settlement problems could push a customer into
default even if it had plenty of money coming to it, a point made
by the presidential task force in its post mortem on the crash.
   The fragility of the settlement system is worsened by a practice
known as ``daylight overdrafting,'' in which banks cash checks for
big customers or other banks before the money to cover the checks
has arrived.
   These overdrafts are huge, a fact that becomes apparent only
when something goes wrong. In November 1986, the Bank of New York
had to take out an emergency overnight loan of $26 billion from the
Federal Reserve because of a computer bug.
   ``The real issue is, what you've got is risk piled on top of
risk,'' said McKinsey's Allen.
   Global trading is exacerbating the problem. Big U.S. banks
routinely shut down for the night with giant holes in their books
because they have not received money from abroad to cover
overdrafts.
   Theoretically, a major default overseas could knock out a U.S.
bank while all its officers were asleep.
   Although the 1987 stock market crash began in the United States,
the next one could well start in Japan or Europe. Or a big
institution could fail for reasons unrelated to a stock crash _ as
Continental Illinois Bank nearly did in 1984.
   Americans say the European clearing and settlement systems are
one place trouble could start. The two biggest European systems
handle a combined $90 billion a week but, unlike their U.S.
counterparts, don't guarantee that the parties to a trade will
fulfill their obligations.
   ``There are few institutions that seem to monitor and are fully
aware of that type of risk,'' said Abraham Gulkowitz, senior vice
president for credit policy at Bankers Trust Co.
   The Federal Reserve is cutting back on the size of overdrafts
banks are allowed to make. But since global markets are here to
stay, the long-term solution is for banks to stay open around the
clock.
   In the end, there is a danger that the market's survival through
Black Monday will create a false sense of security, leading
bankers, brokers and traders to believe that reforms are not needed
because the Federal Reserve will always be there to bail the system
out.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Oct. 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881012-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 2021EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-MarketGridlock-Reforms Adv16   10-12 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Market Gridlock-Reforms, Adv 16,0381</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 16</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Oct. 16 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Reforms In Back Offices Could Stave Off Next Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Market Gridlock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some changes in the clearing and
settlement system that would reduce the likelihood that another
stock market crash will send the financial system into gridlock:
   SPEED UP SETTLEMENTS. Delayed settlements tie up money and keep
traders exposed to risks. The New York Stock Exchange has said it
recognizes the problem and will move by 1990 to two-day clearing _
that is, straightening out who owes what to whom. However,
settlement will continue to take places five days after trading
until sometime later in the 1990s.
   KEEP BANKS OPEN. Banks need to move to around-the-clock
operations so they can meet the needs of financial institutions
that do business at all hours. This will reduce risks and keep
banking business from moving to foreign banks.
   REDUCE OVERDRAFTS. Customers should have to pay for the
privilege of getting cash from a bank before the money to cover the
withdrawal has been deposited. This should discourage overdrafts
and reduce the vulnerability of banks to defaults.
   UPDATE LAWS. Revise the federal bankruptcy code and other laws
so they treat stocks, futures and options more consistently. For
example, banks should have clear rights to obtain liens on put
options that are pledged as collateral.
   PERMIT CROSS-MARGINING. With changes in laws, exchanges would be
freer to allow traders to pledge assets in one market as collateral
against liabilities in another _ for example, put options against
stocks. This would help traders with hedged positions and ease the
selling pressure in a falling market. The Chicago Mercantile
Exchange and Options Clearing Corp. plan to allow cross-margining
next year.
   IMPROVE EQUIPMENT. Make sure computers and communication systems
are secure and have back-ups. Many observers feel the sense of
panic on Oct. 20 was heightened when the Fedwire, which handles
money transfers between banks, briefly failed.
   LOOK OVERSEAS. U.S. authorities should take the lead in
improving the security and efficiency of foreign clearing and
settlement systems. In today's interlocked markets, a major default
in a system overseas would quickly affect the United States.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Oct. 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
