<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Britain-MoneyLaundering     10-12 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Money Laundering,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senior Banker Charged In Money Laundering Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official of the Bank of Credit and Commerce
International accused of participating in a $32 million
international drug money-laundering ring surrendered to British
customs agents Wednesday, officials said.
   Nazir Chinoy, 55, a senior executive in the Paris office of the
international banking group, was turned over to police and appeared
later in Bow Street Magistrate's Court where he was ordered held in
custody pending a court appearance Friday. His attorney, Roger
Bevan, did not seek bail.
   Chinoy, a native of Bombay, India, who keeps an apartment in an
exclusive section of west London's Bayswater area, is wanted under
a United States arrest warrant alleging he conspired between May
1986 and October 1988 to possess cocaine in Florida and elsewhere.
   A Customs and Excise Department spokesman said Chinoy was in
London for a business meeting Tuesday when U.S. officials unsealed
indictments against 85 defendants in what federal agents called the
first drug-related money-laundering case involving a global
financial institution.
   The indictments named nine banking officials and the
Luxembourg-based bank holding company, BCCI Holdings, which has
branches in 72 countries. Also named were two subsidiaries, Bank of
Credit and Commerce International S.A. and Bank of Credit and
Commerce International (Overseas) Limited.
   U.S. Customs officials said the indictments stem from a two-year
undercover investigation into a money-laundering ring that routed
drug profits through the banks to Colombian cocaine cartels.
   The United States has not yet formally filed papers seeking
Chinoy's extradition, but has 60 days to do so, officials said.
   At least 40 people have been arrested worldwide in connection
with the case. Indictments were returned in Tampa, New York,
Chicago, Detroit, Philadelphia and Houston, and warrants were
issued in Miami, Los Angeles, London and Paris.
</TEXT>
