<1ST_LINE>r f AM-JobDiscrimination     10-12 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Job Discrimination,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEOC Chief Criticizes GAO Report on Agency's Performance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clarence Thomas, chairman of the Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission, on Wednesday criticized a
General Accounting Office report that said the EEOC did not fully
investigate as many as 80 percent of job discrimination claims over
a three-month period last year.
   In a statement, Thomas said the report by GAO, an investigative
arm of Congress, ``trivializes civil rights enforcement to a level
commensurate with widget making. It's politically motivated, highly
misleading and deficient in several major regards.''
   Thomas criticized the GAO report for failing to note
improvements in EEOC's program and its successes in civil rights
enforcement; conducting a limited, overly mechanical study that
ignored the complexities of civil rights enforcement; and
recommending old ideas for improvement and disregarding initiatives
implemented by EEOC.
   ``EEOC's recent unprecedented success in comparison to the
agency's past record was virtually ignored by GAO in this report,''
said Thomas. ``We have investigated more charges, filed more
lawsuits and obtained more tangible benefits for victims of
unlawful discrimination than any previous commission.''
   He said the report's ``inaccurate and misleading findings impugn
the reputations of many career civil servants and undermine the
progress we have made as a civil rights enforcement agency.
   ``We have buttressed our strengths,'' Thomas said. ``We have
acknowledged our weaknesses and taken steps to correct them. Our
program is working.''
   In its report, released Tuesday by Rep. Augustus Hawkins,
D-Calif., chairman of the House Education and Labor Committee, GAO
said the stated policy of EEOC since 1983 has been to ``fully
investigate'' charges of violation of federal, state and local
anti-employment discrimination laws.
   GAO reviewed investigations of charges closed between January
through March 1987 in which no evidence of discrimination was
found. The investigators said 41 percent to 82 percent of the
charges closed by the six EEOC district offices and 40 percent to
87 percent of charges closed by five state agencies were not fully
investigated.
   Hawkins, who asked for the study, said: ``I find it outrageous
that there are people across the country who may have a legitimate
job discrimination claim denied because the EEOC mishandled the
case, didn't enforce the law and was more concerned with reducing
paperwork than with protecting claimants' civil rights.''
   Thomas said GAO acknowledged it has a lack of expertise in
evaluating evidence to determine whether discrimination had
occurred.
   ``GAO has a fundamental lack of understanding of the
investigatory and judicial principles of witness credibility,
evidence and burdens of proof inherent in civil rights
enforcement,'' he said. ``GAO refused to seek clarification of the
evaluation standards used by EEOC and ignored our attempts to
define those standards.
   ``A full investigation is that amount of investigation required
to make a sound determination on the merits of the charge,'' said
Thomas. ``It is nothing more and nothing less.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881012-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1855EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Money     10-12 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Money,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank Of England Scales Down Size Of British Banknotes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tourists will find it easier to tuck British
banknotes into their wallets in a few years as the present series
of large, unwieldy bills is replaced by smaller currency, the Bank
of England announced Wednesday.
   ``United Kingdom banknotes are quite, quite large
internationally,'' said a spokesman for England's central bank,
requesting anonymity. ``There seems some logic in reducing their
size so people can fit them into their wallets.''
   The bank's D-series notes, introduced in 1970, will be phased
out in gradual stages beginning with the introduction of a new
E-series 5-pound bill in 1990, which is the equivalent of $8.50,
and continuing with new 10-pound, 20-pound, and 50-pound bills
through 1994, the spokesman said. They are the equivalent of $17,
$34 and $85 respectively.
   The D-series notes will remain legal tender.
   Unlike the United States, where Federal Reserve notes are a
uniform size and color, British banknotes come in various
dimensions and hues.
   The blue 5-pound note, slightly larger than a U.S. dollar bill,
is dwarfed by the greenish 50-pound note, nearly the size of a page
from a paperback novel.
   The average reduction will be about 0.5 inches (or 1.27
centimeters) in length and width. The bills will remain different
sizes to help blind people distinguish between them, the spokesman
said.
   Britons carry more of the high-denomination notes than they used
to, the spokesman said. The most popular is the pink 10-pound note,
with 610 million in circulation.
   The Bank of England will save ``substantial'' paper costs by
reducing the size of the notes and producing them with advanced
printing technology, the spokesman said.
   Though final designs remain to be worked out, all the bills will
continue to feature a portrait of Queen Elizabeth II on the front
and a historical figure on the reverse, the spokesman said.
   The reductions in size for each bill are:
   Five-pound note, from 3 inches by 5.7 inches to 2.7 by 5.3
inches; 10-pound note, 3.34 inches by 5.94 inches to 2.95 inches by
5.6 inches; 20-pound note, 3.5 inches by 6.3 inches to 3.14 inches
by 5.86 inches; and 50-pound note, 3.7 inches by 6.65 inches to
3.34 inches by 6.14 inches.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
