<1ST_LINE>u f AM-HollyFarms     10-12 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Holly Farms,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Holly Farms Will Study Tyson's Takeover Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Farms Corp. said Wednesday it will
consider the nearly $900 million takeover offer from rival poultry
processor Tyson Foods Inc.
   Tyson, the nation's largest poultry processor, offered late
Tuesday to pay $45 in cash and a quarter share of its Class A
common stock for each of Holly Farms' 18.1 million outstanding
shares.
   In a brief statement Wednesday, Holly Farms said its board of
directors would study the offer. The company declined to offer any
other comment.
   ``I think Holly Farms will sell to Tyson only as a last
resort,'' said John M. McMillin, an analyst with the investment
firm Prudential-Bache Securities in New York.
   However, John Lawrence, an associate analyst at the investment
firm Morgan Keegan in Memphis, predicted a deal would be worked out
between the two poultry rivals.
   Holly Farms stock rose sharply in heavy trading, jumping $6.62{
a share to $49.62{ in composite New York Stock Exchange trading.
Tyson fell 62{ cents a share to $17 in over-the-counter trading.
   McMillin said he estimated Holly Farms was worth at least $55 a
share, or about $6 a share higher than Tyson offered. Lawrence put
Holly Farms' value at between $50 and $55 a share.
   McMillin said Holly Farms' managers could seek a higher bid from
a third party but he speculated they might try to buy the company
themselves in a leveraged buyout.
   A leveraged buyout is financed with debt that is repaid with the
target company's cash flow or sale of assets.
   ``There's a couple of options,'' McMillin said. ``One is to look
for a white knight, which could potentially be a Phillip Morris or
a Sara Lee ... look for a company to basically choose who they want
to get married to.
   ``The other is to pursue a management-led leveraged buyout, take
the company private. I think that's what they're pursuing right
now,'' he said.
   Several hours before Tyson disclosed its offer, Holly Farms had
announced it had been approached by an unidentified company
regarding a possible business combination. Holly Farms said no
specific proposal had been received and the company did not intend
to seek one.
   The company also said it had activated its ``poison pill''
takeover defense, which is designed to make a hostile takeover
prohibitively expensive.
   Bob Justice, a spokesman at Tyson's headquarters in Springdale,
Ark., said Wednesday that Tyson had not heard from Holly Farms
about the offer.
   ``We are just waiting on whatever decision they are making over
there. We are standing by,'' he said. ``We do have a timetable of
Oct. 19. That's our deadline. Hopefully, they can make a decision
prior to that. And we feel optimistic about a response before
that.''
   McMillin said a merger would increase Tyson's share of the
national poultry market from 18 percent to 28 percent.
   Tyson produces 14 million pounds of chicken meat each week from
an operation that includes hatcheries, feed mills, processing
plants and a sophisticated marketing arm. The company sells both
whole chickens and processed products to supermarkets, fast food
chains and institutional customers.
   Tyson had revenues of about $1.8 billion in its most recent
fiscal year, with an after-tax profit of $67 million. It has 25,600
employees.
   Holly Farms is a diversified foods company, with about 50
percent of its sales concentrated in chicken. The company also
mills flour and provides other meats for the food service industry.
   Holly Farms had sales of $1.6 billion last year and net income
of $36.2 million.
</TEXT>
