<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 1853EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Earns-CBS     10-12 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-CBS,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Posts Earnings Rise, Boosts Dividend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Inc. said Wednesday its third-quarter profit
climbed 16 percent, reflecting improved broadcasting results and a
hefty amount of interest earned on the money it has amassed from
asset sales.
   The company also said its board had boosted the quarterly
dividend by 47 percent, a move that some shareholders have been
pressing for in the wake of the recent sales of major assets such
as the magazine and records divisions.
   CBS said the dividend boost to $1.10 a share ``reconfirms our
confidence in CBS's future prospects and represents a tangible
sharing with our shareholders of our financial well-being.''
   But on the New York Stock Exchange, CBS fell 75 cents a share
Wednesday to $178.12{.
   For the three months ended Sept. 30, CBS said it earned $69.9
million, or $2.72 a share, compared with $60.1 million, or $2.31 a
share, a year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue rose 4 percent to $568.8 million from
$545.5 million a year earlier.
   The CBS Broadcasting Group posted an operating profit of $49
million, up 7 percent from $45.6 million a year earlier.
   Laurence A. Tisch, president and chief executive, sales and
profits were up at the CBS Television Network despite the
presidential election coverage and disruptions to the fall season
caused by the now-resolved writer's strike.
   Results for the company's television stations were mixed with
soft local advertising demand in some markets, the company said,
while the radio division had higher sales and profits.
   But a big contributor to the improved overall results was the
$44.5 million in net corporate interest income recorded for the
quarter. The company had a net interest expense of $2.3 million in
the quarter last year.
   For the first nine months of the year, CBS had a profit of $1.11
billion, or $43.16 a share, up more than fivefold from earnings of
$200.9 million, or $7.84 a share, a year earlier.
   Nine-month revenue edged up 1 percent to $2.01 billion from
$1.99 billion a year earlier.
   The nine-month results include an $866.6 million gain on the
sale of the CBS Records division to Sony Corp.
   The new dividend, up from 75 cents a share last quarter, is
payable Dec. 12 to shareholders of record Nov. 23.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
