<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 2108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Zenith-Brookhurst     10-12 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Zenith-Brookhurst,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Begins Soliciting Zenith Shareholder Votes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A battle for control of Zenith Electronics Corp.
officially began Wednesday when the company's largest shareholder
began soliciting shareholder consents for its plan to sell the
troubled company.
   Brookhurst Partners, a limited partnership formed by New York
investors Herbert B. Abelow and Nicholas L. Ihasz, mailed blank
consent forms to all Zenith shareholders along with a letter
outlining its proposals and urging shareholders to sign and return
the forms.
   If a majority of shareholders return signed forms by Dec. 4, the
Brookhurst proposals will take effect, just as if shareholders had
voted by proxy, Brookhurst said in a statement.
   Brookhurst wants to shrink Zenith's board of directors from 10
to six members and replace three of the remaining six with its own
nominees, who would be committed to a sale of the entire company.
   The dissident shareholders said shareholder value ``can be
maximized only through the sale of Zenith, and the election of our
nominees to the board of directors will best ensure that the sale
of the company is both actively pursued and fairly considered.''
   Brookhurst also is seeking a change in Zenith's bylaws to permit
shareholders owning at least 10 percent of the company's stock to
call a special meeting of shareholders. Brookhurst Partners owns
6.1 percent of Zenith, which is based in Glenview, north of Chicago.
   Officials of Zenith, the last U.S. television manufacturer, have
contended in a lawsuit that Brookhurst actually was seeking only to
drive up the price of Zenith's stock so it could sell its shares at
a profit. The company has asked the U.S. District Court in Chicago
to block the group's move.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
