<FILEID>AP-NR-10-12-88 2356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-FirstCity     10-12 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-First City,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First City Reports $23.6 Million Earnings for Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First City Bancorporation of Texas Inc., in its
first quarterly report since a $1.6 billion restructuring earlier
this year, on Wednesday announced a $23.6 million third-quarter
profit.
   Earnings for the three months ended Sept. 30 were in line with
the company's forecast of $98 million in net income for the first
12 months of operation, said A. Robert Abboud, First City's
chairman and chief executive officer.
   The forecast assumes gradually increasing earnings through the
period, Abboud said.
   The third-quarter earnings amount to 97 cents per share,
compared with net income of $17.2 million, or 70 cents per share,
for a shortened reporting period running from April 20 through June
30.
   First City was bailed out in April with $970 million in
assistance from the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., a spinoff of
$1.79 billion _ and possibly more _ in poorly performing assets and
a $500 million capital infusion from an investor group headed by
Abboud.
   The Houston-based bank holding company, with 62 banks in Texas
and one in South Dakota, grew quickly during the Texas oil boom,
but was hard hit by energy and real estate losses when oil prices
plummeted. First City also has branches in London, Singapore and
Nassau, and representative offices in Hong Kong and Tokyo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
